INSERT INTO `assignments` VALUES (1,80,'new assignment','<p>fgsfgfsg</p>','<p>fg</p>',12,0,NULL,'2014-10-17 14:33:13','2014-10-20 06:09:40'),(2,83,'assignment first','<p>good</p>','<p>good asginment</p>',2,0,NULL,'2014-10-20 06:02:28','2014-10-20 06:02:28'),(3,82,'dasd','<p>dfafd</p>','<p>dfdf</p>',12,1,NULL,'2014-10-20 06:56:30','2014-10-20 06:56:30'),(4,80,'sdaf','','',12,1,NULL,'2014-10-27 07:03:06','2014-10-27 07:03:06'),(5,86,'new asignment','','',4,1,NULL,'2014-11-12 06:23:49','2014-11-12 06:23:49'),(6,91,'Test Assignment','<p>Summary</p>','<p>Description</p>',4,3,NULL,'2014-12-05 05:53:28','2014-12-05 06:36:24'),(7,88,'test_new_course _assignment','<p>test_new_course _assignment</p>','<p>test_new_course _assignment</p>',6,0,NULL,'2014-12-10 08:44:11','2014-12-10 08:44:11'),(8,88,'test_new_course _assignment_2','<p>test_new_course _assignment_2</p>','<p>test_new_course _assignment_2</p>',8,1,NULL,'2014-12-10 08:44:32','2014-12-10 08:44:32'),(9,94,'first-assignment-study','<p>first-assignment-study</p>','<p>first-assignment-study</p>',4,0,NULL,'2014-12-12 08:09:39','2014-12-12 08:09:39'),(10,93,'FREE Lesson Assignment','','<p>Your turn to make a compelling image embodying as many of the characteristics discussed in this brief lesson - designed to show you just how the TCI online and interactive learning process works.&nbsp; Two examples is what I want to see and when you feel you\'ve captured two of your best, upload them to the TCI website for a <strong>FREE CRITIQUE</strong> of your work.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Have fun with your first TCI assignment!</strong></p>',14,0,NULL,'2014-12-26 13:20:16','2015-03-26 13:43:54'),(11,102,'Test Assignment','<p>sdsad</p>','<p>asdasdsadasdasdasdasdasdasdasd</p>',2,0,NULL,'2015-01-22 09:35:17','2015-02-05 06:47:07'),(12,103,'http://180.149.241.219/','<p>sacasc</p>','<p>ascscas</p>',30,1,NULL,'2015-01-23 08:45:58','2015-01-23 08:48:36'),(13,102,'picture of mount','','<p><strong><em>While lenses 50mm and longer are traditional choices for people shots, there\'s expressive power at the other end of the focal-length spectrum, as well.</em></strong></p>\r\n<p>Many of the first people photographs I ever took were made with a 50mm lens. From there, I moved in the telephoto direction like many a beginning photographer does. Those earliest stages of my work dealt with family and friends and shined with the signature-soft backgrounds characteristic of a 70-200 zoom, set to a wide aperture. Wide-angle lenses lay low on my priority list of equipment to buy. \"People-less\" landscapes weren&rsquo;t exactly my thing and I didn&rsquo;t shoot much in close-quarters back in those days either. It wasn&rsquo;t until years later that I purchased a 28mm prime to use for my first magazine assignment, just to feel \"professional,\" I guess. But at that point the tide had turned and \"wides\" had moved to a prominent position in my camera bag &ndash; especially when it came to photographing people in new and novel ways.</p>',3,2,NULL,'2015-02-05 06:46:18','2015-02-05 06:46:18'),(14,104,'Go North india','In this north india we are visit Taj mahal hawa mahal , Varanasi ghat','<h2 style=\"margin: 5px 0px; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-weight: bold; line-height: 36px; color: #333333; text-rendering: optimizelegibility; font-size: 26px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff;\" title=\"Historical Places in New Delhi\">Delhi</h2>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 10px; word-wrap: break-word; color: #333333; font-weight: normal; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff;\">Delhi has a rich history and thus has several historical monuments. Delhi was made the seat of power by many dynasties that have also constructed some magnificent monuments during their reign. Historical places worth seeing in Delhi are the Qutub Complex, Humayun\'s Tomb, Red Fort, Lodi Garden, Tughlaqabad etc.<br /><br /><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">{attachment1}</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 10px; word-wrap: break-word; color: #333333; font-weight: normal; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff;\">Qutub complex comprises of <strong style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Qutub Minar</strong>, Quwutawal Islam Mosque, Tomb of Illtutmish, Madrasa, Alai Darwaja and Alai Minar. This complex is one of the World Heritage Sites. The entire complex was constructed on the debris of 27 Jaina and Hindu temples. Qutub Minar was constructed by Qutubuddin Aibak in 1199 and was completed by Illtutmish in 13th century. It was built as muezzin for the mosque. It is 230 feet in height and tapers from 15 meter in diameter at the base to 2.5 meter at the top. It has 5 storeys each with a different design and a projecting balcony. The first three storeys are made only of sandstone while the fourth and fifth are made of sandstone and marble.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 10px; word-wrap: break-word; color: #333333; font-weight: normal; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff;\"><strong style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Humayun\'s Tomb</strong> is one of the historical sites in Delhi. The Persian wife of Humayun, Haji Begum, constructed it in 1565 AD. It is made of sandstone and marble. The tomb is built over a huge platform. It is situated in the middle of a garden, which is criss-crossed by channels of water. It is also a World Heritage Site. It is considered the precursor of Taj Mahal in Agra.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 10px; word-wrap: break-word; color: #333333; font-weight: normal; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff;\"><strong style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Red Fort</strong> is an important historical site belonging to the Mughal era. It was constructed by Shahjahan when he built the new city of Shahjahanabad. The main entrance opens in Chatta chowk, which was a covered shopping place for ladies popularly known as Meena Bazaar. Other attractions of this historical monument are Naubat Khana or Drum House, Diwan-i-Aam or the Hall of Public Audience, Diwan-i-Khas or Hall of Private Audience, the Hammams or Royal Bath and Rang Mahal or Palace of Colours housing the wives and mistresses of the emperor.<span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\"><br /><strong style=\"font-weight: bold;\"><br /></strong></span><strong style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Tughlaqabad</strong> is a historical place and the third city of Delhi. Ghiyasuddin Tughlaq founded Tughlaqabad in 1320. The city comprises of a fort and the tomb of Ghiyasuddin Tughlaq. The fort is famous for its defensive architectural features like slanting walls, ramparts, bastions, battlements, zigzag passageway etc. a causeway from the southern side of the fort takes across to the tomb of Ghiyasuddin, which was earlier surrounded by a lake. The tomb is in a private courtyard with fortified walls. You can see the historical places of Delhi on tours with Historical Places of India.<br /><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">{attachment2}</span><br /><strong>Agra</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 10px; word-wrap: break-word; color: #333333; font-weight: normal; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff;\">Agra has many historical places to offer to the tourists. Agra was the capital of the Lodis and later of the Mughals till Shahjahan shifted his capital to Shahjahanabad. The places of historical interests in Agra are Fatehpur Sikri, Red Fort, Sikandra, Tomb of Itmad-ud-daula and Taj Mahal. Fatehpur Sikri, Red Fort and Taj Mahal are the World Heritage Sites.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 10px; word-wrap: break-word; color: #333333; font-weight: normal; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff;\"><strong style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Taj Mahal</strong> is the most popular place amongst tourists. Shahjahan constructed it for his beloved wife Mumtaj from 1630 to 1653. It is made of pure white marble with beautiful inlay work of precious stones known as Pietra Dura. It<br /><br /><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">{attachment3}</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 10px; word-wrap: break-word; color: #333333; font-weight: normal; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff;\"><strong style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Fatehpur Sikri</strong> was built by Akbar between 1570 and 1586. It is made of red sandstone and in the vicinity of the dargah of Saint Salim Chisti and the mosque. The eastern entrance to the mosque is known as Bulund Darwaza, which was erected after the conquest of Gujarat. It is the highest gateway in India. The fort is famous for Diwan-I-Aam, Diwan-I-Khas and Panch Mahal. It was abandoned soon because of lack of water.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 10px; word-wrap: break-word; color: #333333; font-weight: normal; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff;\">Akbar started <strong style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Red Fort</strong> of Agra in 1565 as a military establishment of mud and bricks. Several additions were made by Jahangir and Shahjahan during their respective reigns. The fort is 2.5km long with 20ft high walls and a deep moat. The places of historical interest are Jahangir Mahal, Khas Mahal, Diwan-I-Khas and Diwan-I-Aam and Pearl Mosque.</p>\r\n<a style=\"outline: none !important; color: #0088cc; text-decoration: none; cursor: pointer; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: 26px; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff;\" name=\"varanasi\"></a>\r\n<h2 style=\"margin: 5px 0px; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-weight: bold; line-height: 36px; color: #333333; text-rendering: optimizelegibility; font-size: 26px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff;\" title=\"Historical Places in Varanasi India\">Varanasi</h2>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 10px; word-wrap: break-word; color: #333333; font-weight: normal; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff;\">Varanasi is 700km from Delhi and is situated on the bank of river Ganga. Varanasi has several well-built ghats. The historical places to visit in Varanasi are <strong style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Alamgir mosque, Durga temple, Vishwanath temple, Bharat Mata temple, Tulsi Manas temple, Banaras Hindu University</strong> and an Archaeological Museum. You can see the historical places of Varanasi with the tour of historical places of India.</p>\r\n<br style=\"color: #333333; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: 26px; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff;\" /><br style=\"color: #333333; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: 26px; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff;\" />Mathura\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 10px; word-wrap: break-word; color: #333333; font-weight: normal; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff;\">Mathura is 145km from Delhi in Uttar Pradesh.the places of historical interest in Mathura are <strong style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Gokul, Mahavan, Baldeo, Mat, Govardhan, Kusum Sarovar, Barsana and Nandgaon.</strong> Mathura is associated with the birth of lord Krishna and his childhood. There is an Archeological Museum in Mathura famous for Gandhara sculptures. You can see the historical places of Mathura with the tour of historical places of India.<br /><br /><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">{attachment3}</span><br /><span style=\"font-size: 14pt;\"><strong>Amritsar</strong></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 10px; word-wrap: break-word; color: #333333; font-weight: normal; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff;\">Amritsar is an ancient city and an important seat of Sikh religion, history and culture. There are many places of historical interest in Amritsar for tourists. The historical places in Amritsar are Golden Temple, Jalianwala Bagh and Summer Palace of Maharaja Ranjit Singh.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 10px; word-wrap: break-word; color: #333333; font-weight: normal; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff;\"><strong style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Golden Temple</strong> is a pilgrimage center for the Sikhs. It was made of white marble and inlaid copper work, which was covered by gold plate. That is why it is called Golden temple. It was started by 4th Sikh Guru Ram Dev and completed by his successor Guru Arjan Dev.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 10px; word-wrap: break-word; color: #333333; font-weight: normal; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff;\"><strong style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Jallianwala Bagh</strong> is famous for Martyr\'s Memorial in the memory of the people who died in an open firing by General Dyer on April13, 1919.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 10px; word-wrap: break-word; color: #333333; font-weight: normal; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff;\">Summer place of <strong style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Maharaja Ranjit Singh</strong> is situated amidst the garden called Ram Bagh. This garden is laid out on the pattern of Shalimar Bagh at Lahore. A museum named after Maharaja Ranjit Singh is setup here, which displays miniatures, coins, weapons and the replica of most famous diamond Kohinoor. You can see the historical places of Amritsar with the tour of historical places of India.</p>',5,0,NULL,'2015-02-05 12:14:22','2015-02-06 07:29:44'),(15,104,'GO south india','<span style=\"font-size: 14pt;\">This trip for south indai this is incredival india and historical place</span>','<h2 style=\"font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-stretch: normal; font-size: 18px; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; color: #611674; line-height: 1em; text-align: left; border-left-width: 3px; border-left-color: #ff6600; border-left-style: solid; margin: 5px; padding: 5px; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff;\">Group of Monuments at Mahabalipuram</h2>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 10pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt;\"><span style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 13px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: 19.5px; orphans: auto; text-align: justify; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; display: inline !important; float: none; background-color: #ffffff;\">Mahabalipuram, being one of the UNESCO World heritage site was developed during the Pallava king Narashimha Varman I, who was also called by his people as &ldquo;the great wrestler&rdquo;. A traveler can spot the rock cut caves, monolithic shrines, structural temples and huge bas-reliefs which depicts the master piece of the Pallava art. Visit the shore temple built by Mamalla dedicated to Lord Vishnu while the other two shrines of Lord Shiva was added by Mamalla&rsquo;s successor Narashimha Varman II.</span><br /><br />{attachment1}<br /></span></span>\r\n<h2 style=\"font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-stretch: normal; font-size: 18px; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; color: #611674; line-height: 1em; text-align: left; border-left-width: 3px; border-left-color: #ff6600; border-left-style: solid; margin: 5px; padding: 5px; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff;\">Gangaikondacholapuram &amp; Darasuram</h2>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 10pt;\"><span style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 13px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: 19.5px; orphans: auto; text-align: justify; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; display: inline !important; float: none; background-color: #ffffff;\">Gangaikondacholapuram and Darasuram, which is actually a temple undertaken and maintained by the </span><strong style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 13px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: 19.5px; orphans: auto; text-align: justify; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff;\">UNESCO</strong><span style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 13px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: 19.5px; orphans: auto; text-align: justify; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; display: inline !important; float: none; background-color: #ffffff;\">world heritage team. </span><strong style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 13px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: 19.5px; orphans: auto; text-align: justify; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff;\">&ldquo;The city of Chola who took the Ganges&rdquo;</strong><span style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 13px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: 19.5px; orphans: auto; text-align: justify; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; display: inline !important; float: none; background-color: #ffffff;\"> is the meaning of the name of this place. Brihadeeshvara temple in Gangaikondacholapuram, a replica of Tanjore&rsquo;s </span><strong style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 13px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: 19.5px; orphans: auto; text-align: justify; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff;\">Brihadeeshvara temple</strong><span style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 13px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: 19.5px; orphans: auto; text-align: justify; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; display: inline !important; float: none; background-color: #ffffff;\">, the towered sanctum of this granite Shiva temple is shorter than the one at Tanjore. Airavateshwara temple at Darasuram is an excellent example for architectural marvel and one of the oldest temples. The sculpture of the temple depicts the incidents of Chola period.</span><br /><br />{attachment2}<br /><br /></span>',2,5,NULL,'2015-02-05 12:25:17','2015-02-05 12:29:05'),(16,113,'Creating with Lenses and Perspectives','','<p>Using different viewpoints, unusual angles of view, frames, leading lines and other ideas discussed here, create 6 engaging travel scenes. Try to have them tell a bit about the place you are photographing at the same time.<br /><br /></p>',7,0,NULL,'2015-02-07 15:56:30','2015-02-23 17:19:45'),(17,114,'Storytelling Environmental and Up-Close Portraits','','<p>I want to see portraits of people you don\'t know (honor system applies here). I want to see the local flower vendor, or musicians, artists, truck drivers, moms, dads, or children. I don\'t care who you choose to photograph, I just want you to have some fun photographing people you\'ve never met before!</p>\r\n<p>Show me some environmental portraits, and some head-and-shoulder portraits or close-in portraits. Upload your 6 strongest images for critique and comments.</p>',17,0,NULL,'2015-02-07 15:59:53','2015-02-23 17:21:58'),(18,115,'Capturing Moments of Daily life, Festivals and Rituals','','<p>Go out and explore your town, a park, a market or festival. Make images that are truly candid. Push yourself to try and do it without using a telephoto lens. If you can, work within the 24mm-80mm range. Watch for gestures that tell the story of what\'s going on in the scene. Remember to think about a good composition while capturing the moment, too, and make the most interesting pictures you can while capturing the &ldquo;moment.&rdquo;&nbsp; Upload your 3 most dynamic captures.</p>',17,0,NULL,'2015-02-07 16:08:48','2015-02-23 17:23:29'),(19,116,'Framing with a Sense of Design','','<p>Find situations where you can use the elements of design to enhance your composition; look for lines, patterns, shapes, and textures. Upload 6 of your very best images from this assignment.</p>',17,0,NULL,'2015-02-07 16:10:58','2015-02-23 17:25:04'),(20,117,'Stunning Photos Whatever the Light','','<p>I want to see personal interpretations of things you see. The only thing I ask it to not go too heavy into the post processing. Try to create strong images that have a personal interpretation in-camera first, and then if you do post-process, keep them reasonably true to the scene while adding your own artistic touch.<br /><br />Please upload 6 of your very best images.</p>',16,0,NULL,'2015-02-07 16:22:19','2015-02-23 17:26:22'),(21,118,'Travel Photos that Speak Your Voice','','<p>I want to see personal interpretations of things you see. The only thing I ask it to not go too heavy into the post processing. Try to create strong images that have a personal interpretation in-camera first, and then if you do post-process, keep them reasonably true to the scene while adding your own artistic touch.<br /><br />Please upload 6 of your very best images.</p>',16,0,NULL,'2015-02-07 16:25:20','2015-02-23 17:27:34'),(22,119,'Stories with Interest and Impact / An Insider\'s View','','<p>Now it is your turn. I want you to explore with your camera, near or not so near to your home (your choice) to produce a visual \"sketchpad\" for a distinct story idea. Remember to choose a story that will fit the four criteria we\'ve outlined above, only touching for now on the questions (in any order) of - who, what, when, where, why and how. Then, <strong>write a brief synopsis (approximately 150 - 200 words</strong> and don\'t get hung up on the writing skills part) of your proposed story. Upload to the TCI site, <strong>ten images</strong> that exemplify just what your story will be about. Remember, as a general rule you\'ll always do your best work when photographing something you feel most passionate about.</p>\r\n<p>That\'s it - best of luck with this first assignment! And once again - glad to have you on board!</p>',60,0,NULL,'2015-02-19 16:53:14','2015-05-07 08:19:38'),(23,120,'Shooting in \"Other Cultures\" / Photographing in Personal Space','','<p>Find an \"other culture\" that you feel comfortable working in. Examples: a center of religion in your community, a day-care center for pre-school children in your neighborhood, an ethnic family on your block - any of these constitute situations with which you are probably, to some degree, unfamiliar. Begin by approaching the situation and establishing rapport with its members - its key players. Explore the situation until you can identify its component parts and actors. Learn your story from the bottom up! Remember - the images that appear in your final work will be only the \"tip of the iceberg,\" in a very real sense. If you don\'t have a full grasp of your story, you can\'t tell it journalistically - who, what, when, where, why and sometimes how -are what we\'re looking for. You should strive to create a work that is a blend of creative style (your own vision as a photographer) and content (the \"meat\" of the matter).</p>\r\n<p>OK! So submit to me (\"file\" to your editor) 6 to 8 images telling the story of this \"other culture\" you have encountered and come to understand. This week\'s assignment may focus on your story topic for this course, but it does not need to. It can be something totally different.</p>\r\n<p>Have fun and remember that you can always email me if you get stuck, don\'t understand fully what I\'m asking you to do, or just plain feel frustrated with your progress.</p>',120,0,NULL,'2015-02-20 14:38:08','2015-05-07 08:21:19'),(24,126,'Wide to Ultra Wide','','<p>Your first assignment has three parts, all of which I would like you to invest an adequate amount of time in.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Part 1:</strong> Using a single wide-angle focal-length, I want you to practice photographing a stationary object, in less than the brightest sunlight. \"Open shade\", such as that found beneath a tree or awning on a sunny day, works best for this exercise. Then, setting an adequate exposure (right combination of aperture and a slow shutter speed) each time, practice photographing your subject - hand-held - at 1/15 sec., 1/8 sec. and 1/4 sec. If you\'re still not satisfied with the picture sharpness you receive, try using the \"TIP\" outlined below. Once you are satisfied with your results, upload your best photograph made at each shutter speed setting (three photos) to the TCI website. And, please be sure to label each of these shots.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Part 2:</strong> Choose a subject - animate or inanimate - in good light and photograph it with a single focal-length lens (If you\'re using a zoom, place it on a specific focal-length setting and leave it there.). Move your viewfinder over the scene until you intuitively feel that the design/composition is right. (Note: One thing to keep in mind about wide-angle lenses is that there are no hard-and-fast \"rules\" regarding their use. The door is wide open to your creative instincts). Make a number of photographs in this way and then move closer to take the same picture again. Upload your best near-far combination of the same subject (compositional center-of-interest) - two photographs in all to the TCI site for critique. Please be sure to indicate at which aperture and shutter speed these photos were made.</p>\r\n<p><br /><strong>Part 3:</strong> Select an inanimate object - building or object - as your subject. In good light, photograph this center of interest using an expansive depth-of-field (i.e. f8 or greater) and differing angles from the horizontal plane. Upload your favorite two shots from this take for critique. Again, please include the exposure data that accompanies this photo.</p>\r\n<p>So - in total you\'ll be uploading seven images to the TCI website for instructor critique. Best of luck with this first lesson assignment!</p>\r\n<p><br /><em><strong>TIP: For a solid grip on your camera, start by running your hand once or twice through the strap. That way, if you should slip, etc. you\'ll still have a firm grasp on your valuable piece of equipment. Secondly, while holding the camera securely in your right hand (if you\'re right-handed), place your left hand out in front of you, palm up. \"Plop\" the camera directly down on top of it and pull the viewfinder snug to your eye. Next, draw both of your elbows snug to your sides. Short of stretching out a tripod, this \"3-point\" stance (i.e. elbows firmly to the sides and viewfinder snug against your forehead) will help you to achieve steady exposures at almost any shutter speed and with a wide variety of lenses. Last touch is to place your feet at shoulder width - now you\'re set!<br /></strong></em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',7,0,NULL,'2015-02-23 07:40:45','2015-02-23 08:05:44'),(25,127,'Establishing Strong Foregrounds','','<p>There are three parts to this week\'s assignment representing eight images in total to be uploaded to the TCI site for critique.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Part 1:</strong> The key to compositional success in wide-angle photography, is the effective establishment of strong and immediate foreground interest. For this assignment, I want you to begin by doing just that. Practice placing both animate and inanimate subjects in this compositional space and upload your two best images with a person in the foreground and your two best featuring an object or animal in the immediate foreground of the frame - four photos in all.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Part 2:</strong> If you have a focusing scale on the barrel of your lens, set it at 3 meters (approx. 10 feet) and leave it there. If you must, hold this position with a piece of cloth tape attached to the lens. If you have not such an adjustment on your lens (the majority of AF lenses these days don\'t), set the lens to \"manual\" and focus on something you know to be at this distance from the camera. Then, securing this adjustment set an aperture of between f8 to f16 (with a correspondingly appropriate shutter speed for adequate exposure). Now you\'re ready to just \"pull-up-and-shoot\" when photographing within this distance range. Practice this quick-fire shooting method with family, friends and objects and upload your two best images demonstrating your new-found proficiency with this technique. For best results, be sure to practice it out-of-doors in good daylight.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Part 3:</strong> As a final segment to this assignment, I would like you to combine what you have learned and practiced above with your own creativity. The goal here is to move beyond using a wide-angle lens to just \"fit things in\". When you feel you\'re there, upload your two most intriguing compositions to the TCI site for critique.</p>\r\n<p>Best of luck with all of this!</p>',18,0,NULL,'2015-02-23 13:14:50','2015-03-03 10:49:15'),(26,128,'Thinking Full Frame','','<p><strong>Part 1:</strong> Practice filling the frame completely with your subject, as well as making photographs that \"break\" the frame. When you feel you\'ve got a grasp of these two wide-angle modes of shooting, select two of your best images from each of these two categories (four photographs total) and upload them to the TCI site for critique.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Part 2 (a):</strong> Find a scene and a center-of-interest, therein, that interests you and take a few of your best shots.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>(b):</strong> Then take a moment to study this same scene more carefully through the viewfinder to determine whether all elements within the frame support the main subject, as well fit to one another in a \"logical\" manner (i.e. checking for \"visual integrity\" within the frame). If this is not the case, do what you must (e.g. change camera position, etc.) to make this so. Upload your best single example made during the general scene shoot (a) and then your \"logical\" reassessment of this scene for (b) - two images total.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Part 3:</strong> Explore what we\'ve described to be \"layering\" (strong foreground and a definable middle-ground and background to the horizon) in a wide-angle composition containing a high degree of sharpness throughout (i.e. great depth-of-field resulting from the use of an aperture setting of f8 - f22). Note: Try using a tripod for greater success and effect with this part of the assignment. Go through your work and send your two most impressive examples of layers for critique.<br />Eight photographs total for Assignment #3.</p>',18,0,NULL,'2015-02-23 13:17:55','2015-03-03 10:50:02'),(27,129,'Wide as Standard Lens','','<p>Now, using all the approaches and techniques discussed for wide-angle lenses in this course, I want you to photograph and upload eight of the most powerful photographs you\'ve ever made with a 35mm camera. That\'s your challenge. Have fun successfully meeting it!</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',17,0,NULL,'2015-02-23 13:19:43','2015-03-03 10:53:42'),(28,130,'Photo Fundamentals for food photography','','<p>I have added 2 exercises to this assignment for those students who are beginners or are shooting in either auto or aperture priority mode. The aim of these exercises is to offer you a platform to practice the different topics we have discussed in this lesson and to make you confident enough to move to Manual Mode.</p>\r\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> If you are a beginner I&rsquo;d like you to complete all three exercises mentioned here. Those of you who are already shooting in Manual mode and understand the concept of using each of the elements together may, if you like, skip exercise one and two and concentrate on the main assignment. Of course, you can do the exercises just for practice too.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Exercise 1:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Practice makes perfect! I want you to set your camera on Aperture Priority mode. Create a very simple set up, like the photograph of the pear or of the set-up with the milk bottle in the background, eggs or egg shells etc. in the foreground. Make sure your subject is placed on a table or countertop near a window so that you have enough light to light the set-up.</p>\r\n<p>Mount the camera on your tripod.</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Set your aperture to the smallest value possible (this will vary depending on the lens you are using) and select the focus point in your frame. Take a few images with this aperture value.</li>\r\n<li>Without moving the set-up change your aperture value to a medium f/stop (f/5, f/6.3 etc.) and take a few shots.</li>\r\n<li>Finally, crank up your aperture as far as you can (f/18, f/22).</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>Note down the values your camera is giving for the exposure for each of the images you take.</p>\r\n<p>What I want to see in this exercise is <strong>3 examples</strong>, one from each category (1, 2 and 3). Share the details of each image: f/stop you chose, the exposure the camera used, the time of day and how much or little light you had for the particular image. Also share your thoughts on the difference you see in each image.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Exercise 2</strong></p>\r\n<p>Once again create a very simple set-up (if you are doing this on a different day). Still in Aperture Priority Mode follow the steps in Exercise 1 but here I want you to add an additional step between each category. After you have taken a shot with a small aperture in Aperture Priority Mode and noted what value your camera chose for the shutter speed, I want you to switch to Manual mode. Leave the aperture setting as it is and now you select the shutter speed value using the value from the previous shot as a basis. Continue for each of the other two categories in the same procedure.</p>\r\n<p>Do you see and understand what is happening? It looks like you might be ready for the Manual Mode!! Keep practicing!</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><strong>Assignment</strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Now that you are in Manual Mode here is the main part of this assignment.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Study the image of the bowl of quinoa and fruit from the lesson. I&rsquo;d like you to create a set-up that is similar to this image.</span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\"> A bowl with something in it (a soup, a salad, muesli, granola etc.). This will be your main subject. Make sure you do not change this in the set-up during the course of the assignment.<strong> <br /></strong></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Use a few additional pieces of props around the main subject.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>You have to take three different photographs of the subject in this set-up.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Photo 1:</strong> Should be a tighter shot of the subject with it in main focus so that viewers can instantly direct their eyes on the subject. Move in closer and use as shallow depth of field as possible.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Photo 2:</strong> Should have your subject still in the main focus but it is now part of an environment. Use the appropriate DoF to show this. I would like to see a little more depth and more of the surrounding.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Photo 3:</strong> I want you to tell the entire story of the subject. It is one of the main items in the set-up. How would you change the depth of field to represent this?</p>\r\n<p>Also share all the details of each image when you upload the images (lens, focal length, aperture, shutter speed etc.)</p>',7,0,NULL,'2015-02-24 16:55:28','2015-04-14 13:01:38'),(29,131,'Harnessing Natural Light for Food Images','','<p>Now I want you to harness the natural light around your home / studio. First, as I mentioned identify where in your home or studios you have the best light. Remember it is not necessary to have direct sunlight pouring through the windows. Indirect light works well; you just need a good amount of it.</p>\r\n<p>From now on you should make room in this area for all your food images for the rest of the course. Place a small table in this area and all the equipment you need and if possible leave it here.</p>\r\n<p>As in the previous lesson I am dividing this into 2 practice exercises and then the main assignment. The purpose of the exercises is to guide you step by step through each routine and get you familiar with how to use and hone different natural light situations. Each exercise requires you to upload 2 images and for the final image in the assignment I am allowing you to select one of the options I propose. Don&rsquo;t forget to share the details of each image and discuss your lighting situation, direction, intensity, color of your light.</p>\r\n<p>Have fun!</p>\r\n<p><strong>Exercise 1: Angle of Light &ndash; Upload 2 images</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>a. </strong>Select your subject. You can use anything you like, a simple coffee cake (store bought), bread, muffins, ingredients (pasta, garlic, cheese) etc. You can also study one of the images in the lesson to create a similar set-up. Set-up your subject using a few props; like some cutlery or a plate on your table or countertop.Set up your food subject in a way that the source of light is coming from either 2-3 o&rsquo;clock or 9-10 o&rsquo;clock. Take several shots at different times of the day (morning, midday, afternoon). Compare the photos and observe how the different times of the day effects the image in terms of color, intensity, and quality.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>b. </strong>Now I&rsquo;d like you to move the set-up so that your subject is getting backlight &ndash; your light source is placed at 12 o&rsquo;clock. Take several shots at different times of the day (morning, midday, afternoon). Compare the photos and observe how the different times of the day effects the image in terms of color, intensity, and quality.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Also compare the images in both categories (a and b) and note how the different position of the light creates totally different moods and atmospheres. <br /><br />Select 2 of your best images (one from each category) and upload them here.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Exercise 2: Lighting Equipment &ndash; Upload 2 images Requirements:</strong></p>\r\n<p><em>Reflector &ndash;</em> if you do not have a reflector you can easily use a large piece of white card or white foam board.</p>\r\n<p><em>Diffuser &ndash;</em> if you do not have a diffuser you can use tracing paper to cover up the window, or light translucent white fabric.</p>\r\n<p>As above select your subject using anything you like, a simple coffee cake (store bought), bread, muffins, ingredients (pasta, garlic, cheese) etc. You can also study one of the images in the lesson to create a similar set-up. Set-up your subject using a few props; like some cutlery or a plate on your table or countertop.</p>\r\n<p>Place your subject with the source of light coming from the side. Take a few photographs of your subject as it is.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>a. </strong>Start with the reflector and place this directly opposite to the direction of light and see how the shadows change. Take a few photographs.  Next, move the reflector so that instead of being directly opposite the light source it is at an angle. Take a few photographs. The angles can be changed horizontally or vertically. You will notice that every time you change the angle of the reflector the shadows change. What we want in this image is to minimize any dark patches and shadows.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>b. </strong>Using a diffuser instead of a reflector go through the process indicated in category a). Keep in mind that a diffuser is placed between the light source and the food. If you do not have a diffuser and are using tracing paper or fabric, cover the windows with this as required. What we want here is soft diffused light and to remove any harsh beams of light that fall in the frame.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Select and upload 2 of your best photographs (one from each category).</p>\r\n<p><strong>Assignment - Upload 1 image</strong><br />Your subject for this assignment is a cake or bread. It can be any kind of simple cake or bread you can find or bake (a gugelhopf, coffee cake, baguette, ciabatta etc.). For this assignment I want you to combine all your knowledge from our lesson in light and produce one image. I want you to consider everything about the direction color, quality and intensity of light using the equipment and techniques from the lesson and exercise.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>a. </strong>A moody, dark and atmospheric shot. Use the drama of shadows and light reflection to paint your image.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>b. </strong>A soft, very diffused but bright shot. This shot should have minimal shadows, just enough to create movement in the image and raise the viewer&rsquo;s interest. Harness the light so that there are no harsh rays of light in the image and it has an even balanced light.</li>\r\n</ul>',0,0,NULL,'2015-02-24 16:58:55','2015-04-24 08:26:54'),(30,132,'Get the Look: Color and Texture','','<p>Now I want you to start painting your canvas with colors and creating textures to give the image a real feel. <br /><br />For this assignment I am looking for 2 of your best images.  The subject for both images is soup with a dominant color (e.g. tomato or pumpkin soup).</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>1)</strong> For the first image use the color wheel or my Pinterest board to find a <strong>complimentary color scheme</strong>. Place an item or prop with that complimentary color/s into the scene. This can be a napkin or other ingredients. Now think about adding texture and layers to your soup and the scene and observe how the light hits the individual items. Use what we discussed and practiced in lessons 1 and 2 to create the appropriate depth of field and pay attention to the lighting.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>2) </strong>For the second image I&rsquo;d like you to play around with <strong>contrasting colors</strong>. This might be a little challenging at first but take time to study various images that show how contrasting colors are used. Also look at the color wheel to guide you to choose the appropriate color. Here too I would like you to work with layers to build height and add texture to the dish. Use what we discussed and practiced in lessons 1 and 2 to create the appropriate depth of field and pay attention to the lighting.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Have fun coloring your images!</p>',0,0,NULL,'2015-02-24 17:43:10','2015-04-24 08:27:28'),(31,133,'Setup, Styling and Perfect Focus','','<p>Now I&rsquo;d like you to find the perfect point of focus in your image. <br /><br />Study the image of the breakfast scene in the lesson. I would like you to create your breakfast scene using a few items placed at different strategic points in the frame. Think about the rule of the thirds to aid you. As you are composing the set-up think about where you will place your point of focus. Take a step back and ask yourself &ldquo;What part of the set-up are my eyes drawn to first!&rdquo;<br /><br />Use this point as your initial focus point and take a few images. Once you are happy with it I&rsquo;d like you to move the set-up around and find another placement. Once again look for the point of focus with this placement and once again take a few shots. <br /><br />I&rsquo;d like you to upload 2 of your best images (1 for each placement), sharing your process, any difficulties you experienced and how you mastered them. <br /><br />Ready? Set &hellip; focus! Have fun!</p>',17,0,NULL,'2015-02-24 17:47:33','2015-02-24 17:47:33'),(32,134,'Angles, Placement and Composition','','<p>Now it&rsquo;s your turn to compose your scene using the techniques we have just discussed.<br /><br /></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>1. </strong>Cook up some food, plate it and begin setting up your scene so that the main dish is off-center. Take a few shots, then move things around to place the main dish in the center and placing the other items around it. Take a few shots.     </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Study the images and upload 2 (1 off-center and 1 centered) of your best ones here.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>2. </strong>Next photograph the same set-up from the three different perspectives : overheand, three-quarters and eye-level. Feel free to move the food and other items around to get the balance in your frame. Pay attention to how the background changes as you change positions and observe carefully if anything needs adjusting.  </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Upload 3 images to show one image from each perspective.</p>\r\n<p>Have fun!</p>',16,0,NULL,'2015-02-24 17:52:44','2015-02-24 17:53:19'),(33,135,'Props and Go for it!','','<p>As this is your final lesson for the course I am making this a major assignment and I would like you to integrate and use all that we have learnt in the past lessons for this final assignment.</p>\r\n<p>I am the Creative Director for a popular food magazine and you have just been commissioned to photograph a three page feature for this magazine.</p>\r\n<p>Please select one of the following magazines:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Donna Hay</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Jamie</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Saveur</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Gourmet</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Delicious</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>The title of the feature is &ldquo;<strong>From Farm to Table</strong>&rdquo; and you need to submit 3 images for this feature. All your images must represent the style and the look of the magazine you have selected, so make sure you take some time to research the photographs in the magazine your have selected.</p>\r\n<p>Your guidelines for the images:</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 1.&nbsp; Location shoot: at your Farmer&rsquo;s Market &ndash; select a vendor, artisan producer or a unique product. I&rsquo;d like a shot that captures the essence of the market integrating the vendor, artisan producer or their product.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2.&nbsp; Ingredient shot: whether you choose to portray the image of the ingredient at the market or back in your studio/home in a more styled scene is your choice but I would like a close up of the image set in a scene. The scene for example could be the ingredient in a basket along with other produce and items, on a chopping board etc. I&rsquo;d like you think about the story you want to tell for the magazine feature and shoot accordingly.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 3.&nbsp; Cooked dish: I&rsquo;d like you to cook up / bake a dish with the ingredient from the market. The dish should be portrayed in a styled scene corresponding to your story. Use props wisely and think about placement and composition. The photograph can be of the dish alone, or of a person holding the dish or of the table setting where the dish makes up the center of the image. This will be the cover image for the magazine.</p>\r\n<p>Upload your images here and I would also like to hear the story that you have created for the feature and the images.</p>\r\n<p>Think about everything we have discussed in the past few lessons and apply them here in these 3 images. Be creative, be inspired and give me your best images.</p>',16,0,NULL,'2015-02-24 17:54:46','2015-02-24 17:57:10'),(34,98,'Using Shorter Lenses','','<p>Enlist family members and friends and use whichever wide-angle lenses are available to you to practice the techniques and approaches discussed above. Then once you\'ve got a good feel for it all, upload your best from the following image categories to the TCI for critique and comment (10 pictures total):</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>2 images (one vertical, one horizontal) in which the subject(s) fill the frame in its entirety.</li>\r\n<li>2 people photos that demonstrate internal \"logic\" throughout (one with softly-focused background to focus interest on a sharply-focused foreground subject; one that is sharply focused throughout, demonstrating the strength of subject-background relationship).</li>\r\n<li>2 photos (horizontal format) in which the juxtaposition of human and non-human elements elicits a particular feeling or message (and please identify in a word or phrase exactly what this is) for the viewer (e.g. as with my \"sinister\" poster image from India above).</li>\r\n<li>2 pictures in which a person (or persons) combine with a graphic background to heighten visual \"tension\" and \"energy\" within the frame.</li>\r\n<li>2 images that intentionally distort perspective to emphasize a feeling or feature (and, describe in a word or phrase your exact \"intent\"). Best of luck with this assignment! And remember - experimentation is the way to learn.</li>\r\n</ul>',7,0,NULL,'2015-02-26 10:16:33','2015-02-26 10:19:53'),(35,99,'Approaching Strangers','','<p>Where are you on the comfort-level scale when it comes to photographing people? Begin where you think you are and upload 3 of your best photos made in just these situations. Then \"raise the bar\" a notch to where your comfort zone, when photographing people, feels a bit challenged. Make a series of photographs here and upload an additional 3 images you\'re most proud of from this collection. Have fun with this assignment - enjoying as much the interaction with newly-met people as you do photographing them. Six strong images in total.</p>',18,0,NULL,'2015-02-26 10:19:22','2015-02-26 10:19:22'),(36,100,'Making the Best of Light and Perspective','','<p>For this week\'s assignment, I want you to pay particular attention to the strength, quality and direction of light you use to make photographs of people. Enlist family, friends and/or strangers to practice composing the types of pictures discussed above. Once satisfied with your results, upload images in the following categories and numbers to the TCI site for critique:</p>\r\n<p><strong>3 </strong>Images in which harsh sunlight is used to photograph a person or persons in a creative and effective way.<br /><strong>3</strong> indoor photos where light from a window is combined with some type of reflected light to create a \"uniformly-lit\" and natural looking portrait.<br /><strong>3</strong> images in which features other than facial are used to describe the person being photographed.</p>\r\n<p><strong>9</strong> photos total - have fun with this assignment!</p>',18,0,NULL,'2015-02-26 10:21:33','2015-02-26 10:21:33'),(37,101,'Seeing Photos Within Photos','','<p>Now it\'s your turn to dive into the \"sea\" of humanity. Find a comfortable place where crowds gather. This venue could be a busy cafe scene, a bus-stop at rush hour, a carnival situation, festival, party or a busy marketplace or bazaar. Find your most current \"comfort zone\" and put to practice all that you\'ve learned in this course. Once you\'ve got your creativity flowing and you feel confident with the material you\'ve captured, upload the following images to the TCI site for critique and review. Remember, too, that your people photographs need not always include faces to be expressive and defining. As in Example 8 above, other human features can be equally telling of a person and the life he or she leads. Push yourself with this this last one and have fun with this assignment.</p>\r\n<p>Upload:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>2 Photos: Choose a well-peopled situation and roam around through it, capturing as you move what you feel are \"defining\" people photographs.</li>\r\n<li>2 Images: Be an \"opportunist\" and locate yourself at a place of action / occurrence to capture people as they arrive / pass by. Note: This works best when you set the exposure you want beforehand, focus on the area where your subject is intended to be and then all you\'ve got to do is squeeze the shutter when the right moment - in this spot and lighting situation - arrives.</li>\r\n<li>3 Photos: Upload one image of the overall crowed scene that you are about to enter. Then move in to capture 2 \"telling\" isolated shots of one interesting person or the interaction of two.</li>\r\n<li>1 Photo: File to the TCI site the best of your \"creative\" (using slow shutter speed setting) takes on a crowd of people.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Upload 8 photographs total for this final assignment. Good luck!</p>',17,0,NULL,'2015-02-26 10:24:23','2015-02-26 10:24:23'),(38,136,'Elements of Visual Art & Design / Principles of Art','','<p>For this first assignment I want you to choose 6 of your own images - 3 that you really like and 3 that didn&rsquo;t quite turn out the way you were hoping they would. Do not re-edit or re-crop based on what we covered here. I want to see your work as it exists before this class.&nbsp; Write briefly about these 6 images in terms of what we covered in this first lesson. Why do you think they were more or less successful? Note: When submitting your images, be sure to specify images as &ldquo;successes&rdquo; or &ldquo;attempts&rdquo; so that I know where you&rsquo;re coming from (perhaps a filename such as &ldquo;yournamesuccess1&rdquo; / &ldquo;yournameattempt1&rdquo;).</p>\r\n<p>Looking forward to seeing your first work!</p>',7,0,NULL,'2015-03-11 17:26:43','2015-03-11 18:38:36'),(39,137,'Rules of Composition (Part 1 of 2)','','<p><strong>Part 1:</strong> Think of some photographers whose work you admire. Review some of their images, keeping the first 15 rules from this lesson in the back of your mind. What rules are they following? What rules are they breaking? Pick two images to share with me and quickly summarize how the photographer is following or breaking the rules. Keep in mind that they could be following some rules and breaking others.<br /><br /><strong>Part 2:</strong> Review these first 15 rules before you go out to do some shooting. Write or print the rules on a piece of paper (or put them in your phone) so that you have a little cheat sheet to look at while you&rsquo;re out. Spend a couple hours shooting images that incorporate the rules we discussed. Experiment with following the rules, breaking them, and combining more than one rule in an image.<br /><br />Come back with <strong>5 images</strong> you feel are good examples of these rules in action. Briefly write about what you like about each image and your thought process while composing.</p>',18,0,NULL,'2015-03-11 17:28:46','2015-03-11 19:00:34'),(40,138,'Rules of Composition (Part 2 of 2)','','<p><strong>Part 1:</strong> Scour through historical images and find 3 good examples of photographs that have withstood the test of time. Share them here and tell me why they are still successful images to this day. Keep in mind that photos can be dated to a certain period and show signs of the times, but also withstand the test of time in the sense that they are still powerful images to this day.<br /><br /><strong>Part 2:</strong> Review all 23 rules and tips before you go out to do some shooting. Write or print the rules on a piece of paper (or put them in your phone) so that you have a little cheat sheet to look at while you&rsquo;re out. Spend a couple hours shooting images that incorporate the rules we discussed. Experiment with following the rules, breaking them, and combining more than one rule in an image.</p>\r\n<p>Like in the last lesson, come back with 5 images you feel are good examples of these rules in action. Briefly write about what you like about each image and your thought process while composing.<br /><br /><strong>Part 3:</strong> Submit your favorite shot before and after editing. Never go overboard on the processing (that could be a whole separate class), but show me some of the processing you&rsquo;re doing. I&rsquo;m particularly interested in seeing how you&rsquo;ve decided to crop/straighten/clean up images. Remember that the before/after doesn&rsquo;t have to be drastic.</p>',18,0,NULL,'2015-03-11 17:32:03','2015-03-11 19:03:03'),(41,139,'Evoking Mood & Emotion, Finding Inspiration','','<p><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><strong>Part 1:</strong><br /><br />Again, I want you to look through the work of photographers you admire and find 2 examples of how they used some of the elements mentioned in this lesson to convey mood and emotion in their image. Analyze the images and explain what it was that they did or included to give the images that special quality that might be hard to describe.<br /><br /><strong>Part 2: Gesture</strong><br /></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Submit 2 sets of before/after images (4 images total) of your own work. Image 1 should be a normal image and Image 2 should be an image where some gesture or movement is added to tell more of a story in the image. Compare and contrast the two images AND tell me how and why you decided to add the particular gesture or movement you did.<br /><br /><strong>Part 3: Mood</strong><br /><br />Submit 3 images you have taken that evoke a particular mood or emotion and explain what elements you included to help evoke those feelings.</span></p>',17,0,NULL,'2015-03-11 17:34:16','2015-03-11 19:05:28'),(42,125,'Grammar of Visual Storytelling','','<p>Now you get to try your hand at it. I want you do go back to your chosen photo-story project and produce <strong>two good images from each</strong> of the \"grammar\" categories we\'ve just discussed:</p>\r\n<p>1) Wide-angle / overview / scene-setting shot.</p>\r\n<p>2) Middle-distance shot (usually made with lenses in the standard 35-50 mm range).</p>\r\n<p>3) Detail / close-up or \"point\" shot.</p>\r\n<p>So, I want to see <strong>six images</strong> that you\'ve gone back and made from the situation surrounding your chosen story for this course. Best of luck!</p>',17,0,NULL,'2015-03-14 15:26:19','2015-03-14 15:26:19'),(43,122,'Editing the Take - Telling the Story Assignment Part 1','','<p><strong>Part 1:&nbsp; </strong>Setting for the first part of this assignment is a women\'s boxing school in Berlin, Germany.&nbsp; The participants all come from troubled backgrounds and are present to build confidence and self-esteem.</p>',9,0,NULL,'2015-03-14 15:30:01','2015-03-14 15:32:37'),(44,122,'Editing the Take - Telling the Story Assignment Part 2','','<p><strong>Part 2: </strong>The second part of your assignment is to take <strong>12</strong> of your own best images - those being worked on for your course photo-story project and place these into a story layout sequence that you feel tells your story best. Submit your 12 images in sequence for story critique. Again, if you want to add comments for your choices, please feel free to do so.</p>',8,0,NULL,'2015-03-14 15:32:09','2015-05-07 08:24:32'),(45,124,'Finding an Audience','','<p>For this final assignment, I want you to write a query for your photo-story and <strong>select six of your best photographs</strong> to accompany it. Your editorial target will be a local newspaper or regional magazine. We\'re not talking National Geographic here - just yet! The point of this working exercise is to go through the process of preparing and submitting work and to receiving a response. But before you drop your packet into the post, let\'s take a hard look at it together. File your query and chosen images to the TCI website. And - keep in mind that 99% of success in anything you do, lies in simply \"showing up\". Best of luck with this assignment - I\'m looking forward to seeing (and reading) your work!</p>',16,0,NULL,'2015-03-14 15:38:13','2015-03-14 15:38:13'),(46,123,'Captioning in the Digital Age','','<p>For this assignment, I would like for you to take the ten images you\'ve already selected for your photo-story and caption each, including keywords you think most effective for each. Remember, this aspect of being a visual story-teller - a photojournalist - is an important one. Deliver the facts concisely and as accurately as you can and submit your 10 images, captions, and keywords for this week\'s assignment. If you need help, remember that you can always email me. Or, submit your question(s) and/or discussion for the all the class to consider and respond to.</p>',16,0,NULL,'2015-03-14 15:42:28','2015-03-14 15:42:28'),(47,140,'Research and Plan: Know Your Subject and Kit','','<p>This assignment is in two related parts:<br /> <br /> <strong>Part one:&nbsp; </strong>Choose a family member, friend or someone you know quite well and who will agree to have their portrait taken. Then sit down and write a list of this person\'s character traits, leisure interests, work interests and anything else you feel defines them as a person. Go through this list and keep in your mind a few of these characteristics you feel you could use to capture the \"truth\" about this person.<br /> <br /> Please upload two images that you feel best portrays your subject and say which aspect of this person you feel you have succeeded in depicting best in each image. Title these first photos, \"Lesson #1 Shot 1 and shot 2&rdquo;.<br /> <br /> <strong>Part two:&nbsp; </strong>Now concentrate on two aspects as discussed in this first lesson.&nbsp; Using your research and knowledge of the person, photograph your chosen subject in a way you feel best captures the essence of this person through a head shot. Don\'t worry too much about the environment around them, we will come to that later, I want you to try and capture the subject\'s personality and character through their face and expression.<br /> <br /> Whilst shooting this portrait, experiment with different lenses and distances between yourself and your subject. If you only have one focal-length lens, then just try photographing from a variety of distances. See how these distances differ visually and ask your subject how they feel about being photographed close-up and from afar.<br /> <br /> Then upload six more images that show the use of these lenses and distances. Please label each one with the lens used and how you and your subject feel about the process of taking each image and the results you have achieved. Title these photos, \"Lesson #1 shot 3_throught to shot 8\".<br /> <br /> <strong>Eight photos in total</strong> to upload to the TCI site for this week\'s lesson. Most of all - have fun with this assignment and I look forward to seeing your results.</p>',7,0,NULL,'2015-03-17 14:50:17','2015-03-24 10:16:53'),(48,141,'Using Light to Aid Your Portrayal','','<p>For this assignment, I would like you to take<strong> four different approaches</strong> to lighting a portrait.<br /> <br /> <strong>One:</strong> Take portraits of someone indoors using only available light. I would like you to use daylight in the form of a window and the artificial lighting on offer. Try and choose two different photographs, one with each lighting and upload your two photos to the TCI site, labelling them \"L: 2_1\" \"L: 2_2\".<br /> <br /> <strong>Two:</strong> Whilst doing these portraits, add a flash gun to see how this brings a different photographic look and \"feel\" to the portrait situation made previously, using only available light. Label it L: 2_3\".</p>\r\n<p><strong>Three:</strong> Take a portrait of the same person (or different, if you please) outside and try and harness the daylight, using the different types of use of lighting as discussed in the lesson, flat light, direct light, side light and back light. Label these \"L2_4,\" etc. and with the type of lighting technique used.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Four:</strong> For the backlight shot, add a little fill-flash and see how this alters the result. Label this L2_8.<br /> <br /> If you do not have a flash then please just carry out parts One and Three. Have fun experimenting with light and I look forward to seeing your results!</p>',18,7,NULL,'2015-03-17 14:56:09','2015-03-24 10:15:35'),(49,142,'Breaking Conventions: A Portrait is More Than Just a Face','','<p>For this third assignment I would like you to look at the techniques and ideas we have discussed in the lesson and put them in to practice. Take <strong>six images</strong> of one or more people. These people could be friends or family or work colleagues. Photograph them using these ideas. No head-and-shoulders shots, but a selection of images where the viewer is told a little more of their story through the things that they surround themselves, elements of their person that sum up their work, life or personality. Play with the genre of portraiture and really look around the environment that you find yourself in and think about how you can best reveal the truth that you see about your subject. Play with the environment, people&rsquo;s features, if they are an artist you could shoot their hands, still lives of their posessions and tools, etc...<br /> <br /> Most of all have fun with your portraiture and I look forward to seeing the results.</p>',18,7,NULL,'2015-03-17 14:58:37','2015-03-24 10:26:55'),(50,143,'Capturing Subject and Moment, Synergy and an Open Mind','','<p>So, for this final assignment we shall be looking at how you can get to the truth of your subject and practicing the ideas we have worked on through out the course. I would like you to choose one subject. Preferably a different person from the previous assignments.&nbsp; Also it would be good to photograph someone whom you are not completely familiar with.&nbsp; This will leave you scope to find out things about them whilst taking the portrait.<br /> <br /> Now, start with planning your shot. Write down all you know about them and pick out a trait you would like to portray in your portrait. Then go to their environment. This could be work or home or a place they spend a lot of time, but home would be most telling. Now take a series of five portraits of this person.<br /> <br /> Through all the portraits in this assignment, think about the light and use it wisely. Look at where the best light is and even plan your shots around that, it is an important aspect of your portrait. Use daylight and get the best light you can on your subject and the environment.<br /> <br /> 1: Start with the pre-planned image. Shoot this as planned.<br /> 2: Spend time with your subject and study the environment with which they surround themselves. Take the next image where you are working with a fairly wide lens and make sure that the environment around your subject tells as much of their story as their face and demeanour towards the camera.<br /> 3: Now use your patience and see if you can capture a moment you weren?t expecting to find, see if you can swerve off plan by following the mood and emotion of your subject on that particular day.<br /> 4: With simple lighting take a close up portrait of the sitter that brings out their personality without the aid of any other elements.<br /> 5: Take a look around the sitters environment and take a still life which you feel tells the most truth about this person.<br /> <br /> Enjoy this challenge, there is quite a lot here to get your head around but see if you can capture as much as possible. I look forward to seeing the results.</p>',17,7,NULL,'2015-03-17 15:00:53','2015-03-24 10:29:32'),(51,144,'Learning the Characteristics','','<p>Your turn now to get that 50mm prime back into operation.&nbsp; For this first assignment I want you to work extensively with this lens and this lens only (even if your dslr possesses a cropped chip factor), producing images that vary in terms of their depth of field.&nbsp; Put your feet to work too, creating \"wide-angle,\" as well as \"zoom\" shots of the same subject.&nbsp; When you feel practiced enough, upload <strong>six images</strong> total - one demonstrating a soft, out of focus background behind the subject; one showing the foreground subject soft and background sharp and two sets of 50mm images depicting a \"wide-angle\" (greater context) and a \"zoom\" (detail) view of the same subject.&nbsp; Good luck - and have fun with this!</p>',7,0,NULL,'2015-03-23 08:19:45','2015-03-23 08:26:25'),(52,145,'Exploring Versatility','','<p>This week you\'ll be putting your 50mm prime to the creative test.&nbsp; I want you to take to \"the street\", practice what we\'ve talked about in this week\'s lesson and then upload to the TCI website for critique and comments your very best in the following categories and numbers:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Two images using \"Bokeh\" in different and creative ways.</li>\r\n<li>Two \"street photos\" composed \"simply\" and possessing a definite \"sense of moment.\"</li>\r\n<li>Two photos in which positioning and depth-of-field convey a telephoto lens perspective.</li>\r\n<li>Two images in which the viewer senses a wide-angle lens was in use.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Have a fun and challenging time with this assignment and don\'t forget what we discussed concerning the relationship between subject and background.</p>',18,7,NULL,'2015-03-23 08:21:16','2015-03-23 08:28:35'),(53,146,'The Low-Light Advantage','','<p>Forget the \"Golden Hours\" of morning and late afternoon photography for this assignment.&nbsp; I want you to push the light limits with your 50mm prime.&nbsp; Use an ISO setting in the 100 - 160 range and seek out low-light situations to make stunning photographs with your lens and your own creative camera skills.&nbsp; Specifically, I would like you to upload three of your strongest (composition, light, color and sense of moment) in each of the following categories - 9 photographs in all.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>3 images in an environment where very low levels of natural light are present (e.g. a church or cathedral, forest or museum).</li>\r\n<li>3 photos made where only window light filters into a room.</li>\r\n<li>3 pictures in near darkness where a point-source (e.g. tungsten light, fireplace or candlelight) is in some way made the subject of your photograph.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Be creative and have fun with this assignment!</p>',18,7,NULL,'2015-03-23 08:22:52','2015-03-23 08:33:06'),(54,147,'Going It Alone','','<p>For this final assignment, I am sending you out \"into the world\" to produce a photo-essay using nothing but your 50mm lens.&nbsp; Similar to what I\'ve done in Lesson #4, I want you to photograph a topic or situation of your choice using the full range of strengths your 50-mil has to offer.&nbsp; Include a scene-setting overview shot, middle-distance shots, \"wide-angle,\" \"telephoto\" and close-up perspectives.&nbsp; Try hand-holding in low light and apply \"bokeh\" where appropriate.&nbsp; Keep in mind that a good photograph includes quality light (can be low, but should have a degree of richness or warmth to it), good color (a limited palette of related hues is best), good composition (Rule of Thirds is an excellent start) and \"sense of moment\" (an action that raises the picture above the \"ordinary\").&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Be aware too of the relationship of subject and background.&nbsp; The two should be supportive of a common theme to the point of creating \"visual integrity / internal logic\" within the frame.&nbsp; If the background does not do this, change camera perspective to eliminate it completely or use a wide aperture setting to blur the background beyond recognition.</p>\r\n<p>Spend time shooting a thorough \"take\" and then upload your most stunning 8-photo essay to the TCI site for critique and comment.&nbsp; Have fun with this and think creatively!</p>',17,7,NULL,'2015-03-23 08:24:01','2015-03-23 08:35:30'),(55,148,'Taking Control','','<p>For this first assignment, please make no fewer than 20 exposures varying your choice of camera controls as we discussed them above. Then, compare this &ldquo;take&rdquo; with the pictures you selected from magazines earlier. Briefly describe any technical and stylistic similarities you see between these two collections. Then, upload the best <strong>eight</strong> of your photographs to the TCI site for critique. &ldquo;Pushing boundaries&rdquo; is the key phrase here. Have fun with it all!</p>',7,0,NULL,'2015-03-23 15:21:57','2015-03-23 16:18:47'),(56,149,'Bending and Breaking Rules','','<p>With the contents of this lesson as your &ldquo;license&rdquo; to creative freedom, I want you to thoroughly explore the photographic frame in all its visible and not so &ldquo;see-able&rdquo; dimensions. Then, upload your favourite 8 photos of this \"adventure\" to the TCI site for critique and discussion. This is an opportunity to really stretch your awareness concerning the kind of photography that &ldquo;grabs your soul&rdquo;. Have fun and learn a lot from it.</p>',18,7,NULL,'2015-03-23 16:22:42','2015-03-23 16:22:42'),(57,150,'Letting the Ghost Run Free','','<p>Select some interesting subjects and practice the techniques we\'ve discussed above. Then upload three of your most prized photographs from each topical category - \"flash-ghosting\", simulating a night-time scene and the pan-fill-flash combination - 9 photographs in total to the site for critique. Be sure to jot down a few technical notes (exposure details) to accompany each, too. Good luck!</p>',18,7,NULL,'2015-03-23 16:25:50','2015-03-23 16:25:50'),(58,151,'The World According to - YOU!','','<p>For this final assignment, I want you to visually interpret the world you know best - that which lies immediately around you. Using your favourite lenses and the techniques and approaches discussed here, I want you to explore your personal vision and upload eight photographs that you feel most closely reflect this. Take your time with this final assignment and above all else, have fun in doing it!</p>',17,7,NULL,'2015-03-23 16:28:45','2015-03-23 16:28:45'),(59,152,'Fundamentals of Interiors Photography','','<p>For this first assignment I would like you to choose a subject, be it your home, even someone else&rsquo;s home and practice taking photographs of rooms, thinking about the angles, the subject and why you are shooting it. Be careful with the light. Present 6-8 photographs with a brief synopsis of why you chose them.</p>',7,0,NULL,'2015-03-24 15:46:49','2015-03-24 15:46:49'),(60,153,'Styling and Lighting the Scene and Subject','','<p>For this assignment I would like you to split it into two categories; Styling and Lighting producing 3-4 photographs on each subject. For Styling choose a room, play around with objects, moving them and adding them to create your photograph. For Lighting, experiment with different times of the day, using candles, fires and lamps. Play around to see what different ambient shots you can create.</p>',18,7,NULL,'2015-03-24 15:48:17','2015-03-24 16:09:15'),(61,154,'Still Life and Portraits','','<p>For this assignment I would also like you to split it into two categories; Still Life and Portraits producing 3-4 photographs on each subject. For the Still Life category I would like you to include a detailed shot in a house and then create a composition of your own. For Portraits play around with settings, people in different positions, either posed&nbsp;or perhaps doing something around the house.</p>',18,7,NULL,'2015-03-24 15:49:49','2015-03-24 16:11:02'),(62,155,'Presentation of Your Interiors Layout','','<p>For this final assignment, I\'d like you to put together a mini-reportage of 8-10 photographs of a house or bed and breakfast of your choice, pulling all the elements learnt in the last 3 assignments together. Provide a&nbsp;short synopsis of the place you have chosen, so that the reader understands where and what you have photographed.</p>',17,7,NULL,'2015-03-24 15:51:23','2015-03-24 16:14:46'),(63,156,'Highlights and Shadows','','<p>For this first assignment, please upload <strong>8 photographs</strong> that represent your response to seeing and photographing in black-and-white. In making your images, think about:</p>\r\n<p>1. gradations of tonality</p>\r\n<p>2. sharp contrast of light and shadow among elements in the photograph</p>\r\n<p>3. texture shown in light and shadow</p>\r\n<p>4. emotion shown through contrast, shape and texture rather than color.</p>\r\n<p>Note: Please do not upload RAW images for this assignment.&nbsp; Size them to not larger than 1000 pixels on the long side at 72 dpi / jpeg file format.</p>\r\n<p>Best of luck and have fun with this assignment!</p>',7,0,NULL,'2015-03-25 10:22:55','2015-03-25 13:29:13'),(64,157,'The Digital Camera Perspective','','<p>For this assignment, please study and photograph the following:</p>\r\n<p><strong>1. For contrast:</strong></p>\r\n<p>a. 2 scenes for high contrast.</p>\r\n<p>b. 2 scenes that you think have low contrast.</p>\r\n<p>c. 2 scenes in which you use contrast to accentuate your subject</p>\r\n<p><strong>Upload all 6 images</strong> to the TCI website for critique and comments.</p>\r\n<p><strong>2. For shape and pattern:</strong></p>\r\n<p>a. 2 triangles. Not obvious street sign sorts of triangles or individual objects that are triangles, but multiple objects that create interesting triangle patterns. Be creative and have fun!</p>\r\n<p>b. 3 circles. Again not obvious or individual circular items, but circular patterns or patterns evocative of circles that are in the world around you but that you don\'t necessarily notice in your every day world of color. Challenge yourself to find patterns that you only see if you look with grayscale eyes. Look at your world differently than you usually do.</p>\r\n<p>Send all the above images to me at the end of the 10-day assignment period. Good luck and again, have fun! Happy photographing!</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',18,7,NULL,'2015-03-25 10:24:55','2015-03-25 13:32:31'),(65,158,'Developing B & W: Computer and Software','','<p><strong>PART 1:</strong> Look at the histograms of the images you\'ve taken as part of this course over the last two weeks in your RAW converter. This will give you a feel for what the histograms of variously lit images look like. No image submission necessary here, just explore this and ask any questions that arise.</p>\r\n<p><strong>PART 2:</strong> Select 2 of the images you have made with your camera in RAW over the last two lessons. Process them each two different ways: one for high global contrast and a second way for low global/overall contrast. Submit both versions of the image.</p>\r\n<p><strong>PART 3: </strong>Make all adjustments you feel are necessary to the same 2 chosen images from the last assignment so that they convey the message/feeling you want them to. List what you have done to each of them and send me a JPEG version of the starting RAW image and JPEG versions of your final product.</p>',18,7,NULL,'2015-03-25 10:26:33','2015-03-25 13:35:27'),(66,159,'Expressing Yourself in Monochrome','','<p><strong>Part 1:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Photograph the same scene 3 times to express the following feelings with contrast.</p>\r\n<p>1. Romantic</p>\r\n<p>2. Foreboding</p>\r\n<p>3. Mysterious</p>\r\n<p><strong>Part 2:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Look for areas of interesting texture that can be photographed by zeroing in on specific surfaces and examining them for signs of patterned contrast.</p>\r\n<p>1. Create a 2 highly textured images</p>\r\n<p><strong>Part 3:</strong></p>\r\n<p>1. Create a high-key image.</p>\r\n<p>2. Create a low-key image.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Ongoing Assignment:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Study images of black-and-white photography masters Studying prints, a wide variety of them, and looking at their tonal values, the tonal separation and their relation to the subject, as well as our own responses to them will help you develop your photography greatly. I\'ll compare learning to identify image values to a musician\'s training for recognition of pitch. There is no substitute for constant and ongoing practice.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',17,7,NULL,'2015-03-25 13:24:24','2015-03-25 13:38:09'),(67,160,'Equipping Yourself – Rights and Mobility','','<p>One camera, one lens - and carry them with you wherever you go! Such is the \"game-rule\" for this first assignment, consisting of two parts - eight photographs total to be presented for instructor critique and comment.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Part 1:</strong> Use either a 28mm or a 35mm prime lens. If your zoom includes either or both of these focal lengths, set one of them and place a piece of cloth tape (so-called \"gaffer\'s\" tape) on the barrel of your lens to hold it at just this focal position. Now take to the \"streets\" wherever you live and be prepared for \"adventure.\" Steer clear of any hazards or danger, but make an effort to push yourself beyond your normal \"comfort limits\" to a degree. Make a mental note of just how you feel walking around with a camera and minimalist equipment, at that. Your task for this first part of the lesson is to reflect on this experience and briefly describe just how you felt walking around and making pictures with your camera. Were you uncomfortable doing this? Did you shy away from certain situations? Did you enjoy this experience? What advantages and/or disadvantages did you experience having but a single focal-length lens at your disposal?</p>\r\n<p><strong>Part 2:</strong> Interact with people, explain your assignment to them and ask to make photographs of them, capturing visually expressive - \"defining moment\" (e.g. a hand being raised, a smile - some type of \"animation\" being expressed) - image of your interaction. Don\'t forget to follow-up afterward with a presentation of your result, viewed on your digital camera\'s monitor display. Then upload four of your best photographs of these situations and subjects to the TCI site for instructor comment and critique. Of these human subjects you photographed, identify one you would be interested in photographing further in detail and include another two images of he or she.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Part 3:</strong> Discover your own billboard or interesting background and wait for just the right person or people to pass by. Upload two of these images for critique.</p>',7,0,NULL,'2015-03-25 17:25:10','2015-03-25 17:48:11'),(68,161,'Finding Your Way','','<p>You won&rsquo;t find a one - &ldquo;single&rdquo; - definition of &ldquo;Street Photography.&rdquo;&nbsp; There will always be many definitions of what street photographers do.&nbsp; Most basically though, this genre explores the interrelationship of humans and their urban settings - how people from all walks of life affect - and are affect by - the humanity that surrounds them.</p>\r\n<p>What sets street photography apart from other approaches to photography, is the constant search for interesting &ldquo;contrasts&rdquo; found amid the mundane and &ldquo;everyday&rdquo; of the street.&nbsp; Street photography is about &ldquo;selection&rdquo; - what to include in the frame and what not.&nbsp; And above all else, the genre is about capturing all this at just the right moment - that fraction of a second in which everything in viewfinder comes together to poignantly &ldquo;define&rdquo; that contrast that stands before the lens.</p>\r\n<p>Some street photographers choose to remain mobile and aloof throughout this process.&nbsp; Others - like myself - tend to get closer to subjects - even returning to explore contrasts at different times of the day.</p>\r\n<p>For this second assignment, I want you to define what &ldquo;street photography&rdquo; is for you.&nbsp; And while incorporating these over-riding characteristics of the genre described above, practice your street photography and <strong>upload your 6 best images</strong> to the TCI website for critique and review.</p>',18,7,NULL,'2015-03-25 17:26:20','2015-03-25 17:50:43'),(69,162,'Thinking - Seeing “Selects”','','<p>For this assignment, it&rsquo;s &ldquo;composition&rdquo; we&rsquo;re focusing on and ways to bring expression and interpretation to it.<br /><br />I want you to continue the process of street observation, anticipating interesting actions, situations and events that might - or are known to re-occur - before your camera.&nbsp; Then in particular, I want you create photographs in the following categories and to send in your very best in the numbers specified below:<br /><br /></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>2 photos with foreground subject in sharp focus and background soft (&ldquo;aperture priority approach&rdquo; to emphasize the subject and to lessen background distraction or obscure a thematically-unrelated background).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>2 photos with foreground in soft focus and background subject in sharp focus (technique to heighten &ldquo;edge / tension / suspense&rdquo; and to direct the viewer&rsquo;s eye to a thematically-related subject, positioned in the background of the picture).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>2 photos with both foreground subject and background in sharp focus, demonstrating a thematic ties between the two.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>1 photo that demonstrates action blur (shutter priority approach with slow shutter speed setting).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>1 photo stopping an interesting action at its peak (i.e. shutter-priority approach to capture a &ldquo;Defining Moment&rdquo;)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>1 photo where &ldquo;layers&rdquo; have been compositionally created to add interest and interpretation to a photograph</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Nine images total</strong> for critique.&nbsp; This assignment is challenging in a &ldquo;Street Photography&rdquo; context, but give it your best and learn from mistakes made.&nbsp; Good luck!</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',18,0,NULL,'2015-03-25 17:29:09','2015-04-27 08:53:01'),(70,163,'Exceeding the Sum of Parts','','<p>Whether your street photography portfolio is tied together in &ldquo;story form&rdquo; (as mine here happens to be) or your images are associated only broadly - by location, time of day or some other thematic &ldquo;thread,&rdquo; these photographs should reveal something unique and thought-provoking about everyday life.&nbsp; Your photos should - through observation, composition and timing - take the &ldquo;mundane&rdquo; and bring it to viewer attention in a way that begs more than a single and fleeting look.<br /><br />Given this focus, I want you to to through the work you&rsquo;ve produced to-date for this course and upload the 10 photographs that you are most proud of and best reflect the genre of &ldquo;Street Photography.&rdquo;<br /><br />Looking forward to seeing your choices.</p>',17,0,NULL,'2015-03-25 17:30:37','2015-04-27 08:53:24'),(71,164,'Gearing Up for the Night Sky','','<p><strong>Assignment Preparation:</strong></p>\r\n<p>These assignments require that your camera is on a tripod and should be set up as follows: for minimum noise use an ISO of between 100 to 400, select the multi segment metering, matrix metering (Nikon cameras), evaluative (Canon cameras) and use the manual exposure mode to determine the correct exposure. Use a small aperture setting for more depth of field, such as F8 or F11 and then calculate the correct shutter speed. Use Live View to help frame and compose the scene. Remember Live View eats batteries, so take at least two batteries. Use auto focus unless the light is too low or too low in contrast for your lens to auto focus. Then use manual focus. I recommend setting a Grid pattern on your focusing screen, which helps straiten the image. Bracket all your exposures, and use the longest shutter you can, preferably in the seconds. And make sure your camera is secured and stable on the tripod!</p>\r\n<p>Photograph on a clear night and on an overcast night, in both an urban and rural setting, if you can.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Part 1:</strong></p>\r\n<p>In a city or town photograph at dusk and night on a clear and an overcast night.&nbsp; Photograph at dusk and at night in an urban setting on both a clear night and on an overcast night. Produce 3 images from each light situation. For both situations look for scene with relatively even exposure. When photographing on a clear night, try to avoid a high contrast scene instead look for a scene with brightness throughout or with minimum of shadow areas. Frame the scene and take a meter reading. Trust your meter and make an exposure. Bracket your exposure by + 1 stop over and to -1 stop under. You can bracket by changing the either the shutter speed or the aperture setting.</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><em>NOTE: I tend to bracket by changing the shutter speed, not the F/stop, just in case I want to merge the images in a HDR, High Dynamic Range.</em></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #000000;\">This first exercise is more about technique and exposure and not composition. Concentrate on seeing the light, correctly exposing and producing a sharp image. We will work on composition throughout future assignments. When submitting your images include the metadata or the ISO, shutter speed and f/Stop, and of course your questions.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><strong><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Part 2:</span></strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">In a rural area photograph at dusk and at night on a clear and overcast night.<br /></span><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Assignment #2 moves you to the countryside or to a rural area. This may be more difficult if there is no brightness in the sky. And this exercise is weather dependent, so be patient. Find a location on both a clear night and on an overcast night that has minimal deep shadows. For example try not to have trees or a hill or the subject back- lit, especially on the clear night. Produce 3 images from each light situation. Use Live View &ndash; if you have it- ISO 200 and a small aperture setting such as F8, or F11. Bracket your exposures in full or &frac12; stops.</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Good luck and remember you can always post your questions for me to answer. Don&rsquo;t forget you learn through your mistakes. </span><strong><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><br /></span></strong></span></p>',18,7,NULL,'2015-03-26 13:05:10','2015-03-26 14:01:53'),(72,165,'Capturing Motion and Painting with Light','','<p><strong>Assignment Preparation:</strong></p>\r\n<p>These assignments must show motion by using a slow or long shutter speed. Look for scenes with moving objects or subjects; this can be moving cars or people walking. Challenge yourself to photograph objects whose movement you can control and cannot control. Choose locations that provide long exposures from at least 1 &ndash; 30 seconds. Set your camera to ISO 100 or 200, at F5.6 or F8 and then calculate the correct shutter speed. </p>\r\n<p><strong>Part 1&nbsp; Capturing motion of a moving object:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Your first assignment is to capture the motion of either cars or objects moving. These can be cars in the street or any subject that is moving. For the street scene choose an area where the lights of the cars are not moving towards you, but parallel to the camera. Make several test exposures at different shutter speeds to determine the appropriate combination of shutter speed and aperture setting.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Part 2&nbsp; Capturing motion of a person:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Find a stairwell or location and have someone walk through the scene. It would be helpful to position the camera on an angle to the scene or the subject. This allows the motion to appear more pronounced.&nbsp; Experiment with different settings but only change one setting at a time. This way you will know which setting works.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Part 3&nbsp; Light Painting with a Flashlight:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Select a location where part of the scene requires additional light. Use a low ISO setting and a long shutter speed that allows you enough time to walk into the scene. If you are close enough to the subject you can remain by your camera. Using a flashlight add light to the areas that require more exposure, or that you want to de-saturate the color, or that you want to brighten.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><br /><strong>Part 4&nbsp; Light Painting with a Strobe Unit:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>If you use a strobe unit, in the automatic mode set your strobe unit to match the aperture setting on your lens. On the strobe unit, notice the distance scale showing the range of distance your strobe must be from the subject. For example at F5.6 the distance may be from 5ft to 15ft. Your strobe unit must be within this distance to emit F5.6 worth of light. Set the strobe unit to match the aperture setting on your lens, for example if your camera exposure is 15 seconds at F5.6, set your flash unit to F5.6. To fire your strobe unit press the test button. Wait for the ready light to appear before firing the strobe unit again.</li>\r\n</ul>',18,7,NULL,'2015-03-26 13:06:57','2015-03-26 17:49:11'),(73,166,'Mastering the Strobe','','<p><strong>Assignment Preparation:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Lighting a Portrait: Using the strobe unit as the main source of light and as a fill light <br />Produce a series of images that illustrate the following lighting situations; in the streets at night, indoors where the subject is back or side lite from a window and indoors with no ambient light. For these assignments your ISO can range from ISO 200 to 800, and practice hand holding the camera at slow shutter speeds. <br /><br /><strong>Part 1 </strong>- Lighting a Portrait with the Strobe as the Main Source of Light:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>For this exercise photograph a person in a dark room. Use the following settings. ISO 200, 1/30 at F8 strobe at TTL 0. If the room is very dark or very large, with black walls and you need to open up or add exposure to the background use a slower shutter speed. To reduce the ambient or background exposure use a fast shutter. If you really want to darken the room set your camera to the fastest shutter speed that will sync to your strobe unit and use the smallest aperture setting on your lens, at TTL 0 on your strobe unit. NOTE: your strobe unit needs to be within 5ft of your subject to achieve F16 or F22 worth of light on your subject. This method produces a very dark background with a very bright subject.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><br /><strong>Part 2 - Lighting an Environmental Portrait with the Strobe unit as a Fill Light:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The goal in this environmental portrait is to include the ambient or background exposure with the light from the strobe unit. Place a person in a location that has some ambient light, this can be inside or outside. Set your camera to the ambient exposure and bracket your strobe settings from TTL 0 to -1, -2, &amp; -3.&nbsp; For example if the subject is outside in the streets at night use ISO 400 or ISO 800, if the meter reads 1/8 at F5.6, set your camera accordingly and bracket the strobe settings.</li>\r\n</ul>',18,7,NULL,'2015-03-26 13:08:14','2015-03-26 17:55:06'),(74,167,'\"Light\" is the Language','','<p><strong>Final Assignment - The Photo Essay:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Tell a story through a series of <strong>5 to 7 images</strong> taken under low light and at night. Use a tripod if necessary; consider the frame and the placement of your subject within the frame. Incorporated the techniques learned in Lessons 1 to 4. If your essay includes an environmental portrait use a strobe unit as the main source of light and as a fill light. <br /><br />Be Patient, Keep Notes, Expect to Problem Solve and Good Luck!</p>',17,7,NULL,'2015-03-26 13:09:32','2015-03-26 17:53:08'),(75,168,'Simplicity: Styling, Makeup, Expressions','','<p>Your first assignment is to make <strong>four images</strong> of your model that present them in a fresh and natural way.&nbsp; Be sure to pay close attention to:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>expression</li>\r\n<li>body posture</li>\r\n<li>uncluttered background</li>\r\n<li>flattering light (e.g. open-shade)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Note that in this first lesson, I converted images to black-and-white in order to make them a little more \"timeless\" and to put more attention on the eyes, than on the colors around the model.&nbsp; For this assignment, you are free to choose color or monochrome - whichever you feel suits the particular situation, best.&nbsp; Keep any adjustments to a minimum, as the natural texture of the skin is important and agencies cannot use images in which the model has been altered too much or looks waxy or over-exposed.&nbsp; The more you practice with this general formula for \"testing,\" the faster you will build a portfolio of your own that generates from the agencies and models who see it.</p>\r\n<p>Good luck with this first assignment and be sure to ask if you have any questions.</p>',60,0,NULL,'2015-03-27 07:22:16','2015-04-24 08:38:10'),(76,169,'Locations, Model Direction, Lighting','','<p>Your new assignment is to shoot a model on location.&nbsp; Plan the shoot ahead of time in your mind, so you have a \"shoot-list\" ready to work from when you arrive.&nbsp; Pay attention to your model\'s clothing and the background you\'re using.&nbsp; Direct the model in, <strong>1) portraits</strong>; <strong>2) full- length</strong>; and <strong>3) small movement</strong>. Do this in ways that flatter the model.</p>\r\n<p>Once you\'ve completed your shoot and are happy with its results, upload two of your best images from each of these three categories - <strong>six photographs in total</strong> for critique and comments.</p>\r\n<p><strong><em>Be creative and have fun with this assignment !</em></strong></p>',53,0,NULL,'2015-03-27 07:24:07','2015-04-24 10:02:36'),(77,170,' The \"Fashion Edge\"','','<p>Your assignment is to do a fashion shoot from concept to casting, styling to make-up and hair, and to include a beauty shot and movement shot.&nbsp; Use what you have available to you for location and cast a model if you can or a very photogenic model-hopeful.&nbsp; If she or he can collaborate with you on styling and makeup then have a plan and storyline and work together to achieve the best shoot you can. Try to find local makeup artists and stylist to collaborate with you if you can.&nbsp; Don&rsquo;t try to copy your inspiration exactly as the original will always be better based on the high level of production &ndash; just use it to inspire your own creativity.&nbsp; I can&rsquo;t wait to see what you shoot!&nbsp; Fashion is fun!&nbsp; Enjoy it!</p>',60,0,NULL,'2015-03-27 07:29:45','2015-04-24 08:39:26'),(78,171,'Lighting Techniques - Photographic Range','','<p>Your assignment is to shoot <strong>four or five images</strong> using an interior location with available light, and if you are equipped, to shoot in a small studio. Direct the model to achieve expressions with calm and interesting eyes, and relaxed, natural body positions that highlight long limbs and slender figures. Bring out the unique qualities of your model.</p>',60,0,NULL,'2015-03-27 07:31:50','2015-04-24 08:39:55'),(79,172,'Lifestyle Photography and Why Smiles Sell','','<p>Capture 3 images of the same model / models in 3 different scenarious, in an outdoor setting.</p>\r\n<p>Choose your outdoor activity - for example:</p>\r\n<p>A person walking or playing with their dog in a park<br />A father and son riding bikes in a suburban setting<br />A woman excercising <br />A couple dining at a caf&eacute;<br />A group of friends having fun at a beach</p>\r\n<p>Choose your setting carefully, selecting the right lighting and right time of the day to enhance the mood of the image. Visit the location at different times of the day so you have a better understanding of the light so you can be prepared for your shoot. Lighting should be ambient and well lit - use a reflector of bounced flash if necessary.</p>\r\n<p>Pay attention to the background details and colours and if it is part of the story telling or distracting; if it is too busy and leads the eye away from the subject and feeling of the photo. Crop in tight if need be.</p>\r\n<p>Select your wardrobe and props accordingly to tell your story and enhance the feel of the image.</p>\r\n<p>Be creative and original:</p>\r\n<p>view the scene from a different perspective or angle <br />select only part of the person and prop to portray your message <br />use your lighting to create a dynamic image<br />use a slow shutter speed to create movement and excitement</p>\r\n<p>Choose your models well - people that will be naturally expressive and comfortable in front of the camera.</p>\r\n<p>What is it about your model/models that is so appealing, charming, quirky or upbeat? Bring out the best qualities and expressions in you models. Watch for the most spontaneous moments of interaction.<br /> <br />Most of all, enjoy your shoot with your model or models and have fun - you may be surprised how great your shots will be!</p>',7,0,NULL,'2015-03-28 15:38:26','2015-03-28 15:43:15'),(80,173,'Concepts and Coordination: Planning Your Shoot','','<p>In this assignment you will be coordinating your photo shoot with a choice of 3 different themes:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Play</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Romance</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Happiness</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>So the focus of this assignment is on the mood of the image and preparing your shoot accordingly.</p>\r\n<p>For example, your lifestyle photo depicting &lsquo;PLAY\' could be as simple as somebody doing a cartwheel on a beautiful sandy beach on a sunny day or a little girl trying on her mother\'s oversized shoes and hat while standing in front of a mirror. Be creative with your concepts and story telling and use either movement, colour, light, and props to express and enrich the mood.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Casting:</strong> Obviously for this assignment your casting is critical in achieving the desired result. Select subjects that will be naturally &lsquo;playful\', &lsquo;romantic\' or &lsquo;happy\'. You may also want to spend more time with your subjects to help them to open up and feel more relaxed in front of the camera in order to allow for those spontaneous natural moments to flow easily without trying to force them to happen. During the shoot be sure to give positive feedback to your models to encourage them to be expressive and relaxed. Ideally you want your models to take their awareness off the camera to allow for the most natural and spontaneous feelings to be conveyed and captured. You can choose single subjects, couples, families, children or pets.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Location:</strong> Scout out your location for your lifestyle shoot in accordance with the story telling - whether it be a home setting, local shopping centre, beach or local fairground - you can be as creative as you like! Check the location in detail, the backgrounds, the lighting, if there are any interferences at any particular times of the day or if permission is required to take photographs.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Styling, wardrobe and props:</strong> Your styling, wardrobe and props can enrich and add flavour to your lifestyle shoot or in some cases can be the critical component in creating a desired mood or effect or in creating strong composition for example.</p>\r\n<p>What props are required for your storytelling? Think this through in detail to make the image real and believable so that it doesn\'t look set up. Are the props and wardrobe enhancing the story telling? Choose your props accordingly.</p>\r\n<p><br /><strong>Submit a minimum of three images in three different scenarios using either one or all of the themes.&nbsp; <em>Have fun!</em><br /></strong></p>',18,7,NULL,'2015-03-28 15:47:05','2015-03-28 15:47:05'),(81,174,'Markets First: Seeing Subjects as Clients See Them','','<p>For this lesson\'s assignment, the focus and theme for the lifestyle shoot is related to current social issues and situations, popular for today\'s editorial and advertising markets.</p>\r\n<p>Select 3 categories from the list below and make a number of photographs for each.&nbsp; When you feel you\'ve \"got it,\" upload your 3 strongest images from each of these chosen categories (9 photographs in total) to the TCI website.&nbsp; Be sure to label the categories to which your images belong.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Friends hanging out</li>\r\n<li>Women exercising either indoors or in nature</li>\r\n<li>People eating healthy food</li>\r\n<li>Couple in romantic situation</li>\r\n<li>Seniors enjoying positive life experiences</li>\r\n<li>Men / women\'s grooming</li>\r\n<li>Family spending quality time together</li>\r\n<li>Children or toddlers at play</li>\r\n<li>Teenagers doing sporting activities</li>\r\n<li>Woman expressing, health, vitality and wellbeing</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Remember - cast your subjects appropriately with your chosen theme in mind.</p>\r\n<p>To bring life to your photos, add expression, humour, feeling, quirkiness, props, colour or movement.</p>\r\n<p>Be adventurous, creative and bold - have fun with your models and allow the spontaneous, natural moments to flow!</p>',18,7,NULL,'2015-03-28 15:50:26','2015-03-28 15:50:26'),(82,175,'LIFE & STYLE: Getting the Most From Your Picture','','<p>For this final assignment the theme is working with the qualities of your unique environment for conceptualising and creating your lifestyle photographs.</p>\r\n<p>Allow this to be your source of inspiration, added with your original artistic style and a bountiful amount of imagination!</p>\r\n<p>Take some time to look at your surroundings, from different angles and perspectives.</p>\r\n<p>Perhaps even explore and discover new and interesting locations. Observe also people and their natural interactions in these environments to be another source of ideas in conceptualising your photo shoot.<br /> <br />Anything from an intricate architectural detail or texture which creates a stylish backdrop to a wide open dreamy beach scene bathed in late afternoon light as the perfect lifestyle setting.</p>\r\n<p>Choose three separate locations that are all completely diverse from one another.</p>\r\n<p>Choose them for the quality that they will have individually in enhancing your images.</p>\r\n<p>For example:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>A beautiful setting in nature</li>\r\n<li>Dynamic architectural details</li>\r\n<li>Textures in nature</li>\r\n<li>Patterns and form in an urban scene</li>\r\n<li>Simplicity or monotones within your environment</li>\r\n<li>Quality of light</li>\r\n<li>Dimension</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Upload 5 photographs from the 3 individual settings.</p>\r\n<p>Be adventurous and imaginative and most of all have fun exploring and have fun with your subjects!</p>',17,7,NULL,'2015-03-28 15:57:26','2015-03-28 15:57:26'),(83,176,'Camera Settings for Your First Shoot','','<p>This assignment is designed to help you understand how to use your camera. You will be photographing the same image in various ways. I suggest you keep all of these experiments as personal reference material.</p>\r\n<p>1. Choose a scene and using the same composition, shoot at apertures of f22, f8, and the lowest your lens will allow. Compare the sharpness from front to back in each image.</p>\r\n<p>2. Select your next location and shoot the same composition in every white balance choice you have. Compare the color difference in each one.</p>\r\n<p>3. Move to another site and shoot the same scene in a variety of compositions. Get low and shoot up, get high and shoot down. Divide your landscape into thirds instead of in half. Try vertical as well as horizontal compositions.</p>\r\n<p>4. At another location, shoot the same scene without your polarizer and then again with it. Slowly turn it all the way around to find the best color enhancement. Remember, polarizers work best when at a 90 degree angle to the sun. If you are shooting when the sun is directly overhead, or coming straight at you, it will not work.</p>\r\n<p>5. Find your last scene and shoot the it in the highest number ISO and the lowest number ISO you camera allows. Notice the difference in noise (grain).</p>\r\n<p>Once you have your shots, upload two images from each experiment for review and critique. Tell us what settings you used and which one you think was most successful.</p>',7,0,NULL,'2015-03-30 08:21:33','2015-03-30 08:56:27'),(84,177,'Timing - Right Place, Right Moment','','<p>Assignment #2 will expand upon the experiments you tried in Lesson #1. Use your tests as guides for choosing your apertures, lenses, and equipment. Use your aperture priority for these shots to define how to best tell the story of the location.</p>\r\n<p>1. Find a location that gives off an emotion. It can be a busy lake, a quiet hillside, a peaceful grove of trees, or a misty beach. It could even be your own backyard. Photograph it using an aperture that presents the main subject of your story in the landscape to its fullest. Compose your shots both horizontally and vertically. Think about your ISO. If you have a scene you want to present very clearly, use a low number ISO. If you want to portray a soft, moody foggy scene, you could use a higher ISO to add some grain, enhancing the overall mood.</p>\r\n<p>2. Choose another location where you expect some sort of action to take place. It could be a path where bicycles are, a lake where animals visit, or a stream with fishermen. Photograph it when it is very still, and there is no sign of activity, then again when there is action. Patience is important here. Wait for the right moment to press the shutter button. Which image do you like better?</p>\r\n<p>3. Moving to another place, photograph it at different angles. Try putting your main subject in the center of your photo, then recompose it so that the subject is to the right of the frame and again towards the left. Tilt your camera up and take a shot, then down and take it again. Do you like more ground in the photo or more sky? Which tells your story best?</p>\r\n<p>4. Find a place that is not too far from home so you can visit several times. Photograph it at different times of the day. How does the mood change from morning throughout the day into evening? Remember to adjust your white balance and ISO if necessary. Use your polarizer when appropriate.</p>\r\n<p>Try your best to find things about the landscapes that are unusual. Things you have not seen before. Go back through your first assignments and use what you learned to make the best possible shots you can. Don\'t forget about your polarizer to cut down on glare and enhance colors. Take time to set up your tripod and check that the horizon line is straight.</p>\r\n<p>When you have completed your shots, upload two from each experiment for review and critique. Tell us what attracted you to the scene and which images you think were most successful.</p>',18,7,NULL,'2015-03-30 08:22:54','2015-03-30 08:55:00'),(85,178,'Catch That Light!','','<p>Your third assignment will combine all of the camera techniques you have encountered as well as train your eye to to find the best types of light to enhance the features of your subject. Keep the following things in mind as you shoot. Does the light create a mood? What story am I trying to tell? What aperture best describes the story? Is the sky interesting? If not, crop it out. Would your image look best in a horizontal or vertical format? Remember to use your polarizer when appropriate and do the same if you have a warming filter. Use your white balance setting to best enhance the overall feeling of the photo.</p>\r\n<p>1. Get up early. Go to a location to photograph it at sunrise. Try the following experiments. Shoot a few frames before the light appears on your subject to compare it to when the light hits. When the light casts its golden hue, shoot quickly, because it doesn\'t last long. You have about 20 minutes of optimum light. After that, you will still have good photos, but as the sun gets higher, it becomes more of a white light, and you need to add the glow in PhotoShop. Remember to adjust your ISO between before sunrise and after sunrise shots. The darker the light, the higher your ISO needs to be or your shutter speed may be too long to prevent noise.</p>\r\n<p>2. Visit a location in the middle of the day. Hopefully, you can find a spot with water to see the effect on the color. If not, shoot whatever you can to discover the contrasts that exist. Look for patterns and strong angles to add a graphic element to the image.</p>\r\n<p>3. Find a place that will look good in late afternoon. Somewhere with people or things that will cast long shadows. Sometimes a location with a combination of man made buildings and natural land works well. A beach with a pier, meadow with houses dotting hills behind it, rocky desert, or a roadside with tall trees. Your goal is to catch the soft light with interesting shadows, and textural elements of the objects.</p>\r\n<p>4. If you encounter overcast or foggy days, sing a happy tune. You can shoot almost anything. Wildflower meadows, streams, rivers, waterfalls, barns, and beaches all work well. Your skill at telling a story must be especially strong with these kind of shots.</p>\r\n<p>5. Go watch the sunset. You get to have a lovely experience while working at the same time. Compose your shot to involve most of the sky if there are interesting clouds. If not, make the land your story. Shoot your location as the sun is setting, and keep shooting well after it drops below the horizon. This is another time you will need to adjust your ISO. Just as with the sunrise shots, your exposure time can become too long for your camera to handle the noise that comes with it.</p>\r\n<p>I realize you may not have the opportunity to shoot all of these types of light within our time frame. Unfortunately, we cannot have weather made to order. If you don\'t get all of the weather conditions, choose different locations with the light you get and notice the differences between the locations.</p>\r\n<p>When you finish your shooting, upload two from each experiment for review and critique. Make sure you tell us what type of light you encountered and what you were attracted to in the shots. If you don\'t get all types of light, choose a <strong>total of eight images</strong> to upload.</p>',18,7,NULL,'2015-03-30 08:25:25','2015-03-30 09:24:42'),(86,179,'Digital Post-Production Toning','','<p>Your final assignment is challenging. Here you will need to develop your artistic eye to objectively judge the quality of your shots. We tend to get caught up in the moment of image capture, remembering the sounds, sights and events we experienced while shooting. But that doesn\'t necessarily mean the shot is good. Look at photography books and magazines. Study the ingredients that make good images. Compare yours to theirs. Strive to achieve the best quality possible. Be objective about your photographs. Just because you took them does not automatically make them good. Professional photographers throw out many more images than they keep because their eyes have become trained to only accept the best. If you want to build a reputation as a good photographer, you can\'t put just any old image out there.</p>\r\n<p>Keep the following things in mind as you edit your photos.</p>\r\n<p>Are there any distracting elements that need to be cropped out? Is there too much dead space that should be cropped out?</p>\r\n<p>Is the exposure correct? Can the image benefit from bringing the exposure up or down?</p>\r\n<p>Is the image sharp? Would sharpening it help improve the overall look of the photo?</p>\r\n<p>Can the image use a lift from saturation?</p>\r\n<p>Using your best images from this course, choose 4 photos to enhance in your software program. Assess the images for sharpness, composition, exposure, and mood. Make adjustments to each image according to the suggestions in the lesson. Tell us which program you are working with and what changes you made. Upload the original file (compressed in jpg form) as well as the edited version for comparison.</p>\r\n<p>Choose 2 images to convert to black and white. Follow the steps in the lesson, making your changes carefully according to each image\'s needs. Upload the original color version as well as the converted black and white for comparison.</p>\r\n<p>Take your time with editing. Most photographers complain that they spend more time on the computer than they do shooting. This was true in the wet lab as well. Capturing the image is the first step. Making it sing is the next.</p>\r\n<p>Have fun, and show me a symphony with your edited photographs.</p>',17,7,NULL,'2015-03-30 08:26:45','2015-03-30 09:30:03'),(87,180,'Finding Your Subject - Possibilities Are Endless','','<p>Using your macro lens or camera&rsquo;s macro feature, and incorporating the techniques described above, practice shooting different subject matter from various distances and apertures. Your subjects can be from nature, machinery, toys, clothing, or anything else that has detail when viewed close up. Once you feel you have a handle on the technique, choose 8 of your best images to upload to TCI for comment and critique. Here is your guideline for choosing your images:</p>\r\n<p>From Nature, choose 4 images in the following categories:</p>\r\n<p>1 subject photographed horizontally at two different distances and apertures. One that shows a good deal of the subject, and one that is extremely close up. This can be 1\" if your lens allows it. If you can\'t get this close, just move in to the closest distance that allows you to still achieve a sharp focus. (2 photos)</p>\r\n<p>1 subject photographed vertically at two different distances and apertures. Same theory as above. (2 photos)</p>\r\n<p>1 image at extreme close up of your choice.</p>\r\n<p>From any subject matter that is not from the natural world, choose 4 images as described above.</p>\r\n<p>Please share with us why you chose your subject matter, and what part of the subject you wanted your viewer to focus on.</p>\r\n<p>Have fun discovering a whole new world!</p>',7,0,NULL,'2015-03-31 06:28:48','2015-04-17 07:58:37'),(88,181,'Reading the Light - Makes or Breaks the Picture','','<p>Take your macro lens or camera and look for different kinds of lighting conditions. Photograph any kind of object you find interesting. Flowers, door handles, the gears on a bicycle, even your own toes. Look at everything with the intention of studying and capturing the light that best enhances your object. Feel free to set up a lighting situation of your own if you like. Practice, practice, practice!</p>\r\n<p>After the first assignment, you should be familiar with how close you can get to a subject with your lens or camera&rsquo;s macro feature. Choose your distance relative to its capabilities and with the ￼ idea of getting one image of the whole object, and one as close as possible to create a pleasing composition.</p>\r\n<p>Once you have photographed your subjects, pick your 9 best images to upload to TCI for comment and critique. The guidelines for your images should be as follows:</p>\r\n<p>2 subjects photographed horizontally at two different distances and apertures. One that shows a good deal of the subject, and one that is extremely close up. This can be 1\" if your lens allows it. If you can\'t get this close, just move in to the closest distance that allows you to still achieve a sharp focus. (4 photos)</p>\r\n<p>2 subjects photographed vertically at two different distances and apertures. Same theory as above. (4 photos)</p>\r\n<p>1 image at extreme close up of your choice.</p>\r\n<p>I hope the light shines perfectly for you. Good luck and I look forward to seeing your images.</p>',18,7,NULL,'2015-03-31 06:44:06','2015-04-17 08:02:40'),(89,182,'Composition - Ordinary versus Dynamic','','<p>Please use the lighting lessons you learned in the last lesson while setting up your objects, but if you cannot get perfect lighting, concentrate more on your composition. If you are indoors,take your time setting up your objects. If you are outdoors photographing nature, walk around until you find the best point of view. Try many different angles and distances. By now, you have experimented with your macro lens enough to see just how close and how far you can get. Notice how the story of the object changes depending on the distance you choose to photography it from.</p>\r\n<p>Consider the best camera settings to use depending on your conditions. What white balance and aperture enhances your object the most?</p>\r\n<p>Photograph the following assignment:</p>\r\n<p>The rule of thirds. You may shoot different subjects, or the same one from a different angle.</p>\r\n<p>Leading lines. Please photograph different subjects and experiment with different directions of the lines.</p>\r\n<p>Symmetry. Please photograph different subjects and look for subtle differences in the symmetry that create interesting tension.</p>\r\n<p>Unusual point of view. You can shoot the same object or a different ones. If you choose to photograph the same subject, make sure the point of view in each photograph is equally interesting - no straight on shots allowed.</p>\r\n<p>Balance. Please photograph different subjects and look for the weight distribution within your composition.</p>\r\n<p>Once you have photographed your subjects, pick two of the best images from each category (total of 10) to upload to TCI for comment and critique. Please tell us why you chose each composition, and if there are any other compositional elements at play in the image.</p>\r\n<p>Good luck and have fun.</p>',18,7,NULL,'2015-03-31 06:45:28','2015-03-31 06:56:06'),(90,183,'Depth of Field - Storytelling Emphasis & Precision','','<p>1. Choose one subject that has several planes from front to back and photograph it in the following manner:</p>\r\n<p>One aperture with a shallow depth of field (low number) photographed with three different focal points (3 images total).</p>\r\n<p>One aperture with a medium depth of field (f8) photographed with three different focal points (3 images total).</p>\r\n<p>One aperture with a deep depth of field (high number) photographed with three different focal points (3 images total).</p>\r\n<p>Compare the difference of apertures and focal points. You will notice a dramatic difference with the shallow depth of field, less difference with the medium, and perhaps none<br />at all with the deep depth of field, depending on how many planes your subject has and how high an f-stop you choose. Keep these images as comparison references.</p>\r\n<p>2. Find a subject that will allow you to make a beautiful, artistic, extreme close up. Flowers, insects, weathered toys, or bicycle spokes will work well, but use your imagination.&nbsp; Get as close as you can with your lens, and open the aperture as far as it will go (use a small number f-stop). See how much you can make it look like a painting without obscuring the identity of the object.</p>\r\n<p>3. Look for a subject that will work best when photographed with a deep depth of field.&nbsp; You could line up jelly beans or marbles. Flower beds are prime candidates, too. The<br />subject should be something that you want to have in focus from front to back. Choose an aperture of f11 or higher and see how much you can keep in focus.</p>\r\n<p>4. Choose a subject that will tell your story best with a medium depth of field. Whatever you choose should have an interesting focal point, with some interest around it that<br />helps to define your story, but not so much that it gets lost. Think back to the image of the martini glass and the blue antique bottle. Use an aperture between f5.0 and f8.</p>\r\n<p>Keep the last lesson on composition in mind when you are constructing your images.&nbsp; Composition is very important in macro photograph.</p>\r\n<p>When you are finished, upload one image from each section of this assignment for review and critique. Good luck, and enjoy yourself.</p>',17,7,NULL,'2015-03-31 06:49:30','2015-03-31 06:58:46'),(91,184,'Establishing a Photographic Context','','<p>Now it\'s your turn! For this assignment, please have a shoot where you have a body of imagery to edit. I would recommend at least 30-50 images from a particular shoot. If you need images to work with, go out over the weekend and find an event of interest or stage a portrait shoot with a nearby subject.</p>\r\n<p><strong>1)</strong> Upload a screen shot of your editing process, with at least 15 images from a shoot so I can see what you are working with to start. This can be anything from a sporting event, to a portrait shoot, environmental landscapes or fashion photography. The content is your choice -- it just needs to be something that has enough takes that we can take a good stab at applying our editing skills to.</p>\r\n<p><strong>2)</strong> Upload 5 images that are similar to one another that you feel are the best from the shoot.</p>\r\n<p><strong>3) </strong>Upload your final choice out of the selected five best images that you feel is the most powerful, and explain why.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Don\'t forget to please provide a context for your imagery</strong> -- simple caption information as text works, or please use your metadata options, inserting any notes or caption info into your \'file info.\'</p>',7,0,NULL,'2015-03-31 13:21:03','2015-03-31 13:22:20'),(92,185,'Applying a Critical Eye','','<p>This assignment will ask you to either work with a previously shot assignment or project, or, to shoot a simple project keeping the \"storytelling shot list\" in mind. You can work with these six ideas, including additional images from any of the categories, if necessary. Do not exceed 10 images. Try to keep your story simple for now. Your essay\'s imagery should be able to tell the story with minimal caption information -- it should be the clarity of the photos themselves that will allow for your reader to easily comprehend the subject matter.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Things to keep in mind.</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Consistency: Keep the consistency of your post- production images so that they flow together comfortably in tone, color, contrast, and identify or brand your unique photography style.</li>\r\n<li>Although you are looking to create a fluid, dynamic story, the story does not have to be exactly linear.</li>\r\n<li>Provide caption information for each image as part of your upload.</li>\r\n<li>Less is more.</li>\r\n<li>Only use images that tell the story or compliment details that fill the story; edit out the images that don\'t fit the story, even if they are great shots. There will be another place for them as singles or in another project later.</li>\r\n</ul>',18,7,NULL,'2015-03-31 13:27:59','2015-03-31 13:27:59'),(93,187,'Edit to Tell the Story','','<p><strong>1)</strong> Upload up 2 batches of up to 15 images each (30 images total). They can be from a singles, travel, documentary, or reportage portfolio. You can also send a link to any work up to 2 portfolios or projects, totaling no more than 30 images.</p>\r\n<p><strong>2)</strong> Send any relevant text or caption information.</p>\r\n<p><strong>3)</strong> After reviewing your uploaded images, I will send you my written feedback. In addition, I will then arrange an appropriate one-on-one Skype or&nbsp; consultation about your work. (Not to exceed 30 minutes).</p>',17,7,NULL,'2015-03-31 13:37:51','2015-03-31 13:37:51'),(94,186,'Singles and Stand-Alone Sequences','','<p>This assignment is in two parts. It aims to help you to identify singles on their own as well and to organize thematic work. We are looking to identify singles on their own, but by placing them in a sequence, we will understand the visual relationship they share with one another.&nbsp; <br /><br /><strong>1)</strong> Upload 5-8 singles for a category specific portfolio. The type of portfolio is your choice, depending on your work. It will be categorized under travel, sport, fashion, reportage, documentary, etc.<br />The singles selected should flow together and fit thematically in the category you choose using the tips learned in the lesson. Keep any relevant caption information in the file info. Do not upload 5 images from a photo essay.</p>\r\n<p><strong>2)</strong> Upload 10 singles for a portfolio called \"SINGLES\" and incorporate at least 3 of the images you used for first half of the assignment. The images in the SINGLES portfolio should flow together visually. They do not have to work thematically.&nbsp; Sequence the work using the sequencing tips listed above.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>2a</strong> (optional) Explain why you chose your sequence for each image.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><br /><strong>Things to keep in mind:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>1)</strong> Get organized. Decide which body of work you want to extract singles from and place them in a separate folder on your desk top. If you are taking singles from many different bodies of work create appropriate folders and save accordingly</p>\r\n<p><strong>2)</strong> Don\'t be afraid to switch gears. If images begin to look repetitive, or if you start choosing a 20 image edit out of a 25 image, take a break. You are looking to cull the size of your work down</p>\r\n<p><strong>3)</strong> When you are working on a singles sequence, identify when images do not work next to one another. If an image does not look right next to another, do not worry. One of the images might have to be cut. There will be another time and place to use the cut image, but placing within a context of other images that don\'t work will make the quality of the other work appear less strong. </p>',18,7,NULL,'2015-03-31 13:39:26','2015-03-31 13:39:26'),(95,188,'Qualities of Outdoor Light','','<p>For your first assignment, I want you to experiment with different kinds of lighting techniques. Photograph two or three separate scenes under at least two different lighting conditions, using the examples that we\'ve covered above. The subjects can be landscapes, people; whatever sparks your interest, and you might need to visit the scene more than once to get your desired results. Try to make shoot at least one of your scenes during the \"magic hours.\" When you\'ve completed the assignment, <strong>upload six images</strong> for critique. Have fun with this first assignment!</p>',7,0,NULL,'2015-04-01 07:40:31','2015-04-01 07:59:53'),(96,189,'Capturing Landscapes','','<p>For this assignment, I want you to practice shooting landscapes. Find a few scenes that spark your interest and photograph them using different lenses, techniques and creative ideas. Think bold and dynamic with your compositions and then focus on capturing your landscapes in the most visually powerful way that you can. When you have completed the assignment, <strong>upload six images</strong> for critique. Good luck!</p>',18,7,NULL,'2015-04-01 07:43:09','2015-04-01 08:10:42'),(97,190,'Photographing People in the Natural World','','<p>For this assignment, I want you to go out and photograph people in the outdoors. I want to see a mix of action shots and shots of people interacting with the landscape. Experiment with different lenses, vantage points, and activities, and strive to combine the two types of shots into a strong image that conveys both action and a sense of place. When you have finished with the assignment, <strong>upload six of your best examples</strong>.</p>',18,7,NULL,'2015-04-01 07:45:14','2015-04-01 08:13:20'),(98,191,'Creativity is Key','','<p>Shooting more creatively. For this assignment, I want you to choose three or four different scenes or subjects and take a quick snapshot of the scene. Then spend sometime thinking about what attracts you to each scene and how you\'d like to portray it in a single image, and then get to work creating that image.</p>\r\n<p>Shoot a variety of frames using some of the different techniques that we\'ve covered above. Vary backgrounds, play around with framing and empty space and shoot from different vantage points. Work your scenes and try different compositional approaches until you feel you have created a strong image that matches your own idea about the scene. When you have finished with the assignment, <strong>upload your initial snapshots of each scene as well as your \"final inspired images\" of each scene</strong>.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',17,7,NULL,'2015-04-01 07:46:35','2015-04-01 08:15:44'),(99,192,'Submit Your Portfolio for Critique','','<p>Upload your 12 images <strong>or</strong> two multimedia / video pieces and any text that you wish to include.&nbsp; Ami will review and provide a critique of each and contact you to arrange a convenient time for Skype discussion of your work.</p>',7,0,NULL,'2015-04-01 13:59:45','2015-04-01 13:59:45'),(100,193,'Submit Your Portfolio for Critique','','<p>Upload your 12 images <strong>or</strong> two multimedia / video pieces and any text that you wish to include.&nbsp; Bob will review and provide a critique of each and contact you to arrange a convenient time for Skype discussion of your work.</p>',7,0,NULL,'2015-04-01 14:01:13','2015-04-01 14:01:13'),(101,194,'Submit Your Portfolio for Critique','','<p>Upload your 12 images and any text that you wish to include (optional).&nbsp; \"Akash\" will review and provide a critique of each and contact you to arrange a convenient time for Skype discussion of your work.</p>',7,0,NULL,'2015-04-01 14:42:06','2015-04-01 14:42:06'),(102,195,'Capturing Magic Moments','','<p>Your assignment is to choose a subject and location and to shoot five images that capture the child, aiming for a magic moment with expression in the eyes, and images of the child interacting with the environment such as playing in a playground or dancing about or simply standing or sitting. Keep in mind the graphic elements of the photos and limit the visual distractions. In subsequent assignments we will have concepts, props, and cover various age groups as well as doubles shots and families, but for now let&rsquo;s get in the habit of watching the eyes and expressions and to bringing the child&rsquo;s personality out in your shots.</p>',7,0,NULL,'2015-04-02 07:33:20','2015-04-05 13:02:07'),(103,196,'Infants & Small Children: A Special Dynamic','','<p>Your assignment is to find a subject under the age of five and to shoot five images of the child in a suitable environment where they can play and be well lit at the same time. Try to achieve images that are very authentic to their age group, looking for natural movements, playfulness, and innocence. Organize yourself so that you are ready to follow them, considering the height and angles at which you shoot. Be prepared technically so that you can be free to concentrate to on capturing the image as quickly as they happen. Don&rsquo;t forget about twinkly eyes, dimples, and chubbiness &ndash; all very cute in this age group. Aim to capture their delight in the world around them.</p>',18,7,NULL,'2015-04-02 07:38:44','2015-04-05 13:03:35'),(104,197,' Team Creation with \"Tweens\" and Teens','','<p>Your assignment is to shoot five images with kids between ages six and twenty, depending on the kids available to you. Take into consideration who they are as a person, what sorts of things they like to do, and their personality. Choose the location and their attire based on the kid. Consider your angles and composition and take advantage of your surroundings. If you have a sporty subject, try an action shot or two. Engage the subject in the process so that you work as a team to get the best images possible.</p>',18,7,NULL,'2015-04-02 07:40:26','2015-04-05 13:15:35'),(105,198,'Developing Your Style as a Childrens Photographer','','<p>You assignment is to art-direct and execute a shoot. First create a mood board to inspire you. Scout a location and note the time of day that will suit your planned images. Cast the child and plan the styling based on the concept. Shoot a series of four images that show a clear idea and creative vision. Direct the child to get the level of interaction with the camera that works for your story. Edit your images to those that illustrate your concept and story. Shoot color or black and white, or even mix the two in the story for visual impact. Your &ldquo;story&rdquo; should be clear in the images. The possibilities are only as limited as your own imagination. Enjoy the creative freedom to tell your story!</p>',17,7,NULL,'2015-04-02 07:45:12','2015-04-05 13:22:25'),(106,199,'Planning Your Shoot','','<p>Find one or two potential stories suitable for a VERY short (3-7 minute) documentary, and have a Skype discussion with me about it. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Then write an introduction that demonstrates the research you have done, and produce an outline detailing what your film will look like:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Sources:</strong> Who do you need to talk to? Have you contacted them yet?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Important <strong>story angles</strong>. Points and counterpoints.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Visual elements:</strong> In particular, identify the main sequences that you will need to tell your story, plus any additional visuals.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Graphics:</strong> Any graphics or stills you have or need to find or need to produce.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Timetable:</strong> Note any issues about schedule such as availability of your subjects, etc.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><em>All photos and text copyright Tobie Openshaw - all rights reserved worldwide. No form of reproduction or usage - including copying, altering, or saving of digital image and text files - is permitted without the express written permission of </em><em><em>Tobie Openshaw</em> and thecompellingimage.com. </em><br /><br /><em>&copy; </em><em><em>Tobie Openshaw</em>. All rights reserved.</em></p>',7,0,NULL,'2015-04-06 13:17:32','2015-04-07 09:23:27'),(107,200,'Clean Audio and Effective Lighting','','<p>By now, you should have 15-20 minutes of b-roll of footage for your final project. For this week\'s assignment, you will need to:</p>\r\n<p><strong>1) </strong>Conduct at least two interviews about your topic. Shoot one interview indoors using either natural light coming in from a window or using a key light, and shoot one interview outdoors using natural light. If you don\'t have a reflector don\'t worry, but remember the tips above for filming outdoors either in the morning or evening or if it\'s an overcast day.</p>\r\n<p><strong>2)</strong> Collect natural sound for your project. Concentrate on getting really good audio. Record at least a minute of interesting ambient sound (birds chirping, a crowd cheering), and get close to your subject to get 3-4 good crisp sounds like a bell ringing or a shovel being plowed into the dirt.</p>\r\n<p><strong>3)</strong> Start writing your script. If you have 15-20 minutes of good b-roll, 1-2 interviews and some good natural sound, the filming portion of your story is complete. Write a rough draft of your script, referring back to Lesson #1 on how to write a video script. Your script should note visuals and should identify which interview quotes will be used.&nbsp; Here is a guide to what a documentary script should look like:</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.google.com/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=9&amp;sqi=2&amp;ved=0CHQQFjAI&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.chicagomediaworks.com%2F2instructworks%2F3editing_doc%2F3docedit_scriptmpl%2Fdocs2col.doc&amp;ei=FnPzUorXPMvbkAWy_YDIBQ&amp;usg=AFQjCNFO-zf5r8DHyjmUss0FUsnECt_fAQ&amp;sig2=27Xdy8HTd5vGgmL2RwJefw\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><strong>4) </strong></span>http://www.google.com/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=9&amp;sqi=2&amp;ved=0CHQQFjAI&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.chicagomediaworks.com%2F2instructworks%2F3editing_doc%2F3docedit_scriptmpl%2Fdocs2col.doc&amp;ei=FnPzUorXPMvbkAWy_YDIBQ&amp;usg=AFQjCNFO-zf5r8DHyjmUss0FUsnECt_fAQ&amp;sig2=27Xdy8HTd5vGgmL2RwJefw</a></p>\r\n<p><strong>5) </strong>Watch the beginning of this documentary about Che Guevara and note the use of natural and enhanced sound.&nbsp; <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=g-ZJAS_ZzKU&amp;list=PL634E6314EF8070DB%20\">http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=g-ZJAS_ZzKU&amp;list=PL634E6314EF8070DB </a></p>\r\n<p><strong>6) </strong>Discuss this Lesson with your Classmates and Instructor.</p>',21,7,NULL,'2015-04-06 13:31:59','2015-04-07 09:25:46'),(108,202,'The Visual Story: Camera Work and Compostion','','<p>Phew, there was a lot of information in this lesson. When you first start shooting it will feel a bit overwhelming to remember all of the 10 lessons as well as the rules of composition. But with enough practice these rules will become second nature, and then you can worry about the other elements of video (like lighting and audio). Here\'s what I want you do to by next week.</p>\r\n<p><strong>1.</strong> Spend 15-20 minutes shooting in-camera sequences. This means you should have a nice sequence without having to do any editing. Find an action and shoot wide (hold for 10 seconds then stop recording), move closer for a medium shot (hold for 10 seconds then stop recording), move even closer for a close up (hold for 10 seconds then stop recording) and move even closer for an extreme close up (hold for 10 seconds then stop recording). Do 3-4 of these, and each one get more creative in the order you do your shots and the angles with which you compose them.</p>\r\n<p><strong>2.</strong> Spend 20-30 minutes filming for your project that you storyboarded in Lesson #1. Use all of the rules of cinematography that we discussed as well as the rules of composition. Be mindful of sequences, but you\'ll be able to edit this film so you don\'t have to be as precise as in the previous exercise.</p>\r\n<p><strong>3.</strong> Write down your experience in both exercises to me (unless you already know how to upload videos to YouTube, then you could send links to some of the in-camera sequences). Was it more difficult than you expected? Easier than expected? What was the biggest surprise while filming? What was the biggest challenge?</p>\r\n<p><strong>4.</strong> Watch \"<a href=\"http://mediastorm.com/training/beautiful-noise\">Beautiful Noise</a>,\" a compelling mini-documentary done by students at a MediaStorm workshop in New York City in 2008. Pay attention to use of sequences, story arc and pacing.</p>',21,7,NULL,'2015-04-06 13:38:51','2015-04-07 09:21:10'),(109,201,'Putting It All Together','','<p>x</p>',21,4,'2015-04-06 13:40:22','2015-04-06 13:40:03','2015-04-06 13:40:22'),(110,201,'Putting It All Together','','<p>Okay, this is it. It\'s time to put your masterpiece together. By now you should have all of your footage shot and your tape logged. I\'d like you to construct a 1-2 minute video keeping in mind dramatic structure, rhythm and pacing, proper use of transitions and proper use of effects. You will not use every editing convention discussed in this lesson on your first video. Because your video will be short, you will most likely just use straight cuts for your shots (there shouldn\'t be any need for big, thematic transitions in a 1-2 minute piece). But it\'s here because I wanted you to be aware of all the tools available to you as an editor.</p>\r\n<p>In reality, you have two weeks to work on your final cut. The next lesson is about exporting and sharing your video project, so the final assignment will be for you to post your finished work to the video sharing service of your choice.</p>\r\n<p>Good luck, have fun, and as always, if you feel you need to talk through an edit or you\'re just having difficulty figuring out where to start, please e-mail me any questions. I\'ll also be available for live Skype chats (ulead-tobie) - we\'ll just need to schedule a time. Just let me know what you\'d like to discuss and when you are most likely to be available.</p>',21,7,NULL,'2015-04-06 13:40:13','2015-04-07 09:28:16'),(111,203,'Distribution','','<p><strong>CONCLUSION:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Well, thank you very much for going on this ride with me.&nbsp; I hope that you feel you have created something worthwhile and that this will stimulate you to develop your skills further.&nbsp; (Yes, there will be an &ldquo;Advanced&rdquo; class in the future)&nbsp; Feel free to stay in touch and share with me your future endeavors.</p>\r\n<p>P.S When you do post your video production on either YouTube or Vimeo, post the url here and I\'ll get back to you with my final comments.</p>',20,7,NULL,'2015-04-06 13:41:57','2015-04-07 09:31:34'),(112,204,'Creating Dynamic Abstract Compositions','','<p>Using your zoom lens and the techniques described above, practice with different subject matter to make your in-camera abstracts. Try subjects from nature as well as creating your own still lifes. Once you feel you have a handle on the technique, <strong>choose 10 of your best images to upload</strong> to TCI for comment and critique. Here is your guideline for choosing your images:</p>\r\n<p>From Nature, choose <strong>5 images</strong> in the following categories:<br />1 horizontal image with color as the main emphasis<br />1 horizontal image with texture as the main emphasis<br />1 horizontal image of your choice<br />1 vertical image with color as the main emphasis<br />1 vertical image with texture as the main emphasis</p>\r\n<p>From a Still Life, choose <strong>5 images</strong> as described above.</p>\r\n<p>Please let us know what the original subject matter was because we may not be able to tell. It is great fun to discover the transformation from literal subject to abstract can be.</p>\r\n<p>Keep in mind, the more you play with the zoom technique, the more quickly you will master it. Good luck, have fun, and don\'t be afraid to try different subjects and zoom speeds.</p>',7,0,NULL,'2015-04-08 12:06:14','2015-04-08 12:54:44'),(113,205,'Adding Atmospheric Emotion','','<p>Using your piece of glass and Vaseline, along with the techniques covered in this week\'s lesson, practice with different subjects.&nbsp; The aim is to transform your photos from average to <em>mood inspiring.&nbsp; </em>Try subjects from nature, as well as from ordinary objects around your house.&nbsp; Once you feel you\'ve got a solid grasp of this technique, <strong>choose 6 of your best images to upload</strong> to the TCI website for comment and critique.</p>\r\n<p>Here is your guideline for choosing images:</p>\r\n<p>From nature, choose <strong>3 images</strong> in the following categories:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>1 photo with motion created by streaks</li>\r\n<li>1 photo with the feeling of a rainy day</li>\r\n<li>1 photo with the center more in focus than the edges</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>From ordinary objects, choose also<strong> 3 images</strong> from the categories above.</p>\r\n<p>Lastly, be sure to upload your original photo of each subject as it was before applying the Vaseline technique, so the difference can be seen.</p>\r\n<p>Have fun, experiment extensively and try all different kinds of subject matter.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',18,7,NULL,'2015-04-08 12:07:49','2015-04-08 12:57:57'),(114,206,'Overexposure - On Purpose','','<p>Choose a variety of subjects. Perhaps an interesting building, a portrait of someone you know, a landscape, books on a bookshelf, coffee beans, just about anything you want. Photograph two of your chosen subjects with properly exposed technique, then overexpose them in your software editing program. Upload both versions for critique. Then, shoot two more subjects in-camera using your camera&rsquo;s exposure compensation. Upload these two for comment and critique as well. Please explain your experiences with each method. Which one do you prefer?</p>',18,7,NULL,'2015-04-08 12:12:55','2015-05-10 11:09:56'),(115,207,'Vintage Look','','<p>Choose photographs from your library or take new ones for this assignment. Pick a landscape, a portrait, and a random image of your choice. Think about what will work best with each type of technique, polaroid, cyanotype, and Carte de Visite.</p>\r\n<p>Play around with the described techniques. Your settings will vary from mine, because your photographs are different. Just as in the previous lesson, each image is like a human being. We all look and act individually. We all need to be handled unique people, and so do your images. There is no formula. I have just provided guidelines.</p>\r\n<p>Once you feel you have a handle on the techniques, <strong>choose 3 of your best images to upload</strong> to TCI for comment and critique. I am only asking for 3 images for this lesson because I want you to tell me the steps you took to achieve your results. This takes time, so one example of each technique is enough.</p>\r\n<p>Please upload each original photo before manipulation so we can see the difference. It is great fun to see the starting and ending points.</p>\r\n<p>Your adventure awaits. Keep an open mind and play around with your settings until you get results you like.</p>',17,7,NULL,'2015-04-08 12:16:21','2015-04-08 13:28:29'),(116,208,'Mentorship Stage 1','','<p><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><strong><em>TO BE ASSIGNED</em></strong></span></p>',7,0,NULL,'2015-04-09 15:49:48','2015-04-09 15:49:48'),(117,209,'Mentorship Stage 2','','<p><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><em><strong>TO BE ASSIGNED</strong></em></span></p>',17,7,NULL,'2015-04-09 15:52:46','2015-04-09 15:52:46'),(118,211,'Step 1','','<p><span style=\"font-size: 13px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: bold; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Step 1 Assignment &ndash; Research</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 13px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">I&rsquo;d like you to do a little research so we can establish your visual voice. We are both on the same page that you needed creative direction, as well as content to support your marketing goals.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 13px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: bold; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Phase 1</span><strong><span style=\"font-size: 13px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">:</span></strong></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 13px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">I want to see what kind of style you are connecting with &ndash; so I recommend creating a few boards on Pinterest dividing them in the categories you would like to divide your portfolio in the end. </span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 13px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Food prep (raw, ingredients, spices, pre-cooked)</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 13px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Savory dishes (cooked dishes, appetizers and main courses, breakfast dishes, etc.)</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 13px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Desserts</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 13px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Beverages</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 13px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Collect pictures (you can add your own too &ndash; mark them as your own) and think about the color palette, subject matter, composition, use of props, lighting and overall feel of the imagery.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 13px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: bold; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Phase 2:<br /></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 13px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">I want you now to write down your positioning statement &ndash; this might seem a little early and I am sure we will edit this many times as we move along - but I want us to use this as the guiding light in the edit and the shooting portion of the programme.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 13px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: bold; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Phase 3:<br /></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 13px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Now I want you to go back to YOUR own existing images and create a Pinterest board using those with the positioning statement in mind. From here we can address the gaps that you are missing to get you started on the cooking and shooting.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 13px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Have fun! Keep me updated as you move along with the phases so I can see where you are going. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><em><strong>&nbsp;</strong></em></span></p>',7,0,NULL,'2015-04-09 16:04:45','2015-05-21 07:25:47'),(119,212,'Step 2','','<p><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><strong><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Step 2 Assignment &ndash; Selecting &amp; Creating Images</span></strong><br /><br /><span style=\"color: #000000;\">So from the last assignment it was probably a bit of a reality check to see what one&rsquo;s goals are vs. what content one has that matches that goal. What we are now going to do is address the gaps that you are missing to get us started on the shooting. This will take a few weeks so do not be discouraged. In the end we might not use every single image you shoot over the next weeks but we will aim to select 20 of the best ones. </span><br /><span style=\"color: #000000;\">I have tried to work out a schedule, which we can optimize together. If it&rsquo;s too ambitious let me know and we can scale it down a bit. </span><br /><br /><span style=\"color: #000000;\">After viewing your general boards vs. your boards is that many of your shots have a horizontal orientation whereas the images in your general boards are vertical. If you remember I mentioned this in the workshop that a vertical orientation is often a nicer way to go with food photography as it allows you to play around more with the DOF and build a deeper set. </span><br /></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">So let us focus on vertical orientation for the images &ndash; but please do take some in the horizontal orientation too. </span><br />&nbsp;<br /><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Based on your categories I&rsquo;d like you to take at least 4 images per week. We will start simple with ingredients and for these I will give a few (easy) recipes for you to create cooked meals with. You are to shoot simple ingredient shots, food prep and then the cooked meal. Are you OK with this? </span><br />&nbsp;<br /><span style=\"color: #000000;\">What I plan to do is go back to your general boards + use some of my boards and simply highlight an image I think you could be inspired by. In the comment field I will write your name @reef fakhoury so you get a message which image I mean. What you are to do is to study the image and interpret it by keeping your analysis of what you connect with in mind. Build / set-up your shot according your &ldquo;Connect list&rdquo; below:</span><br /></span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">I connect most with very \'styled\' story telling images which incorporate the ingredients and suitable props.</span></span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">The theme of the dish, ingredient or drink is usually evident by the way the styling is done (for example summer dish, christmas dish, etc). The theme is also usually evident in the location in which the image is taken</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Side lighting is my prefered lighting (my eye is usually drawn to shots that are side lit more so than back lit)</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">45 degree angle is my preferred angle and I relate to food shots taken from this angle (seemingly) more than other angles</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Close-up shots (tight) are a preference it seems</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Dark backdrops, boards and props with a well lit subject seems to be recurrent in my selection</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Action shots are very appealing as well (drinks poured, sugar dusted, sauce drizzled, etc)</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Harmonious colors are appealing to my eye more than contrasting or complimentary colors apparently</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">The list above is a great set of guidelines for you to consider every time you shoot. But do not get stuck up with, for example, side lighting &ndash; after you have taken your desired shot just move the set up around so you have back lighting and take a shot with this direction of light. Remember we want to show versatility. </span><br /><br /><span style=\"color: #000000;\">I hope this makes sense. </span><br /><br /><span style=\"color: #000000;\">I have listed a few items and recipes (keeping it simple) but if you do not like the recipe or have another one you would like to try go ahead. In some I have listed an idea/suggestion which you might not have to cook yourself but maybe if you know a good restaurant etc. you can always get it from there (e.g. mezzeh). Please use this as a rough guideline and by all means be creative with other ingredients. By no way are you required to complete them all if you lack the time &ndash; on the other hand if you need more ;) then let me know. </span><br /><br /><strong><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Categories: </span></strong></span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Food prep (raw, ingredients, spices, pre-cooked)</span></span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Spices</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Asparagus</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Herbs (Mint, Coriander, Flat leaf parsley &ndash; Arabic / Basil, Thyme, Rosmarin, Dill &ndash; European)</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Strawberries</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Figs</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Raspberries&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Bread&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Eggs</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Tomatoes&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Aubergine</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Garlic</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Cauliflower</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Savory dishes (cooked dishes, appetizers and main courses, breakfast dishes, etc.)</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><strong>Kedgeree:</strong> </span></span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/food/recipes/kedgeree_11358\">http://www.bbc.co.uk/food/recipes/kedgeree_11358</a>; alternatively see my post here:<a href=\"%20http:/www.whatsforlunchhoney.net/2012/01/salmon-kedgeree-with-butternut-squash.html\"> http://www.whatsforlunchhoney.net/2012/01/salmon-kedgeree-with-butternut-squash.html</a></span></span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Cauliflower Soup: <a href=\"http://%20%20%20%20www.whatsforlunchhoney.net/2012/01/donna-hay-creamy-cauliflower-soup-with.html%20%20Mezzeh\">www.whatsforlunchhoney.net/2012/01/donna-hay-creamy-cauliflower-soup-with.html</a></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><strong><a href=\"http://%20%20%20%20www.whatsforlunchhoney.net/2012/01/donna-hay-creamy-cauliflower-soup-with.html%20%20Mezzeh\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Mezzeh:</span></a></strong></span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Falafel (separate + in the pita bread)</span></span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Cheese board&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Roasted Tomatoes </span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Spaghetti using the roasted tomatoes above <a href=\"http://www.taste.com.au/recipes/27094/spaghetti+in+cherry+tomato+sauce\">http://www.taste.com.au/recipes/27094/spaghetti+in+cherry+tomato+sauce</a></span><br /><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Asparagus Frittata: <a href=\"http://www.bonappetit.com/recipe/asparagus-frittata\">http://www.bonappetit.com/recipe/asparagus-frittata</a> / <a href=\"http://www.whatsforlunchhoney.net/2010/05/spanish-tortilla-with-asparagus-fennel.htm\">http://www.whatsforlunchhoney.net/2010/05/spanish-tortilla-with-asparagus-fennel.html</a>; &nbsp; Alternatively - Cheddar Cheese and Asparagus Quiche: <a href=\"http://www.whatsforlunchhoney.net/2012/06/smoked-cheddar-cheese