 \'Helvetica Neue\', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: 20px; orphans: auto; text-align: left; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 1; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; display: inline !important; float: none; background-color: #ffffff;\">I have lived pain, and my life can tell: I only deepen the wound of the world when I neglect to give thanks the heavy perfume of wild roses in early July and the song of crickets on summer humid nights and the rivers that run and the stars that rise and the rain that falls and all the good things that a good God gives.</span><span style=\"box-sizing: border-box; color: #000000; font-family: \'Helvetica Neue\', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: 20px; orphans: auto; text-align: left; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 1; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;\"><br style=\"box-sizing: border-box;\" />Read more at http://www.brainyquote.com/quotes/topics/topic_nature.html#9wtl0EQr1sfi2W0z.99</span></p>','<p><span style=\"color: #000000; font-family: \'Helvetica Neue\', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: 20px; orphans: auto; text-align: left; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 1; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; display: inline !important; float: none; background-color: #ffffff;\">I have lived pain, and my life can tell: I only deepen the wound of the world when I neglect to give thanks the heavy perfume of wild roses in early July and the song of crickets on summer humid nights and the rivers that run and the stars that rise and the rain that falls and all the good things that a good God gives.</span><span style=\"box-sizing: border-box; color: #000000; font-family: \'Helvetica Neue\', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: 20px; orphans: auto; text-align: left; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 1; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;\"><br style=\"box-sizing: border-box;\" />Read more at http://www.brainyquote.com/quotes/topics/topic_nature.html#9wtl0EQr1sfi2W0z.99</span></p>',0,1,NULL,'2015-05-08 10:02:02','2015-05-08 10:02:02'),(156,240,'Digital Camera Basics','','<p>For this first assignment, I\'d like you to consider all that has been discussed in this week\'s lesson regarding the workings of digital cameras and to experiment freely with the mode control (dial or buttons) on your own camera.&nbsp; Then I would like you to upload your two best images made from each of the following mode settings: Program, Aperture Priority and Shutter Priority for critique and discussion&nbsp; Be sure to indicate which photos were made in each mode.&nbsp; <strong>Six photos in total</strong>.</p>\r\n<p>Have fun with this!</p>',0,1,NULL,'2015-05-08 12:43:39','2015-05-08 12:48:27'),(157,241,'Exposure Explained','','<p>For this second assignment, I would like you to look through and experiment with the adjustments and settings we discussed in this lesson - using your own camera.&nbsp; Then practice using manual mode, aperture priority and shutter priority, along with white balance for the proper lighting situations to produce and upload the following number of images with the following specifications:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>2 of your best outdoor photos using manual (M) mode, ISO 200. One of these photos should demonstrate great depth of field (ie. everything from foreground to background in focus) and the second photo should exhibit a shallow depth of field.&nbsp; Please note settings (f-stop and shutter speed) for both photos.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>2 of your best outdoor photos using manual (M) mode and ISO 400 to capture bicycles or autos moving across your field of vision.&nbsp; One image should stop (freeze) action and the second should allow the action to blur across the photo. Please note settings (f-stop and shutter speed) for both photos.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>2 of your best outdoor images using aperture priority (A) mode and ISO 400 to capture bicycles or autos moving across the frame.&nbsp; One photo should freeze action and the second should allow action to blur.&nbsp; Please note settings (f-stop and shutter speed) for both photos.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>2 photos made indoors under tungsten or florescent light, using shutter priority (S) mode.&nbsp; Adjust your ISO accordingly to produce one image possessing shallow depth of field and the second a greater depth of field.&nbsp; Please note settings (f-stop and shutter speed) for both photos.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Eight photos total, uploaded to the TCI website for critique.&nbsp; Let me know if you have any questions, otherwise - good luck and have fun with this second digital camera assignment.</p>',0,1,NULL,'2015-05-08 12:44:32','2015-05-08 13:15:29'),(158,242,'Composition and Light','','<p>We covered a lot in this lesson - compositional elements within the frame, their arrangement and the effect of lighting directions on them.&nbsp; Your assignment is then to work with all that we\'ve talked about and upload your strongest <strong>8 photos</strong> in the following categories:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>2 photos that demonstrate the \"rule of thirds\" compositional guideline.</li>\r\n<li>1 photo that fills the frame with the subject.</li>\r\n<li>1 photo that uses a \"leading line\" to direct the viewer\'s eye to a subject in the composition.</li>\r\n<li>1 photo that demonstrates the dramatic effect of diagonal lines in a photo.</li>\r\n<li>1 photo that uses front lighting effectively.</li>\r\n<li>1 photo that puts back lighting to use.</li>\r\n<li>1 photo that places the subject (or landscape) in a side light situation.</li>\r\n</ul>',0,1,NULL,'2015-05-08 12:45:42','2015-05-08 13:20:50'),(159,243,'From Snapshots to Photographs','','<p>This being your final assignment, I\'m going to ask you to bring all into play - everything talked about and practiced, throughout the course.&nbsp; Finds some good scenes and subjects near you, practice your skills and techniques and upload your most impressive captures in the following categories:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>A <strong>3</strong>-image sequence of images beginning with a snapshot and ultimately ending with a well composed photograph with a defined subject and either a thematically fitting background or a distracting background that has been de-emphasized by rendering it out of focus.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>1</strong> photograph demonstrating the effective use of either a leading line or an S-shaped curve in a composition.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>1</strong> photo using a silhouette to showcase the subject.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>1 </strong>photo that fills the frame.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>1 </strong>demonstrating the creative use of diagonal lines in the composition.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>1 </strong>stunning final photo showcasing your own skills and creatively as a digital photographer.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Eight images in total.&nbsp; Have fun with this assignment and let me know if you have any questions concerning it.</strong></p>',0,1,NULL,'2015-05-08 12:46:41','2015-05-08 13:34:07');
