INSERT INTO `critiques` VALUES (2,192,'Attachment',52,'interesting',NULL,'2015-02-12 14:05:23','2015-02-12 14:05:23',NULL,NULL),(3,9,'AssignmentSubmission',52,'Rearrangement',NULL,'2015-02-12 14:05:54','2015-02-12 14:05:54','192,190,191,189','189,192,191,190'),(4,86,'Attachment',66,'File attached',NULL,'2015-02-14 13:12:25','2015-02-14 13:12:25',NULL,NULL),(5,230,'Attachment',52,'<p>Wonderful photo!</p>',NULL,'2015-02-23 16:06:00','2015-02-23 16:06:00',NULL,NULL),(6,303,'Attachment',52,'<p>HI check by instructor.&nbsp;</p>',NULL,'2015-02-27 10:32:18','2015-02-27 10:32:18',NULL,NULL),(7,306,'Attachment',52,'<p>Nice</p>',NULL,'2015-02-27 12:15:39','2015-02-27 12:15:39',NULL,NULL),(8,305,'Attachment',52,'<p>Very close and compelling</p>',NULL,'2015-02-27 12:15:46','2015-02-27 12:15:46',NULL,NULL),(9,81,'Attachment',66,'<p>Jaypur ford call Hawa MAhhal&nbsp;</p>',NULL,'2015-03-02 10:35:10','2015-03-02 10:35:10',NULL,NULL),(10,81,'Attachment',66,'<p>It s loocking preaty.</p>',NULL,'2015-03-02 10:37:09','2015-03-02 10:37:09',NULL,NULL),(11,677,'Attachment',75,'<p>Your image locking good but this format locking more good</p>',NULL,'2015-03-28 11:43:38','2015-03-28 11:43:38',NULL,NULL),(12,868,'Attachment',65,'<p>Dear Paul,</p>\r\n<p>Thanks for your submissions. Yeah you are right; sometimes it is difficult to work with one fixed lens. But sometimes it is also an advantage to use one lens because you really then know what you need to keep in the frame and what you need to take out of the frame.</p>\r\n<p>If you want, you can use any lens for your next assignments. It was a test so you can feel the advantages and disadvantages of using one fixed focal length.</p>\r\n<p>Nowadays I mostly use a 24-70mm f 2.8 lens and I can cover most of my interested areas. I take images of people, so I can use wide angle when I need more space/ context or I use 70 mm when I need to take portrait or detail shots.&nbsp; Actually I think a short zoom lens is better because it gives you more options.<br />&nbsp;<br />Let&rsquo;s talk about the images:</p>\r\n<p>01: It is always important to find something exceptional for portraits. For any portrait the face is the most important. The face should be an interesting one, otherwise it&rsquo;s very difficult to grab the attention of the viewer. Then use of good, evenly distributed light, a simple background that does not distract from he main subject, and the expression of the person is very a fundamental point for a good portrait.</p>\r\n<p>I really like your selection of the person. He&rsquo;s really got a very attractive and interesting face. The light looks flat in this photo and also it would be better if there were a little more space in this photo, so we can see a little better how he&rsquo;s dressed.</p>\r\n<p>I have edited the images a little and put some more light on his face. It is looking livelier now. The light was a little too dark.</p>',NULL,'2015-04-12 13:49:58','2015-04-12 13:49:58',NULL,NULL),(13,914,'Attachment',52,'<p>Hi Sejuti, This photo has nice composition.&nbsp; The diagonal \"line\" of the floor running through this frame adds \"dynamism\" and \"energy\" to the photo.&nbsp; These are characteristics of diagonal lines in the design of a photo.&nbsp; Such lines can be \"tangible,\" as this one is - or \"perceived,\" as in two people - one near the upper left corner of a composition and the other near the lower right corner of a photo - looking at each other.&nbsp; This latter example (although the diagonal line is only \"perceived\" or \"inferred\") stills brings the same \"feeling\" into the photo.</p>\r\n<p>Now to bring \"life\" to this photo and greater energy to the perception of your NGO \"Headquarters,\" you DO need people sitting at desks and worker and perhaps a person or two walking along that diagonal line of floor.&nbsp; Hand-holding your camera steady - or placing it on a tripod- and photographing with a slow shutter speed (for example: 1/15 or 1/8 sec.) you would capture those walking through in a semi-blur, which would bring dynamism and greater interest to your photo.&nbsp;</p>',NULL,'2015-04-14 11:35:18','2015-04-14 11:35:18',NULL,NULL),(14,915,'Attachment',52,'<p>Ideally, you would want to move closer to the display and into the space as I\'ve cropped it here.&nbsp; To bring such a photo to life, you would want someone actually looking at the images on display - or two people looking at and discussing what they see.&nbsp; Such shots can be \"set up\" using two of your colleagues.&nbsp; For the type of \"goal\" you have in creating a photo essay (i.e. to show the workings of your NGO), \"directing\" your compositions is completely valid.&nbsp; Your aim is not \"photojournalism,\" where setting up shots is unethical, but creating more of a \"corporate report\" for the agency you work for.</p>',NULL,'2015-04-14 11:36:19','2015-04-14 11:36:19',NULL,NULL),(15,916,'Attachment',52,'<p>Technically speaking, this photo needs a bit more exposure to open up the shadow areas.&nbsp; I would have suggested you take your exposure reading from the demonstrator\'s right hand and then lock-in this exposure for your shot. Always take your exposure reading from the most important part of the scene, as you determine it to be.&nbsp; In this case, doing so would have given you an image something like my Adoboe Lightroom simulation above.</p>\r\n<p>Aside from this, your composition is very nice and there is a \"sense of moment\" to the demonstrator touching the weather station with his fingers.&nbsp; The fact that all those in attendance are paying direct attention to this, strengthens the composition.&nbsp; Had some been looking elsewhere, the photo would not have been so strong.</p>\r\n<p>Also, be careful not to overlap people too much - placing one nearly directly behind the other.&nbsp; In a situation like you\'ve encountered here, I know it\'s not easy to avoid doing so, but always do the best you can in this respect.</p>\r\n<p>Lastly, watch out for bright lights in the backgound and on edges of the frame.&nbsp; Their intensity draws the viewer\'s eye directly to them and away from the intended subject of the photo.&nbsp; For example, to have gotten down just a little bit would have placed that bright ceiling light behind the head of the man on the extreme left of the frame.&nbsp; Always pay attention not JUST to the subject of a photo (the demonstrator in this case), but to all that\'s going on in the background.&nbsp; Subject and background are BOTH important and must work together to equal a \"whole.\"</p>',NULL,'2015-04-14 11:39:57','2015-04-14 11:39:57',NULL,NULL),(16,916,'Attachment',52,'<p>First of all, do watch your horizon lines.&nbsp; Unless you want to create an \"edgy\" / \"tense\" effect that fits to a particular subject and scene, try to keep them as level as possible (my crop above).&nbsp; Also, having taken your exposure reading from the organic manure in the foreground beds would have given you a better-exposed image.&nbsp; The shadow areas would have become more open to detail just what this area looks like.</p>\r\n<p>And - a person with a rake or shovel working the bed between the first and second roof support from the left side of the frame, would have brought \"action\" and \"life\" to this photo.</p>',NULL,'2015-04-14 11:43:45','2015-04-14 11:43:45',NULL,NULL),(17,917,'Attachment',52,'<p>First of all, do watch your horizon lines.&nbsp; Unless you want to create an \"edgy\" / \"tense\" effect that fits to a particular subject and scene, try to keep them as level as possible (my crop above).&nbsp; Also, having taken your exposure reading from the organic manure in the foreground beds would have given you a better-exposed image.&nbsp; The shadow areas would have become more open to detail just what this area looks like.</p>\r\n<p>And - a person with a rake or shovel working the bed between the first and second roof support from the left side of the frame, would have brought \"action\" and \"life\" to this photo.</p>',NULL,'2015-04-14 11:45:14','2015-04-14 11:45:14',NULL,NULL),(18,918,'Attachment',52,'<p>A very nice composition and you\'ve captured a strong \"sense of moment\" in the scientist\'s hand raised, making a point.&nbsp; Again too, the fact that all are paying direct attention to him, strengthens the photo.&nbsp; The only suggestion for improvement here, would have been a bit more exposure.&nbsp; Having taken your exposure from the scientists fact (here\'s where a \"spot meter\" setting on your camera comes into play) and used this for the whole scene, would have given you this - something like my Lightroom simulation here.</p>',NULL,'2015-04-14 11:48:51','2015-04-14 11:48:51',NULL,NULL),(19,919,'Attachment',52,'<p>Again a nice composition with a sense of \"moment\" in the colleague\'s pointing out something to the onlookers.&nbsp; This is a good \"vertical\" shot, which conforms well to brochure design / dimensions and to magazine front-cover layout.&nbsp; This said, keep in mind too that much more visual \"information\" can be placed in a horizontally-formatted frame.&nbsp; For example here, the viewer could see more \"context\" (more onlookers) on the right side of this particular scene.<br />Also, the light in this situation if very \"contrasty\" - bright highlights from a direct sun in the background and deep shadow in many of the people, in the foreground.&nbsp; This is a situation where \"fill flash\" comes in handy to \"balance\" these light extremes and open up shadow areas, such that facial details, etc. can be seen.</p>',NULL,'2015-04-14 11:49:04','2015-04-14 11:49:04',NULL,NULL),(20,919,'Attachment',52,'<p><a href=\"http://www.kenrockwell.com/tech/fill-flash.htm\"><strong>Fill Flash</strong></a></p>',NULL,'2015-04-14 11:51:11','2015-04-14 11:51:11',NULL,NULL),(21,19,'AssignmentSubmission',52,'File attached',NULL,'2015-04-14 11:53:36','2015-04-14 11:53:36',NULL,NULL),(22,19,'AssignmentSubmission',52,'File attached',NULL,'2015-04-14 11:55:00','2015-04-14 11:55:00',NULL,NULL),(23,19,'AssignmentSubmission',52,'File attached',NULL,'2015-04-14 11:55:38','2015-04-14 11:55:38',NULL,NULL),(24,19,'AssignmentSubmission',52,'<p>Very good work for this first assignment, Sejuti. I feel this can be a strong photo essay, but as you say, you\'ll need some strong \"action shots\" from the field.&nbsp; Keep in mind too that your final photo essay will include a variety of three \"types\" of shots exemplified here with images s from an East Africa shoot - 1) wide-angle scene-setting shots to show where things are taking place; 2) medium-distance shots / \"environmental portraits\" that show the \"actors\" in your story, at work in their roles with the context of their work around them, and; 3) close-up / detail shots that will be the \"connective tissue\" between other images - and that help to move the story along in a logical and meaningful way.</p>\r\n<p>Let me know if you have any questions or comments.&nbsp; Otherwise, looking forward to seeing your next assignment!</p>\r\n<p>David</p>\r\n<p>P.S. Are you based in Kathmandu?</p>',NULL,'2015-04-14 11:56:23','2015-04-14 11:56:23',NULL,NULL),(25,929,'Attachment',66,'<p>Good morning! &nbsp;I am so glad you are well again and back to taking pictures! &nbsp;Firstly, great choice of subject. &nbsp;Your model has a beautiful face and I can see you worked well together as a team in creating these images. &nbsp;Her makeup and hair are true to her own look without altering her, and her styling is also on-trend. &nbsp;I really like the direction you have given her for her expressions and you do feel that she is someone interesting and who you would want to get to know. &nbsp;She isn\'t aloof, even though she is looking away from the camera. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Keep in mind that model\'s portfolio books nearly always require vertical images and if they use a horizontal image then the seam in theirr portfolio can\'t go down the middle of the model or cut her in half in an awkward way. &nbsp;In this image, if your model was more to the left of the frame, the composition would work well for a horizontal portfolio image. &nbsp;Positioning yourself facing the bench a little more might also have allowed the model to try various body positions with her legs just to give you options when editing. &nbsp;I also like the color palette you chose, as it is not distracting,and her t-shirt actually draws the eye up to her face.</p>',NULL,'2015-04-15 08:37:28','2015-04-15 08:37:28',NULL,NULL),(26,930,'Attachment',66,'<p>The composition in this image is quite good and I love the angles of the light in the background. &nbsp;It all hints at a bit of mystery and tells a story which is always a good thing in a photo. &nbsp;If this were a modeling image for a portfolio, we would need to see the model\'s face and neck more as her book really has to sell her as a model. &nbsp;Perhaps a little bounce light from a reflector or a reflective surface would brighten up her face, or alternatively, you can select her face in photoshop and brighten the face area with curves. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>This sort of image could work well as an advertisement for a hotel or such, as it does tell a story and leaves room for \"copy\" on the right hand side. &nbsp;\"Copy\" are the words and logo that appear on advertisments and on magazine pages. &nbsp;If your model had taken a slight step backward her profile would have landed more along the white, over-exposed area behind her, separating her from the object in the background; her nose would not appear to touch the outer edge of that object. &nbsp;All in all, it is a good shot for advertising and the model, even though she is looking away, is still engaging and involved with the image.</p>',NULL,'2015-04-15 08:39:23','2015-04-15 08:39:23',NULL,NULL),(27,931,'Attachment',66,'<p>This image has a journalistic quality and again, tells a story. It feels almost like a still from a movie. &nbsp;In those instances the image works great. &nbsp;If it is for a model\'s porfolio, then it becomes too busy and there are to many elements vying for your eye. &nbsp;The focus would need to be really on the model and her face. &nbsp;It would be different if she was in front of the bars instead of behind, and would be quite graphic. &nbsp;The bars and their shadows don\'t allow us to really see the beauty of the model and we get the feeling she might be in danger or in fear. &nbsp;The light was quite strong when you shot the image so putting your model in front of the fence might have made the light too harsh on her face. &nbsp; You may have had to use a scrim to provide some shade, or you could have turned her so her shoulder was on the fence and the light more behind her, shooting along the fence at an angle rather than straight on.</p>',NULL,'2015-04-15 08:41:12','2015-04-15 08:41:12',NULL,NULL),(28,932,'Attachment',66,'<p>This image is quite good. &nbsp;I have enclosed a slightly altered version of the image to illustrate improvements in the actual image that would make it work for a model\'s portfolio. &nbsp;First, it would be good to crop into the image so the focus is really on her face and her beauty. &nbsp;If she sat up a bit straighter and prouder with square shoulders it present her face and neck with better proportion. &nbsp;A model has to show off her beauty and be proud of it without being arrogant ;-) &nbsp;It also appears as if the tree behind her is growing out of her back so sliding her along the bench a little to a simpler background would make her pop out more. &nbsp;Her face looks really beautiful but her left hand and shoulder seems doubtful. &nbsp;When you are photographing models you become a bit of a psychologist, and your job is photograph them in the best possible way to enhance their beauty, even if that means you have to really direct them in their body movements, or point out how they can improve their body position.</p>\r\n<p>It is great to shoot digital so that you can show the model the back of the camera once or twice as models often have a hard time visualizing what you are trying to do. &nbsp;If you show them, it sometimes helps ;-) &nbsp;I actually love my \'Hoodman\" loop which I hang around my neck so that I can see the image on the camera much more clearly and show the makeup artist, model, stylist, etc. how the image looks in-camera so we can improve things. &nbsp;Sometimes we miss thing with our naked eye but we see it in the photo - digital is great that way.</p>',NULL,'2015-04-15 08:44:54','2015-04-15 08:44:54',NULL,NULL),(29,20,'AssignmentSubmission',66,'<p>All in all, a great first assignment! &nbsp;Well done! &nbsp;I hope my pointers help for the next assignment. &nbsp;Looking forward to seeing that too!</p>',NULL,'2015-04-15 09:02:10','2015-04-15 09:02:10',NULL,NULL),(30,929,'Attachment',101,'<p>Hello, Allana!</p>\r\n<p>Thanks for your detailed and descriptive feedback. Please let me know if I understood you correctly regarding positioning myself by checking <a href=\"https://scontent-cdg.xx.fbcdn.net/hphotos-xaf1/v/t1.0-9/11102802_865122113558515_8627543394779709679_n.jpg?oh=55348a25041ff75b55e0565be2d00944&amp;oe=55A6C123\">this photo</a>.</p>',NULL,'2015-04-15 09:11:36','2015-04-15 09:11:36',NULL,NULL),(31,930,'Attachment',101,'<p>Thanks for attracting my attention to such tiny details that I really missed (her nose would not appear to touch the outer edge of that object)<br />I\'ve got a reflector recently but I have not tried it yet. Can you share some hints on using it (besides of getting extra hands :)?&nbsp;</p>',NULL,'2015-04-15 09:13:04','2015-04-15 09:13:04',NULL,NULL),(32,932,'Attachment',101,'<p>Thanks for your edit of the photo. It cleary explains the idea of a model\'s portfolio. And also I\'m greatful for such a simple but useful gadget - Hoodman</p>',NULL,'2015-04-15 09:17:10','2015-04-15 09:17:10',NULL,NULL),(33,929,'Attachment',66,'<p>Hello Kseniya,</p>\r\n<p>Indeed, you understood correctly. &nbsp;In fact, you could shoot a horizontal version of this image if you position the model to the far left of the frame. You can make variations on this shot by having her put both legs up on the wall and leaning over her knees and wrapping her ams around her legs, or sitting with a fairly straight back and her right hand just placed at the edge of the bench behind her and with her right leg down on the ground. &nbsp;Lots of variations! Allana</p>',NULL,'2015-04-15 09:19:54','2015-04-15 09:19:54',NULL,NULL),(34,930,'Attachment',66,'<p>Well extra hands are always useful ;-) &nbsp;LOL But then you have to instruct that person on how to do it effectively as well ;-) I usually find the white or silver reflectors work best, rather than gold unless you are at the beach and you want to make the model look a bit tanned. &nbsp;Make sure that the reflector has light (sunshine) hitting it and deflect that back onto the model. &nbsp;You can place it up to six feet away and it should still add \"fill\" light if there is enough sun. &nbsp;If you get too close it can over-expose the image and make the model not be able to open her eyes, so make sure that it looks flattering to your eye and then take a shot and check it on the camera. &nbsp;If the reflector is placed too low and angled upwards it will make hollows and circles around the model\'s eyes so make sure the the fill light coming from the reflector is even on her face. &nbsp;Once you master the basics of the reflector you can get really creative with it and create nice contrast in your images. &nbsp;But first, you just need to understand how to find the light and deflect it back onto the model.&nbsp;</p>',NULL,'2015-04-15 09:21:27','2015-04-15 09:21:27',NULL,NULL),(35,20,'AssignmentSubmission',66,'<p>Feel free to upload additional photos. This is possible via &ldquo;Add an Attachment&rdquo; in the menu. I will be happy to review them for you - not a problem ;-) &nbsp;It is better to have someone really point out what needs correcting so that you can learn and grow with your photography skills and not waste time wondering why an image doesn\'t \"work\". &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>I am addicted to magazines and love pouring over vintage magazines as well. &nbsp;If you are on Pinterest and you see a classic fashion image that you like, try to see if there is a photographer named and then research that photographer through google images and Pinterest. &nbsp;Referencing other photographers can inform your own style and help you develop your eye so that things become more automatic when you shoot. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>When I first began \"testing\" models for our mutual portfolios, I used to have two lists in my kit: one list was all the technical things I needed to remember, and the other were these crazy little stick-figure drawings that I did before each shoot, showing a basic idea of what I wanted to achieve, such as composition, hand and body positions, and variations - all so I wouldn\'t forget when I got caught up in the shoot ;-)</p>\r\n<p>The good thing with digital is that you can really experiment and try things and delete what doesn\'t work, and review images so you can improve a shot while shooting. &nbsp;Shoot as much as you can so things become easier and you will feel more comfortable trying new things.</p>',NULL,'2015-04-15 09:25:20','2015-04-15 09:25:20',NULL,NULL),(36,932,'Attachment',66,'<p>Glad the edit helps! &nbsp;The cropped image has tons of potential! &nbsp;</p>',NULL,'2015-04-15 09:25:25','2015-04-15 09:25:25',NULL,NULL),(37,939,'Attachment',65,'<p>First of all sorry for the delay to answer you, I am working in an area where network signal in very poor.</p>\r\n<p>Now let&rsquo;s talk about the first assignment. I am glad to hear your experience. Actually the more you will spend time for photography you will learn different thing. Meeting stranger and building relationship before taking image helps the subject to pose naturally in front of your camera. In Bangladesh people happily pose for photography, they will not ask for money. But in India/Africa people will not let take images without money at all. So it depends on the situation. I appreciate your attempt with different background&rsquo;s individual.</p>\r\n<p>The composition of this first image is very beautiful. The way the man is sitting is comforting that&rsquo;s make the body language is natural. The image portraits a nice environment. You have to work on the light. The light does not go in the face of the subject where else it has shifted prominently in the surrounding area which makes the subject less attractive. Eyes directly go to the back side of the subject. Next time you have to keep the light in a genuine consideration focusing subject in this kind of image composition.</p>',NULL,'2015-04-15 13:23:42','2015-04-15 13:23:42',NULL,NULL),(38,940,'Attachment',65,'<p>I like that you also try the frame vertically. Nice composition, natural body language as the first image is very appreciating. But again more light in the background than subject takes eyes away form the subject.</p>',NULL,'2015-04-15 13:25:03','2015-04-15 13:25:03',NULL,NULL),(39,941,'Attachment',65,'<p>Nice composition and it has detailed shot. But the same problem with the light.</p>',NULL,'2015-04-15 13:26:00','2015-04-15 13:26:00',NULL,NULL),(40,17,'AssignmentSubmission',65,'<p>Thank you so much, Bonnie. Looking forward for your next assignment. I think you are very good with people in terms of building relationship.&nbsp; Just give some time and experiment with light. Try to use early morning and late afternoon lights. In your free time please have a look in my street photography blog posts category; it might be helpful for you. The link is: <a href=\"http://www.gmbakash.wordpress.com\">www.gmbakash.wordpress.com</a>.</p>\r\n<p>Best regards,</p>\r\n<p>Akash</p>',NULL,'2015-04-15 13:34:21','2015-04-15 13:34:21',NULL,NULL),(41,942,'Attachment',65,'<p>Again more light in the background than subject takes eyes away from the subject.</p>',NULL,'2015-04-15 13:34:27','2015-04-15 13:34:27',NULL,NULL),(42,943,'Attachment',65,'<p>This picture has action which is very interesting. If the action (karate) is clearer it would be nicer. You have to be careful about overlapping during photography. The tree that has overlapped the man&rsquo;s head is distracting the subject. Also the light issue is same as previous pictures. More light in the environment is taking attention from the subject. For using the light you have to give priority to your subject.</p>',NULL,'2015-04-15 13:34:32','2015-04-15 13:34:32',NULL,NULL),(43,944,'Attachment',65,'<p>The close up shot is good, the action is clear here. If there would be more light on him it could be a better image.</p>',NULL,'2015-04-15 13:34:38','2015-04-15 13:34:38',NULL,NULL),(44,945,'Attachment',65,'<p>This shot is nice. Better light here. More energy in the image and the action is very clear. Nice attempt.</p>',NULL,'2015-04-15 13:34:43','2015-04-15 13:34:43',NULL,NULL),(45,946,'Attachment',65,'<p>Your subject smiled naturally. The composition of the subject is great. The light is much better in this picture also the background reflection. But next time keep your eyes for any kind of overlapping like the window pillar went through the subject.</p>',NULL,'2015-04-15 13:34:48','2015-04-15 13:34:48',NULL,NULL),(46,947,'Attachment',65,'<p>Would like to compliment this image as previous comment. This detail frame is interesting with action. Careful about the overlapping next time and your reflection at the window glass.</p>',NULL,'2015-04-15 13:34:53','2015-04-15 13:34:53',NULL,NULL),(47,948,'Attachment',65,'<p>I like that you attempt pictures differently. But remember that when you are working with two people there should be a connection or interaction, otherwise attempting one subject as priority and another supportive character. Lack of this the image become uninteresting. The light and color of the picture is appreciable.</p>',NULL,'2015-04-15 13:34:58','2015-04-15 13:34:58',NULL,NULL),(48,949,'Attachment',65,'<p>Light is the most important factor for any picture. As the subject is wearing white shirt the light is reflecting from the T shirt. Try to use even light in the subject in such case.</p>',NULL,'2015-04-15 13:35:03','2015-04-15 13:35:03',NULL,NULL),(49,950,'Attachment',65,'<p>As a viewer of this image, it has a lot of information which is interesting. If you can take different shots with these reflection or background it would be possible to get more interesting image.</p>',NULL,'2015-04-15 13:35:09','2015-04-15 13:35:09',NULL,NULL),(50,951,'Attachment',65,'<p>You make your subject very natural in front of camera that comes with a visual interesting interaction. Nice timing. Proper timing is very important for photography. Also the action in the image creates more interest in the image.</p>',NULL,'2015-04-15 13:35:14','2015-04-15 13:35:14',NULL,NULL),(51,952,'Attachment',65,'<p>Very interesting image. Like the background which added a different dimension in the picture. Just remember that always try to give little space in the way the subject is going/moving.</p>',NULL,'2015-04-15 13:35:19','2015-04-15 13:35:19',NULL,NULL),(52,953,'Attachment',65,'<p>Same as previous image. Avoid overlapping like in the picture the lady has covered a bit of the carved angle.</p>',NULL,'2015-04-15 13:35:24','2015-04-15 13:35:24',NULL,NULL),(53,939,'Attachment',97,'<p>Akash, thank you so much for the very thorough and insightful&nbsp;critique. I can see that my use of light is where I need to improve most. Having said that, when doing photos like this, particularly when approaching people (as opposed to finding a place with great light and waiting for someone to walk into it), would you ask them to move into better light? Or would you just wait for them to do so (it\'s all about the moment, after all). I suppose an experienced street photographer would not have chosen these subjects because of the poor lighting situation in general...</p>\r\n<p>I was quite nervous, and when I\'m that way, I find it difficult to notice the things I know to normally look for to make a decent image. Throughout the course I\'ll try to be more cognizant of light, firstly, and secondly, overlapping foreground and background elements!</p>\r\n<p>Thank you very much again...looking forward to the next assignments :-)</p>',NULL,'2015-04-15 13:44:14','2015-04-15 13:44:14',NULL,NULL),(54,938,'Attachment',70,'<p>Dear Kara! Thank you for your submission! I was hoping to get this completed today before I head out to Vienna for my workshop but time flies! I do not want to rush my feedback and critique on this and I hope you are ok if I get to work on your assignment next week when I return!&nbsp;<br />Many hugs<br />Meeta</p>',NULL,'2015-04-16 06:41:05','2015-04-16 06:41:05',NULL,NULL),(55,938,'Attachment',98,'<p>Hi Meeta - Next week is fine. &nbsp;Have a great time in Vienna!</p>\r\n<p>This morning I did get an email saying that you dd a critique and it includes a link to what I think is the new website being developed. &nbsp;(SGDreamboard?) &nbsp;I tried to login - both with my current TCI login and by creating a new login - but I don\'t think it\'s fully functional yet. &nbsp;Couldn\'t get in - wouldn\'t confirm my new account.</p>\r\n<p>So maybe we\'ll just pick it all back up after you get back from Vienna and the website is launched?</p>\r\n<p>Thanks,&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Kara</p>',NULL,'2015-04-16 13:52:24','2015-04-16 13:52:24',NULL,NULL),(56,21,'AssignmentSubmission',70,'<p>Kara - first well done on the finding the right light in your house. I went through the same process too and great that you made your own scrim. So proud of you!!&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>SO: for the first three images in your exercises you did an awesome job. I love the light and it shows that you carefully and very thoroughly went through the process of finding the perfect way to light your images. The focus is on all of the images is really good. I like the way you took it a step at a time and compared how each image in your selection works on you. This is the best way to find your style.</p>\r\n<p>I find the soft focus on (34) Bowl as Main Focus 60mm appealing. The reds are vibrant and the white balance looks good. I&rsquo;d like to comment on a minor styling point &ndash; usually it is nicer not to crop off more than one side of a bowl. It&rsquo;s not a rule but rather something I find more appealing to the viewers eyes as it provides more balance and harmony and allows the eye to follow the outline of the plate into the image nicely. If two sides are cropped off the eyes have to pause on either side before continuing or trying to re-find a focus point. Does that make sense?</p>\r\n<p>I also really like (39) Bowl in an Environment - 60mm. It&rsquo;s probably my favorite &ndash; mainly because I am finding the elements work very well and the glass elements in the background allow diffused light to filter through beautifully. I love using glasses and bottle with water as an additional way to add diffused light and reflections to the image.</p>\r\n<p>I see what you mean with (53) Bowl in a Story - 35mm and I agree partly about it being too wide. But depending on the purpose this would make a lovely shot for maybe a cover of a magazine as it tells a story.</p>\r\n<p>Like you I also find (67) Bowl in an Environment - 50mm well executed too as with (39) it provides a nice balance and the viewer is right into the main hero. With both shots one can really play well with the depth of field / aperture to create a softer focus too.</p>\r\n<p>Great work on your first assignment. I am very pleased with the results Kara! Go for it!</p>\r\n<p>xo</p>',NULL,'2015-04-22 13:51:10','2015-04-22 13:51:10',NULL,NULL),(57,22,'AssignmentSubmission',66,'<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">Good work for this assignment Kseniya. &nbsp;I am thinking that you are a bit shy to get your model to really engage with you and the camera. &nbsp;Your images are so beautiful in the technical sense and now you need to work on developing your skills to direct the model as she looks into the camera and tells her \"story\" to the lens. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">You understand the concept of the story of an image and you have a lovely sense of cinema to your images. &nbsp;But be brave enough to lead your model to expose her emotions to the camera. &nbsp;You are a team and you must trust each other - you are creating powerful and beautiful images together. &nbsp;There is a vulnerability that works so well in photos, and your chosen model has that sense, so you can use it. &nbsp;Some models are all smiles and energy and totally wrapped up in their own \"movie\" of themselves and that makes for different photos, also beautiful and interesting, just different. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">If you have other out-takes from this shoot that you would like to show, just upload them here to the site and I will review them for you. &nbsp;I am so looking forward to your next images, with movement, and great eye contact.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">Thank you again for your patience in receiving my reply and for your kind words about my husband - all will be well in time. &nbsp;He will recover - thank you! &nbsp;Allana</span></p>',NULL,'2015-04-26 10:11:13','2015-04-26 10:11:13',NULL,NULL),(58,961,'Attachment',66,'<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">Hi Kseniya,&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">Thank you for your patience in receiving my reply. &nbsp;Your choice of model is really good and she obviously loves to to be a part of your learning process. You are a good team. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">For a model\'s portfolio to really showcase her figure and proportions, it is super important for her to have images in her book that show that she is tall and thin. &nbsp;This also shows how \"fashion\" works on her body. &nbsp;To really show off her height and figure she should stand and pose in a natural way that suits the clothing she is wearing. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">In this case, the background is very good and I do like the lines. &nbsp;If she was to stand in exactly that spot with her legs a bit apart and resting her weight to one side on one hip with her arms simply hanging down, it would be a really good modeling image. &nbsp;We would be able to see her height and the lines on the ground would add to the illusion of height as well. &nbsp;With the clothes she is wearing, she would definitely pop out from the background and not blend in too much. &nbsp;I do like the light as well. It would also be great if she had her eyes open and was making contact with the camera too.</span></p>',NULL,'2015-04-26 10:11:19','2015-04-26 10:11:19',NULL,NULL),(59,962,'Attachment',66,'<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">In this image it \"almost\" worked. &nbsp;Imagine if she had stepped just far enough to her left that the line from the shadow of the fence would not be crossing her face. &nbsp;If her face was clearly in the light it would be quite a graphic image. &nbsp;The vertical and horizontal lines are eye-catching and add great interest to the image. &nbsp;If this is for the model\'s portfolio for an agency to promote her, the most important part of the image would be the model, so for the potential client who is looking at her book really needs to see her face in the light. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">She is &nbsp;quite natural and relaxed in her pose and the styling works with the location, and it does \"tell a story\" as an image.&nbsp;</span></p>',NULL,'2015-04-26 10:11:24','2015-04-26 10:11:24',NULL,NULL),(60,963,'Attachment',66,'<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">What a pretty model! &nbsp;Firstly I love the composition and light and the shadows of her face. &nbsp;We can really see her delicate bone structure and her pale coloring. It appears as if the light was bothering her eyes a bit, so to keep that same light situation, it could be a good idea to ask the model to inhale deeply with her eyes closed and then open them calmly when she exhales, telling her to be aware of keeping soft eyebrows. &nbsp;Also, the image would \"engage\" the viewer a little more if her mouth was open or even smiling or laughing. &nbsp;I can tell you paid great attention to her beautiful hair and how it fell on the grass - good job!</span></p>',NULL,'2015-04-26 10:11:29','2015-04-26 10:11:29',NULL,NULL),(61,964,'Attachment',66,'<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">You have a great way of choosing your backgrounds so that your model separates from the background and doesn\'t blend in. &nbsp;Good job. &nbsp;I love the feeling the model is having for this shot. &nbsp;For a model portfolio it would be great if she was looking at the camera and whatever story she is telling you in her expression, let it be to the camera. &nbsp;She should drop her shoulder enough that we can see her neck which is super important for models. &nbsp;Remember: long arms and legs, nice shoulders and neck. </span></p>',NULL,'2015-04-26 10:11:34','2015-04-26 10:11:34',NULL,NULL),(62,965,'Attachment',66,'<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">Such a pretty image! &nbsp;It works for many reasons, but it doesn\'t show physical \"movement\". &nbsp;Their is movement in her body lines and in the lines and shapes of the wall and the water behind her, but she isn&rsquo;t moving. &nbsp;Imagine the same shot with her on her side leaning on one elbow and her staring down the camera in a provocative way - oh la la. &nbsp;It still wouldn\'t be a &nbsp;movement image, but it would be very appealing for a model. &nbsp;It would showcase her curves.</span></p>',NULL,'2015-04-26 10:11:40','2015-04-26 10:11:40',NULL,NULL),(63,966,'Attachment',66,'<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">This image has movement but it is only in her hair. &nbsp;If she had spun around and let her hair fly and had graceful arms it would be a great modeling shot. &nbsp;The light is beautiful and a little animation in her body movement would work very well. Do you have the chance to shoot with her again? &nbsp;If so, try to get those \"movement\" shots. &nbsp;You are very good with speed and exposure so don\'t be shy of giving it a good try. </span></p>',NULL,'2015-04-26 10:11:45','2015-04-26 10:11:45',NULL,NULL),(64,22,'AssignmentSubmission',101,'<p>Hi, Allana!</p>\r\n<p>Thank you very much for your detailed feedback. Please take your time and don\'t rush with responding on time as I fully understand the importance of dedicating enough time to the family in such situations.</p>\r\n<p>The critique was clear and I took into account all your advices.&nbsp; I appreciate the opportunity to share more photos for review and will upload them later today</p>\r\n<p>Regards,&nbsp;<br />Kseniya</p>',NULL,'2015-04-28 07:10:48','2015-04-28 07:10:48',NULL,NULL),(65,22,'AssignmentSubmission',66,'<p>Good morning Kseniya,&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;I hope you are well. &nbsp;Thank you for your understanding of any delays in my responses. My husband is still in the hospital, but we are movnign towards a return to health and some recovery. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>I really do look forward to your assingnments and hope my crtiques are clear and helpful. &nbsp;Whenever you are ready, go ahead and send the updated images and we will have a look and go over them together. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Wishing you a wonderful evening; regards, &nbsp; Allana</p>',NULL,'2015-04-29 14:55:36','2015-04-29 14:55:36',NULL,NULL),(66,24,'AssignmentSubmission',70,'<p>change it</p>',NULL,'2015-05-07 11:19:48','2015-05-07 11:19:48',NULL,NULL),(67,977,'Attachment',70,'File attached',NULL,'2015-05-07 11:19:57','2015-05-07 11:19:57',NULL,NULL),(68,22,'AssignmentSubmission',66,'<div class=\"show_critique\" style=\"margin-top: 15px; margin-left: 30px;\"><strong>Comment by Allana Wesley White on May 7, 2015</strong></div>\r\n<div class=\"show_critique\" style=\"margin-top: 15px; margin-left: 30px;\">Good afternoon Kseniya,\r\n<p>i hope you are doing well. &nbsp;I wanted to let you know that my husband is in rehabilitation now and past the danger point, and I have more time to take care of work, etc. I am excited to see your next assignment and by all means send me any questions you may have. &nbsp;I will checking in regularly and will be able to respond quickly. Thank you so much again for your patience. Hope to see your new work soon; &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Sincerely, &nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Allana</p>\r\n</div>',NULL,'2015-05-08 08:04:02','2015-05-08 08:04:02',NULL,NULL),(69,994,'Attachment',65,'<p>This is good image but ...</p>',NULL,'2015-05-08 09:49:46','2015-05-08 09:49:46',NULL,NULL),(70,995,'Attachment',65,'<p>I like this image</p>',NULL,'2015-05-08 09:49:56','2015-05-08 09:49:56',NULL,NULL),(71,996,'Attachment',65,'<p>Good Quality</p>',NULL,'2015-05-08 09:50:06','2015-05-08 09:50:06',NULL,NULL),(72,996,'Attachment',80,'<p>Thanks for sugesstion</p>',NULL,'2015-05-08 09:50:52','2015-05-08 09:50:52',NULL,NULL),(73,29,'AssignmentSubmission',65,'File attached',NULL,'2015-05-08 09:51:39','2015-05-08 09:51:39','994,995,996','996,994,995'),(74,30,'AssignmentSubmission',52,'<p>You did a really impressive job with this first assignment.&nbsp; The shot from a variety of perspective - up, down, etc., which always yields better and more expressive photos than if you were too just stand there and photograph from a standing position.&nbsp; Big thing to work on is \"context.\"&nbsp; Some of these situations would make excellent \"environmental portraits\" with spray cans lined up at the feet of a spraying artist, etc.&nbsp; Try capturing a number of detail shots too.&nbsp; For example, close-up shots of the artist\'s hand reaching down and selecting a particular can of color frame from a group of cans ready to be used - shots like that.</p>\r\n<p>Good luck with returning to the shoot this weekend.&nbsp; Hopefully the weather will hold as it is here.&nbsp; If you haven\'t already, you might offer to give prints to participating artists, of their \"work in progress.\"&nbsp; Or buy them a Coke or coffee to better rapport.&nbsp; At any rate, best of luck with this story.&nbsp; I think it can be a quite interesting on.</p>\r\n<p>Let me know if you have any questions.&nbsp; Looking forward to seeing your second assignment submission.</p>\r\n<p>David</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 09:22:53','2015-05-12 09:22:53',NULL,NULL),(75,1058,'Attachment',52,'<p>In terms of a \"detail shot,\" this is in the direction that I suggested. However, again, a hand setting a can down or picking one up would add greater interest.&nbsp; Right - a longer lens or stretch a clear plastic bag over your lens and secure it with a rubber band.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 09:23:03','2015-05-12 09:23:03',NULL,NULL),(76,1059,'Attachment',52,'<p>I like the slight tilt and the composition, light and colors age good.&nbsp; The shot needs more context at the bottom of the frame.&nbsp; the viewer wants to see what this artist is actually doing here.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 09:23:09','2015-05-12 09:23:09',NULL,NULL),(77,1060,'Attachment',52,'<p>I like how the lines run on a slight diagonal through the frame.&nbsp; Diagonal lines add \"energy\" to compositions.&nbsp; Light and colors are fine too.&nbsp; What is \"missing\" is a particular can or element within this composition that stands out as a \"Subject,\" somewhere for the viewer\'s eye to come to rest on.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 09:23:19','2015-05-12 09:23:19',NULL,NULL),(78,1061,'Attachment',52,'<p>Nice.&nbsp; There is a good \"sense of moment\" to this shot.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 09:23:24','2015-05-12 09:23:24',NULL,NULL),(79,1062,'Attachment',52,'<p>This is a good \"middle distance\" shot and one where there\'s something happening - a \"moment\" captured.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 09:23:30','2015-05-12 09:23:30',NULL,NULL),(80,1063,'Attachment',52,'<p>Yes, much more of what I was referring to.&nbsp; There\'s more \"filling of the frame\" here and the shot is dynamic in its largely diagonal lines.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 09:23:34','2015-05-12 09:23:34',NULL,NULL),(81,1064,'Attachment',52,'<p>Hi Umberto,&nbsp; Light and colors are great in these shots.&nbsp; Nice that closer \"portraits\" can be captured in \"open shade\" with no harsh shadows.&nbsp; That said, some glare and \"flare-outs\" in part, here and there as you\'ve done, could add welcome \"edgy-ness\" to certain images.&nbsp; I think this could be a good and dynamic story and it does have a degree of \"social impact\" in adding some visual interest to City Zuerich.&nbsp; I\'ll go through these shots one-by-one and make a some comments ...</p>\r\n<p>Getting down lower and photographing upwards on a subject accentuates it - giving it more \"power.\"&nbsp; Two suggestions here - the first being that horizontal framing would have allowed more visual \"information\" to the right side of the frame.&nbsp; The second is to be aware of lines that \"meet.\" In this shot I\'m referring to the artist\'s forehead and the top of the wall.&nbsp; It would have been better to have captured some sky between wall and head - or to have obtained a perspective whereby the artist\'s head appears a bit above the top line of the wall.&nbsp; Conversely, a perspective that brought the artist\'s head below the top line of the wall would have worked, too.&nbsp; In summary then, watch lines that absolutely touch / intersect / meet in such a way as to appear \"joined.\"</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 09:23:40','2015-05-12 09:23:40',NULL,NULL),(82,1065,'Attachment',52,'<p>I think this would have worked more successfully had you gotten down on the ground next to the paint can and brush with a wide-angle lens, opened aperture fully, focused sharply on the rim of the paint bucket and framed to include more \"context\" - ground beneath the painter\'s feet and a bit of area around the bucket itself.&nbsp; A slower shutter speed (e.g. 1/15 sec. or slower) would have allowed some movement (blur) in the painter\'s hand / arm movement, which would have brought more dynamism to the frame.&nbsp; So - closer to intended subject (paint can) and more \"context\" as to not cut off feet and bottom of bucket.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 09:23:45','2015-05-12 09:23:45',NULL,NULL),(83,1066,'Attachment',52,'<p>Nice.&nbsp; Watch that \"overlapping\" of elements, though (i.e. background artist\'s legs and back of foreground artist\'s head).</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 09:23:55','2015-05-12 09:23:55',NULL,NULL),(84,1067,'Attachment',52,'<p>A nice composition and I like the warm light on the artist\'s face.&nbsp; Perhaps a step to the left by you or having waited for the artist to take another step forward (to the right of the frame) would have placed the \"Subject\" (artist) more in that empty background blue space and separated him to a small degree from the lion\'s image.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 09:24:05','2015-05-12 09:24:05',NULL,NULL),(85,1068,'Attachment',52,'<p>This is definitely your most dynamic shot of the twelve.&nbsp; I like the colors echoed by passing man\'s trousers and that goldish-yellow on the wall.&nbsp; The passersby stride brings energy in combination with the stance of the artist.&nbsp; The sky is interesting and so to the background in general.&nbsp; Could there be improvement here?&nbsp; To have swung your camera a bit more to the left in order to bring more of the passerby into the frame would have made this a real \"Select\" of a photo.&nbsp; That is, less wall on the right side of the frame and more \"context\" on the left.&nbsp; Still a very nice photo, though.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 09:24:15','2015-05-12 09:24:15',NULL,NULL),(86,1069,'Attachment',52,'<p>I would have cropped it.&nbsp; There is so little of it (white) that it doesn\'t \"add\" in the mind of the viewer TO BE&nbsp; a wall.&nbsp; Therefore, crop it out.&nbsp; Also, without the slow shutter speed setting to place movement in the arm leaves you with a very \"static\" and not so interesting photo.&nbsp; Not one to look twice at.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 09:24:20','2015-05-12 09:24:20',NULL,NULL),(87,1070,'Attachment',52,'<p>I like the dynamics of this image - the body language of the artist and the compostion of it all.&nbsp; It would be cool to get some detail / close-up shots of the artist\'s hand, finger on the spay-can top and paint spraying out on the wall.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 09:24:26','2015-05-12 09:24:26',NULL,NULL),(88,1071,'Attachment',52,'<p>Tilting or \"torquing\" the camera a bit does add \"edge\" to a photo. It would / does work here, but I think had you been closer it would have worked better.&nbsp; With the sidewalk / street in the corner of the frame, the viewer (at least me) feels a bit off-balance.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 09:24:31','2015-05-12 09:24:31',NULL,NULL),(89,1072,'Attachment',52,'<p>I agree with the shoes / feet (more context).&nbsp; As for the out-of-focus artist, there really needs to be more distance between he and the lion for there to be a visible difference.&nbsp; If the artist were to take a few steps back to view his last applications of paint, etc. this would have worked better in these in-focus / out-of-focus terms.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 09:24:42','2015-05-12 09:24:42',NULL,NULL),(90,1073,'Attachment',52,'<p>OK - but keep in mind that very bright lights or spots of bright color near the edges of the frame draws the viewer\'s attention - and away from the subject.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 09:24:47','2015-05-12 09:24:47',NULL,NULL),(91,1074,'Attachment',52,'<p>Good subject - catching the body language and animated interaction of the arts.&nbsp; Too much empty blue wall in the frame in this shot, though.&nbsp; You need to get closer to better define the discussion and interaction.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 09:24:52','2015-05-12 09:24:52',NULL,NULL),(92,1075,'Attachment',52,'<p>I like this photo.&nbsp; You\'ve come in close and nicely filled the frame - which brings greater visual impact.&nbsp; I like the composition, the colors, the light.&nbsp; This image would be a \"Select\" for your story layout.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 09:25:02','2015-05-12 09:25:02',NULL,NULL),(93,1065,'Attachment',106,'<p>Hi David, thanks for the hint. I will look into such things. I guess it comes more automatically with experience. To get this shot I was not really looking into the eyefinder, I just put the camera on the ground at the feet of the artist and shoot trying to get the best shot. But I will check how they are coming out, or better yet I will lay down on the ground next time...</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 10:01:10','2015-05-12 10:01:10',NULL,NULL),(94,1066,'Attachment',106,'<p>Yep agreed with you. It was not really planned but I will try next time if I manage. I must admit is a difficult shot to get while he is moving so fast...</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 10:03:30','2015-05-12 10:03:30',NULL,NULL),(95,1067,'Attachment',106,'<p>Thanks. Again one of those small thing that makes the difference... Will keep that in mind.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 10:04:57','2015-05-12 10:04:57',NULL,NULL),(96,1068,'Attachment',106,'<p>I saw that too when I looked at the image on the computer. Another one of those small things...<br />A question: do you usually shoot 3-4 times each time to see if one shot is better than the others? In this case should I shoot 3-4 shots quickly (I am not doing that now, I only shoot when I think is good) or try to get the one right? What is your tactic usually?</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 10:07:06','2015-05-12 10:07:06',NULL,NULL),(97,1069,'Attachment',106,'<p>Ok. My tought was to get some kind of geometric/abstract/empty image with the artist to get the idea of peace and calmness of creation. I proably was not succesful :-) But I learn quickly. So more energy and dynamic! Understood.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 10:09:03','2015-05-12 10:09:03',NULL,NULL),(98,1071,'Attachment',106,'<p>Ok need to try again with less sidewalk :) and see how it is coming... I posted a slightly cropped and burned image of this one. Is that what you meant? Thanks for looking that too.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 10:13:27','2015-05-12 10:13:27',NULL,NULL),(99,1072,'Attachment',106,'<p>Thanks David, actually the out-of-focus was obtained with a low shutter speed, so he was moving. But I get your point. So a few details that make a difference. Thanks for pointing that out.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 10:14:32','2015-05-12 10:14:32',NULL,NULL),(100,1073,'Attachment',106,'<p>Good point. You are right. It does. So the sun should be behind the wall for this shot to work. What do you think?Or maybe at another time of the day? I actually liked in this shot the harsh light of midday...</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 10:15:45','2015-05-12 10:15:45',NULL,NULL),(101,1074,'Attachment',106,'<p>Perfectly right. My idea was always to get the wall in to give context but here is way too much. I agree...</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 10:17:06','2015-05-12 10:17:06',NULL,NULL),(102,1075,'Attachment',106,'<p>Ok. Thanks. Will go back Tuesday or Wed. and try to get better shots :)</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 10:18:19','2015-05-12 10:18:19',NULL,NULL),(103,30,'AssignmentSubmission',106,'<p>Hi David,</p>\r\n<p>thanks for the feedback. Context is the main thing (apar from all the rest ;-) ) I am working on. I planned (somehow) what shots I wanted to get before going there to try not to shot randomly. Including some detailed shot. The one of the hand is on my list, but with a 35mm was not really possible. I would have to get so close that I would disturb them and get pain on the lens ;-) I need to go back with a longer lens to try to get some closeup of faces and hands.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>I actually tried more with a wider lens to get context information in the frame as much as possible.<br />From our discussion I got that dynamic can be added including things like people walking by, detailed of the sky or even the background. And even some more dramatic shots (more contrast)?&nbsp;<br />I love B&amp;W but I have not tried it here since I think color is a major part of the story.</p>\r\n<p>By the way on the second day I brought them coffee and \"Luxemburgli\" (a sweet specialty of Z&uuml;rich). They were very happy. I also already sent them some pictures that they can use. I got two new friends now. I am thinking of visiting them in their studio or on different events (when they are painting).&nbsp;</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 10:21:09','2015-05-12 10:21:09',NULL,NULL),(104,1068,'Attachment',106,'<p>Thanks. Again, another one of those small things... Ouch. Pity I liked this shot too...</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 10:23:42','2015-05-12 10:23:42',NULL,NULL),(105,1065,'Attachment',52,'<p>Try moving with him.&nbsp; If you get blur from the movement, this simply adds energy and indicates the artist\'s enthusiasm for his work.&nbsp; Point here is to \"interpret\" what is happening - through your own eyes, rather than merely \"documenting\" what is going on.&nbsp; Doing so brings not just \"content\" to your photos, but your own personal \"style\" of presenting it to the viewer.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 11:50:17','2015-05-12 11:50:17',NULL,NULL),(106,1066,'Attachment',52,'<p>Right.&nbsp; Both foreground subject and background are of equal importance.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 11:53:19','2015-05-12 11:53:19',NULL,NULL),(107,1067,'Attachment',106,'<p>I saw that too when I looked at the image on the computer. Another one of those small things...</p>\r\n<p>A question: do you usually shoot 3-4 times each time to see if one shot is better than the others? In this case should I shoot 3-4 shots quickly (I am not doing that now, I only shoot when I think is good) or try to get the one right? What is your tactic usually?</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 12:00:47','2015-05-12 12:00:47',NULL,NULL),(108,1067,'Attachment',52,'<p>My camera is always set to capture single shots, rather than bursts. If a situation / scene is rapidly moving, I will make a number of exposure (one at a time) and choose the best of the series.&nbsp; There are some situations (particularly where you as the photographer have been observing a situation for a while) where you can anticipate what and where a particular action is going happen next, be ready for it (exposure, etc. set) and capture it when \"it gets there.\"&nbsp; The image were discussing here may have come from such a situation, where one could see that the artist was going to enter that blue background space.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 12:04:27','2015-05-12 12:04:27',NULL,NULL),(109,1068,'Attachment',52,'<p>I still like the photo.&nbsp; Sometimes / oftentimes the smallest details can really make a difference - between a \"mediocre\" image and a really well-designed photograph.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 12:06:31','2015-05-12 12:06:31',NULL,NULL),(110,1069,'Attachment',52,'<p>For me, street art is about dynamism, energy, fluidity, action and movement, rather than a studio artist\'s typically more contemplative and \"quiet\" approach.&nbsp; That said, it is up the photographer to set the \"tone\" and \"pace\" of his or her photo story.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 12:09:09','2015-05-12 12:09:09',NULL,NULL),(111,1073,'Attachment',52,'<p>The harsh light is still there - on his shoulders.&nbsp; Yes, either the bright sun behind the wall or if you can move camera position enough , behind the artist\'s head. Another time of day would work, too.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 12:12:30','2015-05-12 12:12:30',NULL,NULL),(112,30,'AssignmentSubmission',52,'<p>Really good!&nbsp; Sounds like you\'ve now established some \"productive\" rapport.&nbsp; Such makes the more that much more enjoyable for both photographer and subject.&nbsp; You\'re correct about the B&amp;W, this is a story about \"color.\"&nbsp; Be on the lookout for all things related to being an artist outside in the hot sun - wiping the brow of sweat, between brush strokes, taking a drink of water, cleaning brushes at the end of the day.&nbsp; Focusing on one particular artist would be good too, capturing him in his own studio, etc - the \"whole story.\"</p>\r\n<p>David</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 12:15:36','2015-05-12 12:15:36',NULL,NULL),(113,1074,'Attachment',52,'<p>So much wall would work if there were something THERE - like a \"leading line\" of paint or design that carried the viewer\'s eye to the subject, the two artist&rsquo;s engaged in discussion.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 12:15:46','2015-05-12 12:15:46',NULL,NULL),(114,22,'AssignmentSubmission',66,'<p>Good morning Kseniya,</p>\r\n<p><br />I wanted to reach out to see if you are ready to upload additional images or if you are proceeding with lesson 3. &nbsp;Either way, I am here for you and can respond quickly to any questions you may have as you go forward with the lesson. &nbsp;I am looking forward to seeing your work! &nbsp;&nbsp;<br />Wishing you a great afternoon; sincerely, Allana</p>',NULL,'2015-05-13 08:03:30','2015-05-13 08:03:30',NULL,NULL),(115,22,'AssignmentSubmission',101,'<p>Hi, Allana!</p>\r\n<p>I\'m really sorry for my silence. I had much work these days. But I can say that I\'ve already done 2 last assignments and they are in process. So I\'ll send them you on thursday.&nbsp;<br />And if you are interested in my last project you can find it on my page in facebook. Your feedback is very important for me</p>\r\n<p>Have a good day, Kseniya</p>',NULL,'2015-05-13 08:15:24','2015-05-13 08:15:24',NULL,NULL),(116,22,'AssignmentSubmission',66,'<p>Hi Kseniya,</p>\r\n<p>That sounds great- I will take a look on your page; busy times for both of us! Looking forward to your new images; &nbsp;Allana</p>',NULL,'2015-05-13 08:16:55','2015-05-13 08:16:55',NULL,NULL),(117,967,'Attachment',70,'<p><strong>Critique by Meeta Khurana-Wolff on May 13, 2015</strong></p>\r\n<p>Hi there Nadine,</p>\r\n<p>It is my turn to apologize for the late feedback on your work. I was in London for my workshop and upon return got caught up in a big photo job! Sorry!</p>\r\n<p>Thank you for your submission of the first assignment. I see you only chose to do the exercises and not the assignment. After viewing your first images I think we will need a bit more practice. I understand you bought a new camera and are still getting acquainted with it.</p>\r\n<p>I see you are having issues with finding your focus properly that is mainly the reason why your images are not as sharp as they can be. Your set-up is fairly basic and I would like you to give this another try with slightly more elements. Try finding a nice background and place your fruit in a more voluptuous manner J Some in the back some in the front &ndash; maybe one or two cut up. The whole idea is to make the image appealing for the viewer. I know we are practicing the camera techniques here but as we move along I want you to consider these elements through each lesson. Please try taking all your images next to a window (as you will have read in the light lesson) as this offers the best most natural light for food images.</p>\r\n<p>Once you have created a smaller set-up then try your hand at the exercise again. Pinpoint where your focus is going to be and focus with the camera exactly there. A tripod is always helpful here. Now all you need to do is set your aperture to the same values you have here. I am sure you will be able to really see the difference.</p>\r\n<p>You said you got a 50mm lens and this is a prime lens with just one focal length only (in contrast to a zoom lens that covers a wider range of lengths). Prime lenses do not have the ability to zoom, so the photographer must move physically closer to or farther from their subject to achieve desired composition within the viewfinder\'s frame. Most lenses come equipped with a distance scale that allows the photographer to zone focus (judge appropriate focus based on estimated distance from the subject).</p>\r\n<p>  Focusing Through the Viewfinder:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Look through the camera\'s viewfinder window. Ensure that the lens is attached securely to the mount at the front of the camera.</li>\r\n<li>Point the camera toward your intended subject. Rotate the focus ring (located near the rear element of the lens, in front of the mounting threads) clockwise for far away subjects and counterclockwise for closer subjects. Fine tune your image by choosing a well-lit detail on which to focus. To start with try focusing on something closer to you / your lens.</li>\r\n<li>Adjust your aperture (size of lens diaphragm opening) to achieve the desired depth of field (DOF).   <strong><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">Remember:</span></strong> DOF refers to the range of effective focus in an image, or how much of the image can remain in focus at the aperture and shutter speed you have chosen. For example, if the foreground of an image is sharply focused and the background is blurred, it can be said to have a shallow DOF. If the foreground and background of an image are both sharply focused, it can be said to have a large DOF. Aperture ranges from f/1.7 to 5.6 will often provide shallow DOF, while f/8 to f/22 will provide larger DOF.</li>\r\n<li>If you are shooting in manual now set your shutter speed in relation to your aperture to achieve proper exposure.  <strong><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">Remember:</span></strong> As a general rule, larger f-stops (f/2.8, for example) will require a faster shutter speed, as the diaphragm is almost wide open at this stop. Smaller f-stops (f/16) will require a slower shutter speed, as the diaphragm is nearly closed at this stop.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>Here you will find a little bit more about Prime lenses:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.bhphotovideo.com/explora/photography/buying-guides/prime-lens-101\">http://www.bhphotovideo.com/explora/photography/buying-guides/prime-lens-101</a></p>\r\n<p>Let me know if you have any further question or are having difficulties.</p>\r\n<p>Meeta xo</p>',NULL,'2015-05-13 12:54:25','2015-05-13 12:54:25',NULL,NULL),(118,31,'AssignmentSubmission',52,'<p>Very good return work done for this assignment.&nbsp; \"Image-type-wise,\" your strongest images are attachment 6 as a wide-angle scene-setting shot (although you\'ve marked it as a \"middle-distance\" photo, which it probably could be too); attachment 4 as a strong middle-distance photo and attachment 3 as a strong \"detail\" or \"close-up\" photograph.&nbsp;<br />Attachments 1 and 2 are also good, but haven\'t the strength of the shots listed above.&nbsp; Attachments 9 and 10 I\'d place in this \"less strong\" category, as well.</p>\r\n<p>Let me know of questions and / comments.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-20 21:15:19','2015-05-20 21:15:19',NULL,NULL),(119,1076,'Attachment',52,'<p>Good \"scene-setting\" type of shot.&nbsp; Exactly what I mean by \"context.\"&nbsp; My only suggestion here would have been to hang here for a while and try to capture the artist (spray can) in hand, gesture with it toward his creation.&nbsp; This would have better identified the painter as such and at the same time, have added a sense of \"moment\" to the photo.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-20 21:15:26','2015-05-20 21:15:26',NULL,NULL),(120,1077,'Attachment',52,'<p>I think you\'ve done well with this wide-angle image.&nbsp; You\'ve \"controlled\" the expansive perspective well.&nbsp; The second artist appears in the background, there\'s no clutter and artist and fish appear to be eye-to-eye in contact.&nbsp; Plus the walkway is a strong \"leading line\" into the photo. Nice.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-20 21:15:31','2015-05-20 21:15:31',NULL,NULL),(121,1078,'Attachment',52,'<p>Still like it due to its \"filling the frame\" and colors (orange and blue are color-opposites, thus catch the eye of the viewer).</p>',NULL,'2015-05-20 21:15:36','2015-05-20 21:15:36',NULL,NULL),(122,1079,'Attachment',52,'<p>I agree.&nbsp; Good light, good color, interesting compostion and - a sense of \"moment\" with the artist\'s reach for a can.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-20 21:15:41','2015-05-20 21:15:41',NULL,NULL),(123,1080,'Attachment',52,'<p>I like this photo and the perspective you\'ve applied to it.&nbsp; A good \"middle distance\" shot.&nbsp; As for the background people, I like that they\'re softly-focused.&nbsp; However, having gotten down just a bit more would have kept visible the head of the girl in blue and this would have been better than placement behind the artist\'s arm.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-20 21:15:47','2015-05-20 21:15:47',NULL,NULL),(124,1081,'Attachment',52,'<p>One of your strongest here, too.&nbsp; Light, color, composition, sense of \"moment\" - all are really good.&nbsp; The sky is great.&nbsp; And really like the sunlight on the pantleg of the passerby.&nbsp; Only improvement would be to have gotten the pedestrian\'s uplifted foot just into the frame.&nbsp; Not a \"game spoiler,\" though.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-20 21:15:52','2015-05-20 21:15:52',NULL,NULL),(125,1082,'Attachment',52,'<p>I appreciate what you are saying.&nbsp; But at the same time, the artist\'s face is in sharpest focus, drawing the viewer\'s eyes and making HIM the Subject of this photo.&nbsp; The hand with spray can is in soft focus and not receiving the same amount of visual emphasis.&nbsp; If this is your intent - to make this shot more of a \"portrait\" of the artist, then fine.&nbsp; Thing is,&nbsp; - the artist is concentrating on his work (the can in hand), so by bringing more context to the area of paint application would have made for a stronger \"alternative\" to a portrait capture.&nbsp; Allowing for more context on the right side of the frame and getting close and focusing most critically on the hand holding can, would have made these elements the \"Subject,\" with the artist in softer focus, behind.&nbsp; This could well have made for a stronger photo - if in fact a \"portrait\" wasn\'t your exact intent.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-20 21:15:57','2015-05-20 21:15:57',NULL,NULL),(126,1083,'Attachment',52,'<p>Good.&nbsp; Uncluttered and strong composition, good colors and light - works well.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-20 21:16:02','2015-05-20 21:16:02',NULL,NULL),(127,1084,'Attachment',52,'<p>Nice perspective.&nbsp; The slight tilt brings an \"edgy-ness\" to the frame - fitting to the story subject.&nbsp; Not a \"game-spoiler\" here either, but watch out from now lines that intersect / touch with near exactness.&nbsp; Here I\'m speaking of the crown of the artist\'s head and the top line of the mural.&nbsp; Best to have the head slightly above or slightly below such a prominent line.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-20 21:16:07','2015-05-20 21:16:07',NULL,NULL),(128,1085,'Attachment',52,'<p>I think it\'s a good, sharp detail shot / close-up.&nbsp; Used in conjunction with the previous shot, it\'s quite clear what this paper is.&nbsp; But even at that, there enough of it here that the viewer assumes the paper is a photo / drawing from which the artist is working.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-20 21:16:12','2015-05-20 21:16:12',NULL,NULL),(129,1086,'Attachment',52,'<p>Not the most \"exciting\" detail shot, but it does work as a \"close-up\" / \"detail\" photo.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-20 21:16:17','2015-05-20 21:16:17',NULL,NULL),(130,1087,'Attachment',52,'<p>I like the expressiveness of this photo, but agree with you on the background.&nbsp; Perhaps a step backwards and a bit to the right would have served to include more to the left of the frame and eliminated the white plastic bag clutter on the right.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-20 21:16:22','2015-05-20 21:16:22',NULL,NULL),(131,32,'AssignmentSubmission',52,'<p>Good job with the start of this assignment.&nbsp; Do ask questions if you like and feel free to upload more images to this particular assignment.</p>\r\n<p>David</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 06:00:25','2015-05-21 06:00:25',NULL,NULL),(132,1088,'Attachment',52,'<p>Hi Suzette,&nbsp; First of all you lowered your ISO setting in this bright light to reach the photographic goal you were after.&nbsp; Great!&nbsp; This is an important step to understanding light and just how it affects the other parameters (shutter speed and aperture) of your picture.<br />This first image is really nice.&nbsp; The shutter speed setting of 1/1000 well \"froze\" the action of the bicycles against an in-focus / sharp background.&nbsp; What I really like about this photo are the individual shadows cast by the cyclists.&nbsp; This is of course a consequence of working in the \"contrasty\" (bright highlights / dark shadows) sunlight near high noon.&nbsp; And if such an effect you are after, this is the best time of day to reach it - lots of graphic possibilities.</p>\r\n<p>Notice too that the light as high-noon is neared (and directly thereafter), the color \"temperture\" is almost white (a mix of red, green and blue that your camera\'s sensor is sensitive to).&nbsp; In my post-processed example of your photo above, I\'ve balanced this light color, moving it a bit more to the yellow side of the temperature spectrum.&nbsp; I\'ve also cropped your photo to allow more space for the bicyclists to move \"into.\"&nbsp; As a general rule, leave a bit more space in front than behind objects in forward motion.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 06:00:30','2015-05-21 06:00:30',NULL,NULL),(133,1089,'Attachment',52,'<p>At a shutter speed setting of 1/30 sec. you did get a blur on the moving bicycles.&nbsp; However, you also rendered the background somewhat out of focus.&nbsp; I\'m guessing you moved the camera a little as you squeezed the shutter button for this shot.&nbsp; Had you pre-focused sharply on the pavement where the bicyclists would ride, waiting steadily for their approach and then gently squeezing the shutter button as they reached your pre-focus mark, you would have ended up with the blurred / \"swooshed\" line of bikes against a completely in-focus / sharp background.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 06:00:44','2015-05-21 06:00:44',NULL,NULL),(134,1090,'Attachment',52,'<p>Really nice.&nbsp; The streak of red from the moving headlights is dramatic.&nbsp; The diagonal line \"drawn\" through the frame adds to the enery (i.e. diagonal lines bring dynamism and energy to compositions).&nbsp; What would have improved this shot, however, is to have used a tripod or some other means of steadying your camera for the shot.&nbsp; That is, had the yellow street sign been sharply in focus, this would have increased the feel of speed and energy in this photo.&nbsp; When reaching shutter speeds below 1/4 sec., it is really important to stabilize your camera by some means, if not wanting \"camera shake\" to inter the exposure \"formula\" too.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 06:00:54','2015-05-21 06:00:54',NULL,NULL),(135,1076,'Attachment',106,'<p>I agree. But the artist actually never went in the direction of the wall. It actually went away for a while. But I see your point.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 08:39:31','2015-05-21 08:39:31',NULL,NULL),(136,1077,'Attachment',106,'<p>Thanks David. I actually like the \"missing clutter\". It gives the idea of the dimension of the wall. The \"leading line\" suggestion it is also helpful, thanks.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 08:40:35','2015-05-21 08:40:35',NULL,NULL),(137,1078,'Attachment',106,'<p>I find it interesting that you classify this shot as close-up. I may need to review my classification...</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 08:41:45','2015-05-21 08:41:45',NULL,NULL),(138,1080,'Attachment',106,'<p>Thanks David. I agree with the head. Another one of the small point that I need to pay attention too. Sometime (from missing practice I guess) I am so focused on the main subject, that I forget the small details and background.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 08:42:51','2015-05-21 08:42:51',NULL,NULL),(139,1082,'Attachment',106,'<p>Thanks for the comments. I agree with you on everything you said. But I still kind of find it interesting, but I know what you mean and try to apply your suggestions.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 08:43:46','2015-05-21 08:43:46',NULL,NULL),(140,1083,'Attachment',106,'<p>Thanks.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 08:44:31','2015-05-21 08:44:31',NULL,NULL),(141,1084,'Attachment',106,'<p>Ok. I tried to pay attention to such things