used sharply on it with a wide-open aperture and made your photo.&nbsp; As is (on its side), it may be too \"nondescript\" / unidentifiable for some viewers.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 09:53:01','2015-05-21 09:53:01',NULL,NULL),(149,1093,'Attachment',52,'<p>Not super exciting, but perhaps stronger (content-wise) than Attachment #10 above.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 09:53:06','2015-05-21 09:53:06',NULL,NULL),(150,1095,'Attachment',52,'<p>Hi Suzette - This photo turned out pretty well in Program (Auto Exposure) mode.&nbsp; However, the landscape is a little underexposed. The reason for this, is that your camera\'s light meter system read the large area of bright sky and attempted to bring its light down to \"middle gray.\"&nbsp; In doing this, the already darker landscape was reduced in exposure, as well.&nbsp; Understanding how a camera\'s light meter operates in this way to yield an image that is balanced for so-called \"18 percent\" or \"middle gray,\" the photographer will consider such a \"contrasty\" (extremes between highlights and shadows within the scene) and compensate by adding one or two stops exposure to this camera \"decision\" in Program mode.&nbsp; The way to do this, is to address your camera\'s \"exposure compensation\" adjustment.&nbsp; Depending on your camera modes, this can be a button or a dial.&nbsp; Go to it and add +1 for one shot and try the same scene, adjusting by +2.&nbsp; Via this process, you can make the most \"pleasing\" exposure from choices you are now offered.</p>\r\n<p>I post-processed this photo using Adobe Lightroom software to simulate just what adding a couple of stops (via \"exposure compensation\") to do for this auto-exposed photo.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 14:19:44','2015-05-21 14:19:44',NULL,NULL),(151,33,'AssignmentSubmission',52,'<p>Good job with this first assignment, Suzette.&nbsp; This basic camera / exposure information can represent a rather steep learning curve, but once it\'s fully understood, the door to creativity is wide open.&nbsp; You\'ll look at a subject or scene and consider just how you want to make of it photographically - choosing either shutter speed or aperture as your priority setting.&nbsp; Once you understand how exposure works, you\'ll be using aperture-priority, shutter-priority or manual mode most of the time.&nbsp; Fully automatic \"Program Mode\" will be there when you want to capture moments that are unfolding quickly - and the most important issue is to capture the scene as fast as possible with the best exposure decision the camera can, automatically, make for you in that instant.</p>\r\n<p>Let me know what questions you have surrounding any of my explanations, because all of these aspects of camera control for creativity are of \"foundation\" importance. The better you understand them now, the greater freedom and fun you\'ll have with your camera and photography in the future.</p>\r\n<p>Cheers,<br />David</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 14:31:06','2015-05-21 14:31:06',NULL,NULL),(152,1096,'Attachment',52,'<p>Same situation here (i.e. bright(er) sky and shadowed landscape.&nbsp; Once again I simulated the addition of a couple of \"stops\" of exposure via the \"exposure compensation\" of the camera.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\"Contrasty\" light is tricky for a camera\'s light meter to deal with.&nbsp; The photographer can either work one light \"type\" or the other for evenly-exposed results.&nbsp; When this isn\'t possible or desired, \"exposure compensation\" is the adjustment to go to.</p>\r\n<p>With this compensational change, highlights begin to appear on the ridge lines of the foreground hills, adding additional atmosphere and interest to the photograph.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 14:31:12','2015-05-21 14:31:12',NULL,NULL),(153,1097,'Attachment',52,'<p>As you\'ve captured in this photo, setting aperture to a high depth of field setting (i.e. f18) has given you a photo that is sharp throughout - from foreground to extreme background.&nbsp; And with such a great depth of field (DOF), no real \"subject\" in the composition has been defined.&nbsp; Nothing stand out in particular.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Now if a lizard were sharply in focus on the slab to the right, the eye would go right to it, simply because it would be \"other than\" just layers of sedimentary stone.&nbsp; If there were such lizards in the background, as well, such a great DOF would indicate a strong relationship between foreground lizard and background reptiles.&nbsp; Reducing DOF and focusing sharply on a \"foreground lizard\" would lessen the relationship between foreground (\"Subject\" of the composition) and like creatures in a now out-of-focus background.&nbsp; See how DOF (f-stop setting) can be creatively used by the photographer to placed either greater or lesser emphasis on a subject - and how strength of relationship between foreground and background can be creatively affected by aperture choice?</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 14:31:20','2015-05-21 14:31:20',NULL,NULL),(154,1098,'Attachment',52,'<p>Good example of shallow DOF.&nbsp; Here it appears that you have focused sharply on the middle section of rock, throwing both the foreground and background out-of-focus / \"softer,\" drawing greatest interest to this area and relegating foreground and background to \"not-so-related\" status.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 14:31:31','2015-05-21 14:31:31',NULL,NULL),(155,1099,'Attachment',52,'<p>Well you did, but in the opposition direction of how this exposure relationship works.&nbsp; That is, having \"prioritized\" shutter speed over DOF setting (aperture), you\'ve ended up with a shallow DOF that emphasizes the sharply-in-focus flower, but a high shutter speed that has absolutely \"frozen\" any movement an existent wind might have caused.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Having first thought, I want this flower to blur a little in the wind to show movement, you would have made the priority setting choice of shutter speed, but a slow one (e.g. 1/15 sec or 1/8 sec.).&nbsp; Setting sharp focus on the flower and hand-holding your camera as steady as possible, the resultant photo would have been a somewhat blurred plant and flower, set within a aharp context, from foreground to background.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Refer again to the diagram presented here,, showing the inverse relationship between aperture and shutter speed.&nbsp; Keep in mind that the photographer must make a creative choice when approaching just how he or she wants their photo to look like.&nbsp; Is blurring or freezing motion of priority importance.&nbsp; Then it\'s shutter speed to first consider.&nbsp; If emphasizing subject or a specific area of the scene is of priority importance for the photo, then it\'s DOF - aperture that you want to use first.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 14:31:41','2015-05-21 14:31:41',NULL,NULL),(156,1100,'Attachment',52,'<p>You must have been quite close to this flower to obtain an out-of-focus background of this degree.&nbsp; I say that because f5.6 would have normally resulted in greater background clarity / sharpness than this.&nbsp; The reason for this \"discrepancy\" is that the closer the camera is to the subject, regardless of aperture set or lens focal length, the more out-of-focus with be that which lies behind the sharply focused on subject.</p>\r\n<p>And since you\'ve set a priority shutter speed so high, you would have captured this still flower - rock solid - even in a strong wind.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 14:31:51','2015-05-21 14:31:51',NULL,NULL),(157,1095,'Attachment',112,'<p>I see the difference in the landscape, David.</p>\r\n<p>Are you talking about white balance here? Is this where checking the infograph of the RGB helps? My friend who\'s in photography mentioned a little bit about white balance which I think you cover in the next lesson.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>How much should I rely on post-processing for my photos? Or should I try to address all exposure needs during shooting?&nbsp;</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 14:33:54','2015-05-21 14:33:54',NULL,NULL),(158,1097,'Attachment',112,'<p>Yes! Thank for the explanation. I found that it was \"easier\" to play around with aperture settings more. If I am shooting at a high DOF, should there always be a \"subject\"? I see what you mean that nothing really stands out. I had one shot of a catepillar within the same sand structure but it wasn\'t angled, so I didn\'t think it was a good example.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 14:35:39','2015-05-21 14:35:39',NULL,NULL),(159,1099,'Attachment',112,'<p>Ok, thanks for that explanation, and how to approach taking photos. The guide will be handy. It\'s helpful to hear what questions I need to ask myself. They say you need to hear something at least (7) times before you get it, right? hahaha...I will need to practice this mode more. So, like the aperture mode, if I prioritize shutter mode, the camera should automatically decide which f-stop to use, correct? Or will I need to figure that out too?</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 14:36:38','2015-05-21 14:36:38',NULL,NULL),(160,1100,'Attachment',112,'<p>Yes, I was really close to this flower trying to get it in focus but I wasn\'t sure what I was trying to do in this photo. But now I know I needed to use lower shutter speed.&nbsp;</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 14:37:29','2015-05-21 14:37:29',NULL,NULL),(161,1095,'Attachment',52,'<p>Best to address exposure while shooting, Suzette.&nbsp; Exposure and white balance are related.&nbsp; Exposure has to do with the combination of shutter, aperture and ISO to obtain enough light to expose a photograph properly.&nbsp; White balance has to do with color \"temperature\" - the quality of light you are photographing in (e.g. sunlight at different times of day, incandescent or florescent light).</p>\r\n<p>I try to keep post-processing to a minimum.&nbsp; Specifically, I might tweak the exposure setting, highlights, shadows, contrast and finally sharpen the image a little.&nbsp; Post-process cropping a very rarely do.&nbsp; I try always to frame the scene the way I want while looking through the viewfinder.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 14:46:06','2015-05-21 14:46:06',NULL,NULL),(162,1097,'Attachment',52,'<p>Photographs consist of both Subject and Background and both are important to the visual&nbsp; \'statement\" the photographer wants to make.&nbsp; The Subject gives the viewer\'s eyes a place to come to rest on (as emphasis), after looking through the entire picture.&nbsp; Without a defined (to some degree) Subject, the viewer becomes confused as to just why the photograph was made, just what the photographer is attemping to \"say.\"</p>\r\n<p>Furthermore, a Subject should be supported (thematically and logically) by the background it is associated with.&nbsp; The higher the depth of field, the stronger the relationship between Subject and its supporting Background is - the photographer is attempting to \"demonstrate\" this relationship in a strong way by setting a high DOF.</p>\r\n<p>Conversely, if a background does not logically fit with / support the subject - and it is impossible to eliminate it by changing perspective, the photographer can set a shallow DOF (e.g. f2.8 or f4) to blur / soften the background and this \"weaken\" the relationship communicated to the viewer.&nbsp; If a background is confusing and busy, best to set a wide aperture to \"neutralize\" it\'s role in the photo, thus placing greatest attention on the Subject, defined by its sharp focus emphasis.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 14:46:11','2015-05-21 14:46:11',NULL,NULL),(163,1099,'Attachment',52,'<p>Correct - in Shutter Priority Mode, you set the speed you want to achieve the visual message and effect you want to achieve and the camera will automatically set aperture to give you a proper exposure for the scene, based on the camera\'s system of \"middle gray / 18 percent gray exposure programming.&nbsp; Same with Aperture Priority Mode - set aperture and camera auto-selects shutter speed to render proper exposure (again, based on 18 percent / middle gray camera programming).</p>\r\n<p>Try this exercise: Place your camera on full manual and set either shutter speed or aperture for a particular scene.&nbsp; Then change either to reach what your camera tells you is a \"proper\" exposure for the scene. NOW - go to the next highest aperture setting (i.e. 1 stop more exposure).&nbsp; To maintain proper exposure you will have to now go to the next slowest shutter speed.&nbsp; The result: You have a greater DOF, but a slower shutter speed to work with.&nbsp; If you add two stops more aperture, you\'ll need to reduce shutter speed by 2 stops to maintain a proper exposure.&nbsp; SO - go ahead a play with this shutter speed - aperture relationship a bit to get a feel for just what the camera is doing when you are using aperture or shutter priority modes.&nbsp; Take another look at the diagram above and keep in mind that shutter speed and aperture work IN DIFFERENT DIRECTIONS.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 14:46:21','2015-05-21 14:46:21',NULL,NULL),(164,1100,'Attachment',52,'<p>If there is no wind blowing and the flower is perfectly still, there is no need to stop motion with a high shutter speed setting. It could be done with 1/30 or 1/60 sec., which would give you a high DOF.&nbsp; Keep in mind: the slower the shutter speed, the higher / greater will be the DOF; the faster / higher the shutter speed set, the shallower will be the DOF.&nbsp; Again, take a look at the diagram above.</p>\r\n<p>And again too, the closer you are to your subject, the shallower will be the DOF behind it. This holds true for lenses of any focal length.&nbsp; However with wide angles lenses, the wider they are (e.g. 20mm, 14mm) the less this \"soft\" effect will be.&nbsp; The longer the lens, the greater the effect.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 14:46:31','2015-05-21 14:46:31',NULL,NULL),(165,967,'Attachment',105,'<p><strong>Comment by Nadine Chamaa on May 21, 2015</strong></p>\r\n<p>Hi Meeta.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>i am sorry for the delay. I am overwhelmed with the courses,the camera. and my blog ! i am stillan alien to my camera ,its is controlling me still.on friday a friend is coming over to explain a bit about all the options of my cam, i am a slow learner, i already started taking pictures for my food blog with the camera( my exercise) if u have facebook u can check , the kitchen babe.On monday i will submit to you the homework, pls dont kick me out of the class lol</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 16:37:01','2015-05-21 16:37:01',NULL,NULL),(166,34,'AssignmentSubmission',70,'<p><strong>Critique Summary by Meeta Khurana-Wolff on May 20, 2015</strong></p>\r\n<p>Awesome Reef! I have now access to the secret boards and will go through them this evening and then get the next lesson ready based on what I see.</p>\r\n<p>For now I am so happy that you found this exercise helpful and were able to list down the points and the &ldquo;style&rdquo; you seem to be connecting with. The very first steps to finding out where we can begin and what your voice is all about.</p>\r\n<p>Do not feel intimidated by the path you (we) need to take to get to where you want to be &hellip; it&rsquo;s a process and you will grow as we progress during this mentorship and also later. The important thing is to keep feeding those boards &ndash; the public ones but we will start filling up the secret ones and these will be the basis for your portfolio.</p>\r\n<p>With regards to your positing statement I want you to have another go. Not because what you have written is not good but this would be more fitting as part of an about you page. A position statement in my eyes tells the client your passion and how you work it.</p>\r\n<p>My position statement on my portfolio is this :</p>\r\n<p><em>Over the past several years I have taught myself everything I know about food photography and&nbsp;styling, developing a style to create tempting and mouth-watering food images. My perspective is&nbsp;unconventional and I am not afraid to break certain rules to capture the perfect shot.</em></p>\r\n<p><em>I love each aspect of creating an appealing and stunning food picture. From preparing the dish, using fresh ingredients to styling, propping, color, lighting and texture, I work with a dedication to each detail. My own personal passion is keeping the image as natural as possible, using natural light and food that has not been \"treated.&rdquo;</em></p>\r\n<p><em>Clients can expect diligence and commitment from me to meet their needs and accomplish their objectives.&nbsp;I prepare, style and photograph each subject to match my clients\' vision and have a resourceful and fully equipped studio and kitchen, which helps me to achieve your goals. I am available for cookbook, editorial, website, catalog, packaging or advertising assignments as well as writing food related articles and&nbsp;recipe development.</em></p>\r\n<p>A friend of mine has this: &ldquo;&hellip;. is a portrait photographer who specializes in real soulful imagery. Her photographs are authentic and raw and create a sense of intrigue to the viewer. She sees beauty in the everyday. Her images primarily utilize natural lighting, which showcase a sense of production and style. Odessa finds unnoticed moments that last. Her work can be seen in editorial magazines to commercial advertising.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>So for you - &nbsp;go back to the above list you created about what connects you with your style and create a few lines that you would like your client to know what makes you and your work special. Do not worry if you do not have experience etc. that is not the point of a position statement! It is an about page that tells the client how/where you have worked and how you got here.</p>\r\n<p>In the meantime I will write up the next assignment after I have viewed the images.</p>\r\n<p>Let me know if you have any questions</p>\r\n<p>Xo Meeta</p>',NULL,'2015-05-22 06:41:51','2015-05-22 06:41:51',NULL,NULL),(167,34,'AssignmentSubmission',111,'<p><strong>Comment by Reef Fakhoury on May 21, 2015</strong></p>\r\n<p>Thanks Meeta!</p>\r\n<p>Here goes my second attempt (I will also try uploading the word document but last time it wasn\'t working on this site. If it is not uploaded here, please let me know if you would like for me to share it via email).</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">Food is a universal language of joy and of love. I once heard that the people who give you their food, give you their hearts. This sums up why I love food, and from where my passion for capturing images of food stems.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">Over the past several years I have learnt a great deal about Food and Beverage Photography, starting off by &lsquo;learning by seeing&rsquo;, followed by &lsquo;learning by doing&rsquo;. This has given me an immaculate eye for detail, and has solidified my style. I capture images that stay true to the subject through the use of natural light, my personal preference, and through styling that incorporates farm fresh ingredients that are used to create the dish. This approach is an honest one, through which I aim to honor the dish and ensure that it is not lost in any clutter.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>Clients can expect dedication, commitment and undivided attention to complete the job having achieved the vision and style within the given time-frame.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-22 06:44:55','2015-05-22 06:44:55',NULL,NULL);
