What makes this photo \"work,\" is the simplicity of subject, composition and color (few and related colors make for the strongest photos.)</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The second image, make in Istanbul, Turkey, is permeated with \"strength\" and \"determination\" of this demonstrator.&nbsp; I was very close to this subject, using a 24mm lens.&nbsp; I set a wide aperture (e.g. f2.8) to soften the background of fellow protestors, to place stronger emphasis on the foreground subject.&nbsp; Of course he knew I was right there photographing him, so he put even greater energy into his \"call for action.\"</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Thanks for these comments and discussion, Zain.&nbsp; Also, I welcome you to complete this lesson assignment.&nbsp; I would much like to see your own work.&nbsp; Let me know if you have any questions.</p>',NULL,'2015-02-24 05:24:09','2015-02-24 05:24:09'),(30,80,119,'<p>Incredibal india</p>',NULL,'2015-02-24 05:34:09','2015-02-24 05:34:09'),(31,80,119,'<p>`. Monk Pick - Monks position in frame creates a very strong and static picture. Giving a strong sense of movement (That the monk is moving out of the frame and heading somewhere\"&nbsp; The sense of movement also creates mystery, Where is he heading?</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>2. Instanbul Pic -&nbsp; Powerfull and expressive pic.&nbsp; Mans raised hand forms a interesting line that puts emphasis on \'Form\" Colourfull red flags also helps with the composition putting emphasis on the Main Point of interest.&nbsp;</p>',NULL,'2015-02-24 05:36:28','2015-02-24 05:36:28'),(32,66,117,'<p>How are you student ??</p>',NULL,'2015-02-24 06:03:47','2015-02-24 06:03:47'),(33,66,117,'<p>hi</p>',NULL,'2015-02-24 07:41:07','2015-02-24 07:41:07'),(34,71,167,'<p>Test, test, test the discussion area</p>',NULL,'2015-02-24 12:03:08','2015-02-24 12:03:08'),(35,83,174,'<p>&nbsp;Nice to be on this course.</p>',NULL,'2015-02-24 14:49:18','2015-02-24 14:49:18'),(36,71,193,'<p>Which types of shorter lenses would you suggest using?</p>',NULL,'2015-02-27 08:56:49','2015-02-27 08:56:49'),(37,71,192,'<p>&nbsp;Hi This course is good.</p>',NULL,'2015-02-27 10:25:58','2015-02-27 10:25:58'),(38,52,192,'<p>yes</p>',NULL,'2015-02-28 12:07:12','2015-02-28 12:07:12'),(39,80,119,'<p>good lesson</p>',NULL,'2015-03-02 07:09:42','2015-03-02 07:09:42'),(40,66,119,'<p>yes</p>',NULL,'2015-03-02 07:10:49','2015-03-02 07:10:49'),(41,66,119,'<p>good course</p>',NULL,'2015-03-02 09:38:46','2015-03-02 09:38:46'),(42,66,118,'<p>&nbsp;good images</p>',NULL,'2015-03-02 10:30:21','2015-03-02 10:30:21'),(43,80,223,'<p>The most important part of this first lesson is what the famed American landscape photographer</p>',NULL,'2015-03-28 11:13:35','2015-03-28 11:13:35'),(44,80,222,'<p>Best of luck and have fun with this assignment!</p>',NULL,'2015-03-30 09:16:24','2015-03-30 09:16:24'),(45,70,249,'<p><strong>13 days ago - Meeta Khurana-Wolff  </strong></p>\r\n<p>Hello and a&nbsp;very warm welcome to you Kara and Vineet (again). Hope you are well and ready to dive into the world of food photography and styling with me. Vineet hope this course works better for you. ;) Over the next couple of weeks we\'ll be spending intensive time with each other and I hope to guide you through the challenges and difficulties you have been having with your food photography. &nbsp;I am really looking forward to it.&nbsp;  Please read through your lessons carefully ... do not be intimidated. If you have any questions along the way feel free to ask them in the discussion area. Being a small group I am quite excited that we can work one-on-one with each other. I would like to encourage that as a group you give feedback / ask questions on each other\'s photographs as well. This brings in different viewpoints and maybe allow us to view the images on different levels. &nbsp;  I am also very interested in knowing what camera, equipment, lens etc. you both are using - do you use a tripod etc.? It will give me a better idea and also help me make suggestions if necessary.&nbsp;  When you complete your assignments and exercises please do give me as much detail about the image as you can. The technical details (f stops, ISO etc.) but also where the light was coming from, your workflow and process and any challenges you faced would help me get a better insight on the images you submit and your thought process.&nbsp;  Enjoy yourself with lesson one and remember there are no dumb questions ... ask me whatever you are unsure of.&nbsp;  Warmly,&nbsp;  Meeta </p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>12 days ago - Vineet Chhatwal  </strong></p>\r\n<p>Thanks Meeta.   I have been using an iPhone and Nexus 5 mostly for taking food pics (instagram feed vin_chhatwal). I don\'t edit the pics much in order to communicate \"what I saw is what I reflect\". That said, I do sometimes adjust some parameters using the basic tools that these devices have.  I have a Cannon Powershot G15 and can get a tripod. I reckon this should be a good start and I can possibly upgrade to something else as my understanding develops a bit more. I have seen so many of my friends pick up these awesome camera bodies and lenses only to then point and shoot in auto mode all the time.  The reason for this course is simple, I want to take better food pics as I am working to open a health food delivery business shortly. Since we won\'t have a dine-in space, social media (and the food pics) will be the primary mode of marketing. We will hire a pro initially to help us get off the ground but I love food too much to not dig into it :-)!  Hope this helps to explain the context somewhat. I am looking forward to working &nbsp;closely with you.    Best regards.    Vineet.  &nbsp;   </p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>12 days ago - Vineet Chhatwal  </strong></p>\r\n<p>And of course...Hi Kara.  Its a pleasure to make your acquaintance here.   </p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>12 days ago - Vineet Chhatwal  </strong></p>\r\n<p>Got some clue about Aperture and depth of field after messing around with my camera. Still don\'t feel in control but guess that is practice. Will click and upload some images tomorrow.  Best regards.   </p>\r\n<p><br /><strong>11 days ago - Kara Hudgens  </strong></p>\r\n<p>Hello Meeta and Vineet!</p>\r\n<p>  I\'m looking forward to working with you both in this class. &nbsp;I\'ve been photographing for a while but hope to develop my skills in composition, color usage, finding an appropriate focal point... etc - for still life and food photography. &nbsp;Finding the right angle to shoot from is challenging to me. &nbsp;I shoot with a Nikon D800 and will mainly use an 85mm or 60mm macro, I think. &nbsp;I\'ll use a tripod as well.  Hope to get into the first assignment this weekend-&nbsp;  Cheers-  Kara </p>\r\n<p><strong>4 days ago - Meeta Khurana-Wolff</strong>  </p>\r\n<p>Hi there Nicky welcome to our course! Looking forward to working with you over the next several weeks. In this course we are already working towards the first assignment with Vineet and Kara. As I mentioned in my first comment above&nbsp;I am very interested in knowing what camera, equipment, lens etc. you are using - do you use a tripod etc.? It will give me a better idea and also help me make suggestions if necessary.  Let me know if you have any questions or are \"stuck\" with anything.&nbsp;  Vineet: yes upgrading once you feel better about photography is always better. I have to say that over the past 2 years I am a big fan of mobile photography but mainly because I love Instgram. Having said that these devises can never replace a proper camera. I am very keen to see how you progress with your Canon Powershot - will you also be using the mobile devises for the assignments? Many aspects in my assignments actually focus on photography with a camera (primarily a DSLR but also Digital &amp; &nbsp;POS so you should be fine. Let me know if you have trouble with any of the assignments.&nbsp;  Kara: I think a you will find all the help and guidance in the lessons for your goal.&nbsp;  To all three of you YES to a tripod!! You\'ll find it helps on many levels. So Now I am looking forward to all your assignments.&nbsp;  Have fun! </p>\r\n<p><strong>3 days ago - Nicky Weber</strong></p>\r\n<p>  Hi Meeta, Kara and Vineet</p>\r\n<p>  I&rsquo;m really looking forward to this course and working with the three of you.&nbsp; I currently live in Australia although I am originally from South Africa (Meeta &ndash; I went to school with Jeanne!)  My dad has been into photography ever since I can remember and a few years ago recommended the Canon Mark II to me when I was ready to upgrade from my point and shoot camera.&nbsp; So I have this beautiful camera and the 70 &ndash; 300mm lens which I absolutely love.&nbsp; I bought a 50mm lens as most food photographers use it but haven&rsquo;t found it successful with food but rather people.&nbsp; I do own a tripod and even have a lighting kit (which I&rsquo;m yet to get into). I try to shoot manual but want to get a tether cable so that I can ensure that I have focussed properly.  The reason for doing this course is that I am working on my own little recipe book of Italian food &ndash; it is a personal project rather than something that I will sell one day.&nbsp; I haven&rsquo;t found my own style yet and instead of coming up with my own food layout I go through my two files of magazine photographs that I like for inspiration.&nbsp; I am hoping that the assignments will push me a bit to be more creative and find my own voice.&nbsp; I used to shoot a lot of top down shots but have been trying to do more vertical shots.&nbsp;   I&rsquo;ve always enjoyed your website and photos Meeta and was so delighted to find that you had an online course.&nbsp;   I&rsquo;m away from Friday for the weekend and with the lack of light before and after work will only be able to complete the first two assignments by 18/19 April.&nbsp; I&rsquo;ll be reading through the lessons whilst travelling to Jindabyne.  Have a great weekend everyone and look forward to seeing your posts Kara and Vineet!   </p>\r\n<p>Nicky</p>',NULL,'2015-04-12 12:08:54','2015-04-12 12:08:54'),(46,52,309,'<p>Hello Sejuti, </p>\r\n<p>Welcome to the course!&nbsp; Two questions I have for you:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>&nbsp;What (generally speaking) is your background in photography?</li>\r\n<li>&nbsp;What type of subject / topic are you interested to work on for your photo essay?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>Looking forward to working with you on this.<br />David</p>',NULL,'2015-04-13 14:13:12','2015-04-13 14:13:12'),(47,104,308,'<p>Dir Sir,</p>\r\n<p>Thank you for offering this opportunity to learn through online interaction. I am not so sure of the choice of subject. But I am uploading one based on the theme which was my primary reason to join this course. I am a development worker. I wanted to be able to document the work of my organisation in a better way.</p>\r\n<p>The set of photographs are selected based on the same. However, since the organisation works in remote Himalayan districts, access could be an issue. So I am planning to upload another set, which is comparatively easy in terms of access. Please let me know what you think.</p>\r\n<p>Sincerely, </p>\r\n<p>Sejuti Basu</p>',NULL,'2015-04-14 09:15:22','2015-04-14 09:15:22'),(48,104,308,'<p>Dear Sir,</p>\r\n<p>I realised I can submit only one assignment and there is no scope to upload the second choice that I had in mind. In that case, I\'d like to stick to the first assignment submitted since that is the option that I really care for and is the reason I joined this course. Hope to hear from you soon.</p>\r\n<p>Sincerely,<br />Sejuti</p>',NULL,'2015-04-14 09:19:58','2015-04-14 09:19:58'),(49,70,249,'<h3>about 19 hours ago - Meeta Khurana-Wolff</h3>\r\n<p>Hello Nadine and welcome to the group. We are underway with the assignments and have already one submission.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>As I mentioned in my initial comment to the group&nbsp;read through your lessons carefully ... do not be intimidated. If you have any questions along the way feel free to ask them in the discussion area. Being a small group I am quite excited that we can work one-on-one with each other. I would like to enourage that as a group you give feedback / ask questions on each other\'s photographs as well. This brings in different viewpoints and maybe allow us to view the images on different levels. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>I am also very interested in knowing what camera, equipment, lens etc. you both are using - do you use a tripod etc.? It will give me a better idea and also help me make suggestions if neccessary.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>When you complete your assignments and exercises please do give me as much detail about the image as you can. The technical details (f stops, ISO etc.) but also where the light was coming from, your workflow and process and any challenges you faced would help me get a better insight on the images you submit and your thought process.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Nicky: saw Jeanne in Vienna this weekend and she says hi to you too. Hope you two connect via FB ... glad it was me that brought you together again!</p>\r\n<p>Kara: I am now on my way to check out your assignment ;) Thank you for being patient. We had an awesome workshop in Vienna .. went down very well.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>I hope the others are doing fine ... just wondering if you have any questions or are having trouble with anything as you have not submitted any assignments. Please feel free to ask questions.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Warmly,&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Meeta</p>',NULL,'2015-04-22 13:38:03','2015-04-22 13:38:03'),(50,105,249,'<p>Hi Meeta,</p>\r\n<p>thank you very much , i started reading the first course but for now i have only an iphone5 camera, during the week end i am purchasing The camera, i was thinking of getting a nikon and it has to be digital SLR.right ? I was adviced to get a Nikon D800 but its not SLR. so what do u suggest?</p>',NULL,'2015-04-22 13:45:20','2015-04-22 13:45:20'),(51,100,251,'<h3>0 days ago - Nicky Weber</h3>\r\n<p>Thanks Meeta. &nbsp;Just returned from beautiful Jindabyne in the Snowy Mountains. &nbsp;Will catch up with the first three assignments by 19th April. &nbsp;Regards</p>\r\n<p>Nicky</p>',NULL,'2015-04-22 13:58:29','2015-04-22 13:58:29'),(52,100,251,'<p>7 days ago - Meeta Khurana-Wolff  </p>\r\n<p>That is perfectly fine Nicky!  I am off to Vienna tomorrow for my workshop (I will be with Jeanne by the way! She says hi and was totally flaberghasted LOL!) and will return Sunday evening. So I will be able to get to your assignment next week!  </p>\r\n<p>Warmly,&nbsp;  Meeta</p>',NULL,'2015-04-22 14:04:14','2015-04-22 14:04:14'),(53,70,251,'<p>7 days ago - Meeta Khurana-Wolff  </p>\r\n<p>That is perfectly fine Nicky!  I am off to Vienna tomorrow for my workshop (I will be with Jeanne by the way! She says hi and was totally flaberghasted LOL!) and will return Sunday evening. So I will be able to get to your assignment next week!  </p>\r\n<p>Warmly,&nbsp;  Meeta</p>',NULL,'2015-04-22 14:07:16','2015-04-22 14:07:16'),(54,70,249,'<p>5 days ago - Meeta Khurana-Wolff<br />Hi there Nadine!</p>\r\n<p> For the camera: it depends on your budget really. But you should go for a DSLR - it does not have to be a high end one for now if your budget does not allow it but a middle class camera would be fine and then invest in some really good lenses. I think you will be happier with that solution for the beginning.  </p>\r\n<p>Good lenses to have are the prime lenses 50 mm and the 85 mm and then a zoom lens the 24-70mm is great (talking about CANON).</p>\r\n<p> Good mid range cameras are the Canon EOS 70D or if you want to go lower on budget the EOS 700D is also good. (again CANON)</p>\r\n<p> LOL! Nikon is great too but can you tell which brand I use? ;)</p>',NULL,'2015-04-27 07:54:32','2015-04-27 07:54:32'),(55,105,249,'<p>4 days ago - Nadine Chamaa</p>\r\n<p>Lol Ok i will go towards Canon ! Thank you Meeta :)</p>',NULL,'2015-04-27 07:56:27','2015-04-27 07:56:27'),(56,105,249,'<p>21 minutes ago - Nadine Chamaa</p>\r\n<p>Hi Meeta, i got an EOS 70D with a 50 mn lense and a zoom lens. But i have lots of questions! i ask them here?</p>',NULL,'2015-04-27 09:20:57','2015-04-27 09:20:57'),(57,52,158,'<p>3 days ago - David Bathgate<br />Hello Umberto and welcome to the documentary course.&nbsp; Good to have you aboard.&nbsp; Before we get started here, it would be nice to know a bit about your background as a photographer.&nbsp; Also, have you already an idea or two concerning story topics / subjects for the course?</p>\r\n<p>Let me know too if you have any questions as we begin this first week of working together.<br />Cheers<br />David</p>',NULL,'2015-05-07 07:49:45','2015-05-07 07:49:45'),(58,106,158,'<p>2 days ago - Umberto Michelucci</p>\r\n<p>Hi David,</p>\r\n<p>thanks for the welcome. Let me answer your questions in two parts. One about me and one about ideas. It will be easier to do it this way.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Quick background about me: I was born in Italy where I studied Physics. I love to learn about people so I studied Psychology and Higher Education at a University in UK to understand how people think and especially learn. I studied especially issues like problems of women in education, of disabled people and so on.</p>\r\n<p>I travelled extensively from Alaska to Nepal (where I have many dear friends) to Malaysia to see other cultures and understand other people. I climbed extensively around the world and I am an active Fireman (Volunteer) close to Z&uuml;rich (where I live). In addition, since I have many interests, four years ago I created an international mountain race (www.sardona-ultratrail.com) to help a valley in Switzerland to get more tourists.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Swiss mountain people are wonderful once you know them well...</p>\r\n<p>I have always felt a very strong need to do something about the problems in the world, to help people. I have always needed (and the need is even stronger now) to understand (in some way) suffering and tragedies. To understand violence, love, sadness, happiness, honour and so on. I feel that people, their history, and especially their feelings are what makes the world interesting and varied. I need to touch other cultures and ideologies to remind me that the world is not what I see everyday in Switzerland. There are many people who are less lucky than us, and I think is our duty to do something about it. We are the privileged ones. Even informing ourself and understanding what is going on is a first important step in the right direction. I learned that text is important and fundamental but images can really change the mind of people, they impress and leave a deeper mark than words. This is why I turned recently to Photojournalism and documentary photography. It would be an honour to be able to leave a mark with an image (or more) that I took. To know that, thanks to my work, the life of someone (even only one person) is now better. I believe that no change is too small.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>I have come to understand that telling a story about people is a way of participating in their experiences. If you understand them, if you are a part of their life (although for a short period of time), in a certain way you feel what they are experiencing, you are living it. It is indeed a marvellous possibility to greater understanding.</p>\r\n<p>I strongly believe that photojournalism in general can really make the people see what (often) they don\'t want to see. So it is a fundamental way to change the world. Is a way to help people. Is a way to let the world see what is really happening (like Journalism). But I don&rsquo;t think I have to tell you this. You know it way better than me.</p>\r\n<p>And this is why I signed for this course. I want to learn as much as I can about how to do it. What are the best methods, what is working and what is not. And, apart from shooting a lot, I think that suggestions from someone who is doing it, is probably the best way of learning.</p>\r\n<p>I hope it clarifies what I think and why I decided to take this course.</p>\r\n<p>Umberto</p>\r\n<p>PS I will post a second answer regarding ideas for projects. Give me some time to be able to write it.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-07 07:52:41','2015-05-07 07:52:41'),(59,106,158,'<p>2 days ago - Umberto Michelucci</p>\r\n<p>Hi David,</p>\r\n<p>I have a few ideas on possible projects but I actually not sure about feasibility for a course like this. Could I run them by you (at least a couple) and get your feedback? It would be very helpful.</p>\r\n<p>Thanks in advance,</p>\r\n<p>Umberto</p>',NULL,'2015-05-07 07:53:51','2015-05-07 07:53:51'),(60,52,158,'<p>1 day ago - David Bathgate</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Umberto,</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Thanks for the background information and description of the path that\'s led you to photography as a means of expression.&nbsp; You\'ve certainly had some interesting life experiences and perspectives on them, along the way. I think you\'ll find this course a solid \"stepping-stone\" to what you want to achieve - and again, I\'m looking forward to working with you.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>As for story possibilities, yes - please do describe what you have in mind and we can discuss their feasibility before beginning.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Cheers<br />David</p>',NULL,'2015-05-07 07:55:34','2015-05-07 07:55:34'),(61,106,158,'<p>1 day ago - Umberto Michelucci</p>\r\n<p>Hi David,</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>thanks for your message. I have an idea on a social theme, but I have the feeling is a bit too complex (for various aspects) for this course. I will outline three ideas that, in my opinion, are concrete enough for such a course.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>My main idea is to investigate and document the trafficking of women in Switzerland, and the work of FIZ (check&nbsp;http://fiz-info.ch/en/Home). My idea would be to follow one or two women that has had this terrible experience with the help of the FIZ center. I think they are doing a wonderful work. I am afraid that this is a complex subject and requires some time to do it properly (possibly more than 6-7 weeks we have at our disposal). I feel is a bit too much for this course, altough it would be an incredible interesting and important long term project. It may need quite some time to find women willing to participate and collaborate.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>My other two ideas would have a less social impact, but possibly more doable (I believe they are still interesting from a documentary point of view).</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Culture in the kitchen: I would like to see how kitchen in different restaurants are organized and how people work with food (in Swiss restaurants, Thai, Chinese, Italian, etc.). I would like to be able to let the viewers see the differences and how cultural and geographic origin will play a role in the relationship between chefs and food. So the idea would be to spend time in the kitchens of restaurants and try to immortalize in images life moments: stress of many orders, pauses, etc.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Life behind the scene in a zoo: I would follow the workers of the zoo (volunteers and paid staff) and try to immortalize what kind of work they are doing. What love it goes into such a job, what difficulties.<br />If I consider the four points you highlighted in your text I think the first two ideas fit more nicely, although I believe the first project is more a long term one that is difficult to fit in 6-7 weeks.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>I had also another idea but I believe it cannot be done in 6-7 weeks. I would like to follow a family with a disabled child (a theme that is very important to me) and show how difficult (or beautiful) life can be. But to find a family willing to collaborate is not so easy. This also may be a long term project that requires a high sensitivity, lot of preparation time, and possibly a bit more experience.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Here I would like to know your feedback. You have quite a lot of experience. What do you think?</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Thanks in advance, Umberto</p>',NULL,'2015-05-07 07:57:47','2015-05-07 07:57:47'),(62,106,158,'<p>1 day ago - Umberto Michelucci</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Hi David,</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>after some additional brainstorming I came up with other two ideas.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Life in a shopping mall: I think that it would be very interesting to document the different sides of life that you find in a big shopping mall. One can try to understand the questions of who/why/where/how of different people going there for different reasons. When is full of people, when is empty. Early in the morning when still empty, on weekends when is full. Parking places exceedingly full, long lines in shops, etc. Is an aspect of moder life that is becoming very frequent. Small shops are dying and big shopping mall are prospering (at least here in Switzerland). &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>I think it is a very interesting theme.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>What we waste: It is rather interesting how, especilally in Switzerland, people are wasting an incredible amount of food and different items. Things are thrown away when still new, since people have enough money to buy new ones. Food is wasted, clothes are wasted, electronic equipment are wasted. There is no end. So much could be achieved with all things that are wasted.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>It would of great importance to draw attention on what we waste, and how much we could do if we could pay more attention.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>What do you think? I will stop with ideas now. I think they are enough ;-)</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Thanks again for your time, Umberto</p>',NULL,'2015-05-07 08:00:29','2015-05-07 08:00:29'),(63,52,158,'<p>about 16 hours ago - David Bathgate</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Hi Umberto,</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Here are my thoughts on the story ideas you\'ve posted:</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>1)&nbsp; Trafficking of Women -</strong> Although working with / through an organization such as FIZ is a good \"in\" to such a story, I too think this would be more of a long-term project.&nbsp; It would require gaining the trust of a number of \"actors\" who could feel participation would bring them and family members into danger, should their visual stories be told. In short, definite social impact and storyline importance, but difficult to gain necessary access in such a short amout of time.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>2) Culture in the Kitchen -</strong> This could be an interesting story if approached in a novel and dynamic way.&nbsp; Let me say here though, that I mentored a photo student in a Moroccan kitchen during a worshop I led not long ago and the result wasn\'t all that exciting.&nbsp; If going this route, you might do better focusing on a particular ethnic restaurant catering to a Swiss clientele - covering everything from the purchase of ingredients, to preparation and finally serving in the dining area - the whole \"scene\" and the \"antics\" that may follow.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>3) Running a Zoo -</strong> I actually think this might be your best story choice.&nbsp; Most everyone is interested in animals and how well (or not) their occupants are cared for.&nbsp; You could offer the zoo director photos in exchange for spending time throughout days capturing \"behind the scenes\" images of the daily routine of zoo and animal care - everything from feeding to cleaning living areas to how the zoo vet treats ailing animals.&nbsp; I think such a story could result in very dynamic photography.&nbsp; Zoos are controversial, so I think such a story would have strong social value, as well.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>4) Family with Disabled Child -</strong> This story has been done quite a bit already.&nbsp; And although still interesting to a broad audience, the photographer needs to spend a lot of time around the family and in the home, something that can be \"annoying\" if an accepting family is not found.&nbsp; Even if one knows such a family personally, it will turn out to be a long-term project, whereby you are capturing images several at a time in the course of a number of family visits and accompaniments.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>5) Shopping Mall Life -</strong> This one would require a number of permissions from everyone in charge of the mall to patrons and customers you photograph close enough in to yield impactful photos, versus those captured from a distance with a long lens. Due to recent events involving terrorist acts and shopping malls in various locations around the world, there exists a great deal of \"suspicion\" surrounding people taking photos in such widely-visited venues.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>6) What the Swiss Throw Away -</strong> This could be a good story.&nbsp; Switzerland is seen as a wealthy society and an environmentally conscientious society. A broad audience would have interest in a story well done that shows just what the Swiss consider \"garbage.\"&nbsp; You would need to connect with and accompany waste collection units and follow them to where that waste is dumped and disposed of.&nbsp; Another contact would be Swiss companies that recycle and capture their operations.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>So in my opinion, the zoo story and the Swiss waste story would fit best the paramenters outlined in this first lesson. Plus I think a good story could be had from either situation in the time allotted for its completion.&nbsp; First step would be \"selling\" your project to \"key players\" in these arenas.&nbsp; Permissions and acceptance to be there are something photojournalists and documentary photographers spend the majority of their time on.&nbsp; Actually taking photos is a small slice of that \"pie.\"</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>I hope my commentary here helps.&nbsp; Feel free to discuss any of these points / issues further I you like before making your final story choice.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Cheers,<br />David</p>',NULL,'2015-05-07 08:04:11','2015-05-07 08:04:11'),(64,107,367,'<p>I have done with europe tour</p>',NULL,'2015-05-07 11:13:47','2015-05-07 11:13:47'),(65,107,361,'<p>good</p>',NULL,'2015-05-07 11:21:55','2015-05-07 11:21:55'),(66,106,158,'<h3>about 4 hours ago - Umberto Michelucci</h3>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Hi David, thanks for your feedback. I agree with you. I started pitching both ideas to see what kind of support I manage to get. I find actually both ideas appealing for very different reasons. But at the moment I prefer slightly the waste project, for its possible social impact that it may have (if done properly and in an innovative way that have some impact). I will let you know how my first requests go.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Cheers, Umberto<br /><br />PS For the assignment I will try to get some images/ideas from both projects if I can, to see what kind of images I could get.</p>',NULL,'2015-05-07 14:00:05','2015-05-07 14:00:05'),(67,107,360,'<p>&nbsp;hello instructor</p>',NULL,'2015-05-08 07:07:33','2015-05-08 07:07:33'),(68,110,441,'<p>good island assignment</p>',NULL,'2015-05-08 07:47:56','2015-05-08 07:47:56'),(69,65,470,'<p>This is Good Course</p>',NULL,'2015-05-08 09:41:10','2015-05-08 09:41:10'),(70,65,469,'<p>Good Assignment&nbsp;</p>',NULL,'2015-05-08 09:41:44','2015-05-08 09:41:44'),(71,65,469,'<p>You say Right ..........</p>',NULL,'2015-05-08 09:48:45','2015-05-08 09:48:45'),(72,110,485,'<p>Hello meeta good lesson for natue photography</p>',NULL,'2015-05-08 10:49:39','2015-05-08 10:49:39'),(73,111,429,'<p>Hi Meeta! Thanks for this, I will get started ASAP :) Whats the deadline?</p>\r\n<p>X</p>\r\n<p>Reef</p>',NULL,'2015-05-11 16:35:46','2015-05-11 16:35:46'),(74,70,429,'<p><strong>about 10 hours ago - Meeta Khurana-Wolff</strong></p>\r\n<p>You have a rough deadline of about 2 weeks for each lesson. See how you get along with it. I am ok if youneed more!</p>\r\n<p>Xo</p>',NULL,'2015-05-11 16:43:22','2015-05-11 16:43:22'),(75,111,429,'<p><strong>about 10 hours ago - Reef Fakhoury</strong></p>\r\n<p>that sounds great I\'m on it :) I\'ll come back to you if I have any questions<br />Hope all is well on your end!<br />x<br />Reef</p>',NULL,'2015-05-11 17:00:19','2015-05-11 17:00:19'),(76,106,158,'<p>Hi David,  a quick update.</p>\r\n<p>I started asking the two zoos close to here and the biggest recycling company in the Z&uuml;rich Area. The recycling area are going to invite me to discuss the project, but it will probably be in roughly 2 weeks (in Switzerland next week is only 3 days long, holiday...). One of the zoo told me they are not interested (or probably they don\'t want unwanted Photos), but I am still asking what is possible. I asked the second zoo and I am waiting for an answer.  </p>\r\n<p>So I think that also the waste is going to work, but it will take some time.</p>\r\n<p>  I thought that to avoid to waste too much course time I should find something that I can learn from, while waiting for the possibility of shooting the projects we discussed.  </p>\r\n<p>I learned that a Graffiti artist was going to paint a construction site in Z&uuml;rich and so I decided to go there and try to shoot the work, how is done, to document the process. I was there two times and I will be back next week. I am thinking of possibly asking the artist if I could follow him in his studio or in other places where he is working and document his work. I stopped and brought him coffee and talked with him, to learn what he does, how is working, etc. Is an interesing guy. The city paid him to pain the otherwise dull construction site walls on a bridge (roughly 200 m of wall).</p>\r\n<p>  It does not have a direct social impact but is something I can work on immediately. I have already some images that I could post and get your feedback. And the work is interesting to document. But I could use some help in deciding what kind of images one could shoot.</p>\r\n<p>  As soon as a possibility open for the other two projects I will start with them. I think is also ok if I don\'t really finish one of them (I guess they will go on for a bit longer than June to be able to capture the many aspects that will make it a good story, difficult to decide when a project is finished right?), but I am still decided to get as much as I can from this course.</p>\r\n<p>  I will continue to brainstorm and see if I can come up with ideas that could work in a short time frame and that would give me quickly access.  </p>\r\n<p>What do you think about the artist idea?  </p>\r\n<p>Cheers, Umberto </p>',NULL,'2015-05-11 18:18:23','2015-05-11 18:18:23'),(77,52,158,'<p>Hi Umberto,  </p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The scenarios sounds very familiar to me and my work.&nbsp; These are the kinds of situations and \"waiting games\" that all documentary photographers and photojournalists deal with on a regular basis.&nbsp; Frustrating to say the least.&nbsp; Thing to do, as you have discussed here, is to find something solid and interesting for the interim.&nbsp; And I think your street artist idea and situation is just that.&nbsp; Check out this <strong><a href=\"http://edition.cnn.com/videos/international/2014/12/11/spc-ones-to-watch-street-artists-a.cnn\">video link at CNN International</a></strong>.&nbsp; I\'d advise to go with this and do it in the most dynamic way you can.&nbsp; It can be a very visual and \"edgy\" kind of story that may just speak of \"social impact and meaning.\"  </p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Best of luck!  </p>\r\n<p>David</p>',NULL,'2015-05-11 18:23:25','2015-05-11 18:23:25'),(78,106,158,'<p>Hi David,</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>thanks for your comment. Don\'t worry, I don\'t give up so easily. I already contacted a second zoo and the director seemed interesting. The zoo is part of a circus, so I asked there too :-) In addition I will not give up on the waste story. It will simply take some time. As I told you I am a firemen and they collect the paper for recycling, so I may even start there. &nbsp;I will keep you posted on how it goes. I got an email from the second zoo, from the director today saying that it finds the idea very interesting and that it has forwarded the request to the head doctor there and that he will get in touch with me soon. And I asked again the first zoo again just to put them under a bit of pressure ;-) You never know...  Will keep you posted. I will look at your video and post some ideas soon so that you may get an idea of what I am doing.  </p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Cheers, Umberto</p>',NULL,'2015-05-11 18:25:26','2015-05-11 18:25:26'),(79,106,158,'<p><strong>about 22 hours ago </strong>- Umberto Michelucci  </p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Hi David, </p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>I have another quick question. Today I went to visit the zoo that seemed more willing to help as a normal visitor, and tried to see what I could get there. I found myself shooting trying to see the point of view of animals and trying to get images that would show something about the animal and their relationship with the zoo. Was an interesting experience how this evolved without really thinking about it. Do you want to see a couple of images? Or should we leave them for the next assignment maybe? I don\'t want to inundate you with images :-)</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>  Cheers, Umberto&nbsp;</p>',NULL,'2015-05-11 18:27:24','2015-05-11 18:27:24'),(80,52,158,'<p>Hi Umberto,</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>I think these would be good for using in the next lesson / assignment - \"Shooting in Other Cultures.\"&nbsp; Looking forward to seeing them then.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Best,<br />David</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 05:50:35','2015-05-12 05:50:35'),(81,106,158,'<p>Hi David, thanks. Will do that. Cheers, Umberto</p>',NULL,'2015-05-12 05:53:45','2015-05-12 05:53:45'),(82,70,249,'<h3>about 2 hours ago - Meeta Khurana-Wolff</h3>\r\n<p>Hi everyone! I just wanted to check up on you all and see if everything was OK! As I am not receiving many assignments and some have not started - I wanted to ask if I can assist with anything? Kindly let me know.</p>\r\n<p>Warmly,</p>\r\n<p>Meeta</p>',NULL,'2015-05-13 12:57:26','2015-05-13 12:57:26'),(83,100,253,'<p><strong>about 1 month ago - Nicky Weber</strong>  </p>\r\n<p>Thanks Meeta. &nbsp;Just returned from beautiful Jindabyne in the Snowy Mountains. &nbsp;Will catch up with the first three assignments by 19th April. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Regards  Nicky</p>',NULL,'2015-05-13 13:06:27','2015-05-13 13:06:27'),(84,70,253,'<p><strong>28 days ago - Meeta Khurana-Wolff</strong></p>\r\n<p>  That is perfectly fine Nicky!  I am off to Vienna tomorrow for my workshop (I will be with Jeanne by the way! She says hi and was totally flaberghasted LOL!) and will return Sunday evening. So I will be able to get to your assignment next week!  </p>\r\n<p>Warmly,&nbsp;  Meeta</p>',NULL,'2015-05-13 13:09:08','2015-05-13 13:09:08'),(85,112,497,'<p><strong>21 days ago - Suzette Nguyen</strong>   </p>\r\n<p>Hi David, just wanted to check in with you. I\'m doing my best to learn the concepts in this lesson but it\'s harder than I thought it would be even with re-reading everything you\'ve written several times. I even took my camera to SF but nothing turned out the way I had wanted, so I\'ll keep at it. Just wanted to let you know that I\'m still in class, and will hopefully, have some submissions to make very, very soon!</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 14:53:04','2015-05-21 14:53:04'),(86,52,497,'<p><strong>20 days ago - David Bathgate  </strong></p>\r\n<p>Hi Suzette,  This first lesson DOES include a learning curve, I admit.&nbsp; But - it is the basis of all that is \"digital photography\" and how your camera does it.&nbsp; Take you time with the concepts.&nbsp; Play around with them using your particular camera model and ask questions here as much and as often as you have them&nbsp; We can even arrange a Skype call (david.bathgate) to discuss it all in real time (camera in hand), if you like.&nbsp; Just let me know.</p>\r\n<p>  Best,  </p>\r\n<p>David</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 14:54:33','2015-05-21 14:54:33'),(87,112,497,'<p><strong>14 days ago - Suzette Nguyen</strong>   </p>\r\n<p>Thank you, David. I would love that! I\'m bringing my camera to the beach this weekend, so maybe we can arrange a Skype call sometime in the next following two week at your convenience?    </p>\r\n<p>Suzette</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 14:55:41','2015-05-21 14:55:41'),(88,52,497,'<p><strong>13 days ago - David Bathgate</strong>  </p>\r\n<p>Hi Suzette,&nbsp; This would be fine.&nbsp; I\'m in Germany through Wednesday of next week and in London from the 14th - 18th.&nbsp; So let\'s find a convenient time for the both of us, either through Wednesday or on Friday.&nbsp; Where are you located?  </p>\r\n<p>David</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 14:57:03','2015-05-21 14:57:03'),(89,112,497,'<p><strong>13 days ago - Suzette Nguyen</strong></p>\r\n<p>  I\'m in California. And do you mean the Wed/Fri you after you come back from London, so Fri. the 22nd? Or Fri., the 15th? Either one would work for me.</p>\r\n<p>  Suzette</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 14:58:27','2015-05-21 14:58:27'),(90,52,497,'<p><strong>12 days ago - David Bathgate</strong>  </p>\r\n<p>Let\'s try to talk before I leave on Wed.&nbsp; So anytime through Wed. will work for me - somewhere between 10 - 12 a.m. your time (7 - 9 pm here in Germany) would be convenient.&nbsp; Would this work for you?&nbsp; If so, pick a day and hour and we\'re set.</p>\r\n<p>  Also take note that TCI is moving to a new version of the website and developers are doing a lot of testing prior to this move.&nbsp; So if you receive email notifications, other than those pertaining to our own correspondences, don\'t be alarmed.&nbsp; It\'s all part of the pre-launch activity.&nbsp; Content is being moved from here to the new website so all will appear seamless once the change is complete.  </p>\r\n<p>David</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 15:00:47','2015-05-21 15:00:47'),(91,112,497,'<p><strong>10 days ago - Suzette Nguyen</strong>   </p>\r\n<p>Thank you, David! How about tomorrow at 11:00AM PST? I will add you on Skype tonight.&nbsp;  </p>\r\n<p>Suzette</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 15:02:10','2015-05-21 15:02:10'),(92,52,497,'<p><strong>10 days ago - David Bathgate  </strong></p>\r\n<p>Sounds good.&nbsp; Talk then ...</p>\r\n<p>  David</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 15:03:23','2015-05-21 15:03:23'),(93,52,504,'<h3>2 days ago - David Bathgate</h3>\r\n<p>Hello Charles,&nbsp; My sincere apologies for such a late \"Welcome to the Course.\"&nbsp; I received notice that you\'d signed on, but assumed it was the session starting on Monday the 18th.&nbsp; Anyway, let\'s get started!</p>\r\n<p>First of all I\'d appreciate learning a bit about your background as a photographer, the camera and lens you\'ll be using for this course, etc.&nbsp; And in the meantime too, let me know if you have any questions as we begin.&nbsp; Don\'t be concerned about deadlines due to my overlook of the start date.&nbsp; I\'m very flexible with assignment submissions.</p>\r\n<p>Again - my apologies.</p>\r\n<p>David</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 15:15:52','2015-05-21 15:15:52'),(94,114,249,'<p><strong>3 days ago - ashlee bixby</strong>  </p>\r\n<p>Thank you for an awesome start! &nbsp;I have a couple of questions... 1) how often do you use a slower shutter speed and tripod in your work with food and 2) what is your preferred method of setting white balance?</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 16:01:11','2015-05-21 16:01:11'),(95,70,249,'<p>3 days ago - Meeta Khurana-Wolff  </p>\r\n<p>Hello and a&nbsp;very warm welcome to you Ashlee. Hope you are well and ready to dive into the world of food photography and styling with me.&nbsp; Over the next couple of weeks we\'ll be spending intensive time with each other and I hope to guide you through the challenges and difficulties you have been having with your food photography. &nbsp;I am really looking forward to it as for now we are one-on-one in this session.</p>\r\n<p>  Please read through your lessons carefully ... do not be intimidated. If you have any questions along the way feel free to ask them in the discussion area.</p>\r\n<p>  I am also very interested in knowing what camera, equipment, lens etc. you both are using - do you use a tripod etc.? It will give me a better idea and also help me make suggestions if necessary.   </p>\r\n<p>When you complete your assignments and exercises please do give me as much detail about the image as you can. The technical details (f stops, ISO etc.) but also where the light was coming from, your workflow and process and any challenges you faced would help me get a better insight on the images you submit and your thought process.  </p>\r\n<p>So to answer your questions 1) A slow shutter speed in terms of food photography would be used in way a) when it\'s quite dark and we need to let more light into the camera or b) when we want to create a sense of motion for example wine being poured, while keeping everything else in focus.  </p>\r\n<p>Above the image of the pear would be the best example - I used a tripod and as it was shot at 5 PM in the winter I hardly had much light so as you can see the shutter was extremely slow at 1 sec, which I could not have taken without a tripod.</p>\r\n<p>  2) One cannot really have a \"preferred\" white balance setting as it depends on the situation / light you are in. If you are shooting in natural light it can change within a second (a few clouds move in front of the sun) - if you are shooting in artificial - controlled light you can use a set WB. So you need to view the current lighting situation and use that.  </p>\r\n<p>Having said that when I am shooting for myself / blog or when I am travelling I usually leave my WB to auto BUT only because I know my camera (Canon Mark III) handles WB extremely well when on auto and I do not have to change much in post-processing. However, when I am shooting for clients I custom my white balance (using a white or grey card) to my light situation always.   </p>\r\n<p>Enjoy yourself with lesson one and remember there are no dumb questions ... ask me whatever you are unsure of.   </p>\r\n<p>Warmly,  Meeta </p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 16:06:24','2015-05-21 16:06:24'),(96,114,249,'<p><strong>3 days ago - ashlee bixby</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>  Thank you Meeta! &nbsp;I am very excited to be here with you!!!  </p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>To answer your question, I am using a Mark III (Canon) with a variety of lenses. &nbsp;I am brand new to food photography, but have been taking pictures of in manual mode for a couple of years. &nbsp;I mostly use a 24-70mm zoom, but I have access to a wide variety of primes as well (ranging from 14mm to 300mm). &nbsp;I have a tripod and pull it out occassionally, but not often.&nbsp; I had asked if you use yours often because I may want to get a table top sized tripod for this class if we will be using one frequently.  </p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>I also have a flash and a couple of strobes with softboxes that I play with, but am just starting out with those. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>  I wanted to also ask you what lens (or lenses) &amp;/or focal lengths you use the most for your food photography?</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>  Thank you so much, I am so excited to get started!&nbsp;</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 16:10:49','2015-05-21 16:10:49'),(97,70,249,'<p><strong>2 days ago - Meeta Khurana-Wolff  </strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Hi there Ashlee! Looking forward to working with you too.  </p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>OK so you seem to be extremely well equipped :)  </p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>I do use my tripod almost always as it allows me to set up my camera to the angle, height etc. I want to and then have my hands free to fiddle around with my set up, which you will be doing a lot of. This way I do not have to keep adjusting the angle of my camera. I also use an wireless remote release.  </p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>I love my 25-70mm and my 85mm prime lens. It might seem an odd lens for food photography but I find not only does it take crystal clear images but it also has a nice focal length.  </p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Looking forward to your assignment. If you have any questions just let me know.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>  xo </p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 16:14:16','2015-05-21 16:14:16'),(98,114,249,'<p><strong>2 days ago - ashlee bixby  </strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Thank you Meeta! &nbsp;That is so interesting about the 85mm. &nbsp;I don\'t own that one, but my dad might, so I will check with him.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>    Are you using a wireless remote so you don\'t have to go back to the camera or are you using it bc you are using a slow shutter speed and trying to avoid potential camera shake when you press the shutter button? &nbsp;Also, do you shoot tethered?    </p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>And finally, which Tripod/what size tripod you use?</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>    Thank you again!  </p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Ashlee</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 16:17:51','2015-05-21 16:17:51'),(99,70,249,'<p><strong>1 day ago - Meeta Khurana-Wolff</strong><br />  </p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Hi there Ashlee,  </p>\r\n<p>Yes to both regarding the remote. It just makes it a lot easier and makes crisp sharp images! I do shoot tethered when shooting for clients so that I do not have to take 100000s of images but can pinpoint what modfications to the set-up I need to make.  </p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>I have a Manfrotto for most of my shots and a Bilora for travel as it is a bit lighter. But I love the Manfrotto.  </p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Looking forward to your work!  </p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>xo  </p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Meeta</p>',NULL,'2015-05-21 16:21:40','2015-05-21 16:21:40'),(100,113,504,'<p><strong>about 15 hours ago - charles berkeley</strong></p>\r\n<p>David, thank you for the welcome. &nbsp;I have been an amateur photographer since 2006, mainly getting out with the camera in my spare time on the weekends. &nbsp;I had you as an instructor when you were with Betterphoto.com and learned a lot from you back then. &nbsp;I didn\'t know that you had your own instructional website until fairly recently. &nbsp;I have a Nikon D700 with a couple of lenses, including a 50 mm 1.4, which I hardly ever use. &nbsp;I also bought a Fujifilm XT-1 about a year ago, which I am using more frequently if only because I don\'t like carrying the heavier Nikon camera around with me when I go to NYC, which is about an hour away from my home in central New Jersey by bus or train. &nbsp;I just purchased a Fujifilm 35 mm 1.4 lens for the Fujifilm camera body. &nbsp;I look forward to working with you throughout the class. &nbsp; Charles&nbsp;</p>',NULL,'2015-05-22 08:50:37','2015-05-22 08:50:37'),(101,52,504,'<p><strong>2 minutes ago - David Bathgate</strong></p>\r\n<p>Hi Charles,&nbsp; Very interesting with the Better Photo connection.&nbsp; Yes - TCI launched its first website version in Sept. of 2007.&nbsp; We are here now on version 2.0 and will be launching a brand new and function-richer website (development site preview: <a href=\"../../\">http://tci.ror-dev.com</a>) in just a few days.&nbsp; When the website transition is complete, all present courses will appear \"seamlessly,\" all course material will be available in Student Areas at once and students will have a full 60 days to complete a course - no \"deadlines\" except for this.&nbsp; Notice too that another well-known BP instructor is with us.&nbsp; Brenda Tharp is teaching a travel photography course.</p>\r\n<p>As for your Fuji XT-1 purchase, I think it an excellent one.&nbsp; I have been using Fuji X cameras exclusively for the past year and a half and have never looked back at my previous Canon system (all sold off now).&nbsp; And the Fujinon XF 35mm 1.4 is top-notch all the way.&nbsp; You\'ll really enjoy using it for this course.&nbsp; Do let me know if you have any questions about the entire \"X\" system, along the way.&nbsp; I\'m working with the Fuji Corp. here in Germany to promote its products and have had the opportunity to extensively use its products.</p>\r\n<p>David</p>',NULL,'2015-05-22 08:55:19','2015-05-22 08:55:19'),(102,111,431,'<p>&nbsp;Hi Meeta!</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Thanks so much for sending these through, I will start tomorrow with 1 recipe and shoot, as you requested, ingredient(s) separately, then prep, then final dish. I will go through the recipes tonight and see what I can kick off with. When we skpe in a couple of weeks we can go through the list more thoroughly and discuss. Shall we set and date and time for our call so we can both block our calendars?</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>X</p>\r\n<p>Reef</p>',NULL,'2015-05-24 17:44:15','2015-05-24 17:44:15');
