8:37:48',NULL,'2014-12-04 07:03:10','2014-12-04 08:37:49'),(91,29,'Photography speciality',NULL,'<p>This lesson will teach us about the specaility of the course.</p>',2,5,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2014-12-04 11:53:07','2014-12-04 11:53:07'),(92,1,'second lesson',NULL,'<p>second lesson</p>',12,2,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2014-12-10 08:38:43','2014-12-10 08:38:43'),(93,30,'Free Sample Lesson and Assignment',NULL,'<p>If you were to look through contact sheets of professional photographers - including the masters, you would see a abundance of mediocre shots, some toss-out-immediately pics and hopefully, one - possibly two - really strong photographs. Take another look at your own work and most likely you\'ll encounter a similar distribution - also with a couple of real \"keepers.\"&nbsp; So what makes the difference? What places the very strongest images - the most compelling photographs, shoulders above the rest?</p>\r\n<p>First thing to keep firmly in mind, is that there is no magic attached to becoming a good photographer.&nbsp; Most anyone can learn to use a camera and there are no \"Moments of Divine Revelation\" involved in any of it.&nbsp; Toddling over one\'s father\'s camera at the delicate age of six months and clicking a perfectly composed snap of the family dog, says nothing about who will be the next photographic great.&nbsp; Making compelling photographs comes from developing a sound foundation of camera skills and acquiring the knowledge of what works within the photographic frame and what does not.&nbsp; Beyond this lies the development of one\'s own vision - a personal and creative way of seeing and interpreting the world.&nbsp; This can only come from practice, experience and the supportive guidance of a knowledgeable mentor who has successfully traveled the photographic path, before you.</p>\r\n<p><strong>So here\'s what you need to know to start your journey:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>A photograph consists of two basic elements - foreground and background.&nbsp; </strong>\"Elementary,\" you say.&nbsp; Well listen, they don\'t just have to be there, they must work together, as well.&nbsp; What lies within the frame - what you see through your viewfinder - must add to a visual \"whole.\"&nbsp; Background must support in some way (can even be psychological) the subject of your composition and vise versa.&nbsp; If some element - even if it\'s on the very edge of your frame - doesn\'t fulfill its role in this respect, you need to find a way to get it out.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Get close and fill the frame.</strong>&nbsp; Those first-time snap-shots that placed uncle Jeff as a small element in the middle of a vast frame just don\'t cut it when it comes down to judging compelling photography.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>In the photograph below, shot at a brick factory in Nepal, I stood atop the mass of just-fired bricks to capture the action of workers involved in clearing the kiln.&nbsp; My subject is the man piling bricks atop his head, dust filtering into the air, signs of struggle on his face.&nbsp; The background?&nbsp; It\'s just what this image is about - nothing more, nothing less - <em>bricks and human toil</em>.&nbsp; Subject and background are composed to support one another.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment1}</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Great Light:</strong> You probably already know that early morning sun and that late in the day make for the most aesthetic and powerful images.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>I worked early in the morning for the shot above - 7 a.m. I think it was in the Kathmandu Valley.&nbsp; The air was clear and crisp.&nbsp; I remember the morning very well - the light, the sounds - the smells of smoke still filtering from the dying kiln fires.&nbsp; Oh! And two other important characteristics of this photo and all strong images include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Great Color:</strong> If you\'re working in color, limit the number and hues you\'re working with.&nbsp; \"Few\" and \"related\" are the keywords here.&nbsp; Keep the color contents of your image simple.&nbsp; No more than four closely-related colors make for the strongest photographs.&nbsp; If black and white is your choice, strive for a full range of tones, from pure white to stark black and as many grays as you can manage, in between.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Interesting Composition:</strong> Move uncle Jeff away from the center of frame unless he\'s sitting cross-legged and meditating.&nbsp; Center-frame brings \"tranquility\" and a static feel to your photo.&nbsp; For a touch of dynamism, place Jeff closer to one of the four corners of your viewfinder.&nbsp; \"Rule-of-Thirds\" is the guideline to follow, in most cases.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>I went the \"Rule-of-Thirds\" route in my brick factory photo, placing the subject (worker with bricks on head) near the lower left corner of the frame, with co-workers and \"work-to-be-done\" surrounding him, throughout the entire frame.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Sense of Moment:</strong>&nbsp; <em>Icing on the photographic cake</em> - capturing an action, nuance - something happening \"beyond the ordinary\" in your photograph, this is what \"<em>Moment</em>\" is about.&nbsp; You want to stir emotion in your viewers.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>I\'ve got two examples of capturing the <em>Moment</em> for you, below - one subtle, the second more dramatic.&nbsp; Both fill the bill of adding something \"noticeably other\" to the composition.&nbsp; The first photo below comes from Montalcino (Tuscany), Italy.&nbsp; It was made during lunch hours when streets of this sleepy hill-top village were all but empty - except for a lone figure of a Capuchin monk, making his way up a cobble-stone street.&nbsp; I stopped, set my camera\'s exposure, knew I wanted the old door on the left of the frame to \"balance\" the approaching figure, which I would position on the right side of my photo.&nbsp; When the monk approached a position that felt intuitively \"right,\" I made my photo.&nbsp; Ok, so what about the \"sense of moment\" bit?&nbsp; Subtle it may be, but that up-turned foot protruding from the monk\'s robes - propelling him forward up the long incline of a ancient, narrow street, is the element that brings dynamic to this picture.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment2}</p>\r\n<p>The next example is more \"in your face.\"&nbsp; This image was made recently during a political rally in Istanbul, Turkey.&nbsp; Long lens from the sidelines?&nbsp; Nope!&nbsp; I moved in front of the gathered crowd of onlookers with a wide-angle lens to frame this young social crusader and capture \"the moment\" of youthful energy this man expressed.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment3}</p>',14,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2014-12-11 08:50:57','2015-03-26 13:43:32'),(94,18,'lesson-study',NULL,'<p>lesson-study</p>',5,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2014-12-12 08:09:19','2014-12-12 08:09:19'),(95,32,'Mid dec lession',NULL,'',6,1,'Sunset.jpg','image/jpeg',71189,'2014-12-24 08:23:52',NULL,'2014-12-24 08:23:54','2014-12-24 08:23:54'),(96,33,'mountain',NULL,'<p>mountain</p>',5,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2014-12-30 07:47:24','2014-12-30 07:47:24'),(97,33,'second-mountain',NULL,'<p>second-mountain</p>',5,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2014-12-30 07:50:16','2014-12-30 07:50:16'),(98,34,'Using Shorter Lenses',NULL,'<p><strong><em>While lenses 50mm and longer are traditional choices for people shots, there\'s expressive power at the other end of the focal-length spectrum, as well.</em></strong></p>\r\n<p>Many of the first people photographs I ever took were made with a 50mm lens. From there, I moved in the telephoto direction like many a beginning photographer does. Those earliest stages of my work dealt with family and friends and shined with the signature-soft backgrounds characteristic of a 70-200 zoom, set to a wide aperture. Wide-angle lenses lay low on my priority list of equipment to buy. \"People-less\" landscapes weren&rsquo;t exactly my thing and I didn&rsquo;t shoot much in close-quarters back in those days either. It wasn&rsquo;t until years later that I purchased a 28mm prime to use for my first magazine assignment, just to feel \"professional,\" I guess. But at that point the tide had turned and \"wides\" had moved to a prominent position in my camera bag &ndash; especially when it came to photographing people in new and novel ways.</p>\r\n<p>To begin with, wide-angles are very \"social\" lenses. They move the photographer to come closer to people and to interact with them on a level that&rsquo;s just not possible with lenses of any other focal-length. And for me, it&rsquo;s that moving into \"personal space\" with a wide and relatively non-intrusive lens that can mark the difference between just a shot of a person and a feel for the personality behind the picture. Take the portrait presented below, for instance. I came across this man a few years ago in northern Afghanistan, near the historic site of Bamiyan, where a giant stone sculpture of Buddha once stood. What first struck me about this man was the air of \"dignity\" he radiated and the lines and folds of cloth that cloaked and guarded his face from the country&rsquo;s harsh sun. I shot from a few meters away at first and then moved nearer. The man didn&rsquo;t refuse and even connected with me on a somewhat personal level for those short moments; until I was able to frame the elements I wanted with my 35mm lens - my nearly \"standard\" lens at the time - squeeze the shutter and tell the story. I thanked the man, he smiled and we both went away content with the interaction.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment1}</p>\r\n<p>But there are even greater advantages accruing to lenses shorter than the one I used here. Expansive perspective and tremendous depth of field are among the characteristics increasingly available to photographers using lenses 28mm and beyond &ndash; traits at hand to create stunning people shots, along with the things they do.</p>\r\n<p>One direction to go with this, no matter which wide-angle lens you choose, is to fill the frame entirely with your subject. I did just this in following photo example.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment2}</p>\r\n<p>Awaiting a brilliant sunset, I walked a beach in the south of India several years ago. Looking over my shoulder, I noticed a group of young Muslim school girls with ice cream cones, following in my footsteps. When I stopped, they stopped &ndash; and giggled, so I decided to take photographic advantage of the situation and walked toward them. When we met, the girls immediately jockeyed for position before my lens. I played along, positioning my viewfinder&rsquo;s frame for the best composition. Reaching what I wanted, I closed the shutter. The \"energy\" that filled the frame at that moment was immense and wide-angle coverage gave it just the \"immediacy\" it required.</p>\r\n<p>A second approach to photographing people with a wide-angle lens is to choose your backgrounds well. All photographs consist of a \"subject\" and a \"background.\" Simple enough, but it shouldn&rsquo;t be just any old background if your picture is to cross the threshold separating \"snapshot\" from \"Photograph.\" That is, every element within your composition should, in one logical way or another, fit with every other element in the frame. Together, these elements should then support, in a logical manner, the main subject of the picture. If a background element doesn&rsquo;t do this, the photographer should move camera position to remove it. And if that&rsquo;s not possible, a wider aperture should be set to render the background \"unrecognizable,\" by one stop of light or more.</p>\r\n<p>But a wide-angle frame need not be restricted to a single subject and held to a single \"plane.\" Use the extensive dimensional qualities of wide-angle lenses to explore your human subject more fully, add context and \"environment\" to your expression and a \"psychological\" aspect to your subject&rsquo;s interpretation.</p>\r\n<p>Beginning with next photograph below, I&rsquo;ve tried to do just this. Here, I&rsquo;ve created an \"environmental portrait\" of this Turkish girl in the context of her Islamic school in Cologne, Germany. Using a wide-angle zoom set to 24mm and opened to f-stop 2.8, I made several photographs of this classroom scene from a few meters away. Receiving an affirmative nod from the teacher readying her lesson at the front of the room, I moved quietly closer to this young student seated in the first row. The girl&rsquo;s shyness kept her eyes on the Koran in front of her. I then lowered my perspective and stabilized my elbows on the table in front of her, composed my image to include classmates throughout the background and squeezed the shutter the moment she looked my way. It was the glance I was hoping for and the soft and thematically-fitting background I&rsquo;d planned. [Note: the closer you are to your sharply-focused-upon subject, the shallower the depth of field behind that subject will be. This holds true for lenses of any focal length, but is of particular interest for those seeking soft backgrounds while using wide-angles and their characteristically great DOF.]</p>\r\n<p>{attachment3}</p>\r\n<p>The next picture highlights yet another facet of people photography for which wide-angle lenses are uniquely suited &ndash; the juxtaposition of elements within the frame to express a particular emotion or feeling. This image was made in northern India. Walking through village streets one morning, I spotted this shopkeeper and movie advertisement on a wall, next door. The faces seemed similar, the eyes dark and haunting. I asked the man if he minded standing next to the poster for a photo and he agreed. But it took a wide-angle lens &ndash; in this case a 28mm &ndash; to bring him and the section of poster-board I wanted together, expressing the air of lurking psychological suspense I intended.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment4}</p>\r\n<p>But juxtapositions and relationships set up in wide-angle, people shots need not always be so \"literal.\" The photographer can often identify and incorporate elements of design that affect the look and feel of the message being sent. My next image is a case in point. Here I positioned a model near a window to fix a \"match\" between this simple, but graphic background and the woman positioned before it. Let me explain.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment5}</p>\r\n<p>Two sets of elements work together - and in counterpoint - to make this photograph effective. The first consists of the soft, sensuous folds and curves of hair and sweater that define the model. The second is brought by the hard diagonal lines drawn in shadow on the wall behind her. (Note: diagonal lines, whether visible or imagined, add visual tension and energy to compositions.) It is the like-direction tilt of the model&rsquo;s head that unifies the two &ndash; subject and background, adding visual interest to the frame. Develop an eye for design elements such as these and you&rsquo;ll bring greater strength to your wide-angle compositions with people, every time.</p>\r\n<p>Any discussion of wide-angle lenses and people photography must touch on the subject of \"distortion.\" Shoot head-on with a 35mm to 24mm lens and you&rsquo;ll see virtually no hint of it. Choose wider lenses or approach your subject from more acute angles and it will be noticeable in your pictures. Key to the phenomenon is to remain flexible, for creative advantages lie within. For instance, to make this last photo below, I sat on the front steps of a Buddhist monastery in Sikkim and pointed my 24mm lens upward to photograph this monk standing at the front doors. The effect is one of \"accentuation.\" The young man appears to \"tower\" in his devout role within Sikkimese society.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment6}</p>\r\n<p>Other instances exist too (e.g. the hands of a golfer on his club; the eye of a billiard player looking down the length of his cue stick, etc.) where e a bit &ndash; if not a lot &ndash; of distortion can further the photographer&rsquo;s interpretation of a person or group, raising people pictures from a wide-angle perspective, to a completely different level. Experiment and see!</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',7,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-12 09:06:14','2015-02-26 10:08:42'),(99,34,'Approaching Strangers',NULL,'<h6>Getting the photos you want from the people you don\'t yet know.</h6>\r\n<p>I&rsquo;m basically shy and introverted as far as personality types go. It was always a major anxiety issue whenever I had to get up and give a talk in school or &ndash; in adult life &ndash; to give a presentation to a room full of strangers. It&rsquo;s something I&rsquo;ve always struggled with and in some ways have finally conquered. But as with even some of the most seasoned professionals who regularly include people shots in their work, for me approaching strangers to take their picture is nearly every time a re-rallying of confidence kind of affair.</p>\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s perhaps, therefore, fortunate that a percentage of the photographs I capture as a professional are made &ldquo;by the side&rdquo; of someone I&rsquo;m working with. In some cases this is a writer who&rsquo;s drawing the attention of the subject. He or she directs the questioning and personal interaction and I&rsquo;m standing slightly out of the way and waiting for just the right expression, hand gesture &ndash; any sort of &ldquo;peak&rdquo; moment in the subject&rsquo;s body language to squeeze the shutter and further my picture story.</p>\r\n<p>In other cases, I&rsquo;m embedded with military personal in conflict zones where I&rsquo;m even more of an observer. Given certain stipulations, I&rsquo;m &ldquo;sanctioned&rdquo; to be there to photograph whatever incidents, action and situations occur. I follow soldiers as they do house searches, question villagers and hand out humanitarian aid. Again, all I have to worry about is &ldquo;getting the picture.&rdquo; I don&rsquo;t have to &ldquo;win anyone over,&rdquo; gain their confidence, establish rapport or engage them in any kind of conversation to get my shot. Excluding whatever risks lie around me, it&rsquo;s relatively unencumbered and easy stuff -&ndash; carte blanche to make the photos I want without having to really &ldquo;deal&rdquo; with the interpersonal \"management\" that lies between.</p>\r\n<p>Are these the kinds of people shots I would always like to make? No question, when a photographer knows his or her craft &ndash; can work fast and competently with the camera, some pretty stunning images can come from it. But these are out-of-the-ordinary situations. A photographer has rarely someone along to do all the &ldquo;people work&rdquo; that will bring these kinds of visual responses from the subject. If we want power and impact from the people images we make, we have to encourage it, learn and practice how to do it and go out and &ldquo;earn&rdquo; such shots for ourselves.</p>\r\n<p>Nearly all of the photographs I make have people in them. Those images that don&rsquo;t will have some tell-tale sign or impact of human presence in them somewhere, though. I&rsquo;ve always said that a good 95 percent of my work has more to do with &ldquo;social skills&rdquo; than it does with camera craft and I still hold to this. An ability to interact and get along with others - at all social and economic levels, as well as cross-culturally - is the greatest asset a people photographer can have.</p>\r\n<p>Can I offer tips and methods for approaching strangers with a camera that will not only land you a quick shot and you&rsquo;re out of there, but bring power and emotion to the photos you make? I can - and do it in a progressive way that stretches your comfort zone for getting in there and photographing people you do not yet know.</p>\r\n<p>We\'ll start with images like the first one below.&nbsp; This photo was made during a Catholic &ldquo;Youth Day&rdquo; rally held in the city of Cologne, Germany. The situation was one of joy, energy and celebration. Amid the &ldquo;brotherly&rdquo; feeling throughout the crowd, it was easy to get close and capture the types of people pictures that define such events best. Using a 24mm wide-angle lens brought me into contact with my enthusiastic subjects, making the connection between subject and photographer even more personal, emotional and &ldquo;intimate.\" Be on the look out for public festivals, fairs and events where people congregate. Then mingle among the festivities to capture exciting, close-in people photos in a relatively comfortable people-photography environment.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment1}</p>\r\n<p>A next step is to go &ldquo;one-on-one&rdquo; with your subject - but doing it in a way that the comfort zone you\'re presently in, is not over trodden. With the next two examples, I&rsquo;ll explain just what I mean.</p>\r\n<p>In contrast to the first example, the following second photograph raises the bar just a little in terms of challenge. Here the situation is not one where the photographer can simply &ldquo;party along&rdquo; to get the shot. The situation is one of daily life; the photographer is not involved, just an outside \"observer\" of the scene. My presence in this case is not marked by engagement with the subject. And although eye contact may exist, there\'s no personal \"relationship\" between subject and camera to say just \"who\" this subject or these people are.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment2}</p>\r\n<p>Photographed at riverside in the Bangladeshi capital, Dhaka, I wanted to capture the color and sheer numbers of people making this ferry crossing, throughout the day. However I chose a time of the day that suited my mission best - late afternoon when people were more relaxed in stride and the quality of light was at or near optimum. Then seeing this particular boat on approach, I positioned myself for its landing. Using a 28mm lens, I set my exposure using f11 to capture the great depth of field I wanted, pre-focused on a point on the ground several meters in front of me and waited for disembarkation of the group. When this beautifully dressed woman reached my pre-focus point, I clicked the shutter. The passengers walked around me and I was again on my way. Look for such places where interesting people shots lurk, observe and anticipate the action and then pre-set your camera and ready yourself for shots just like these.</p>\r\n<p>Exploring the streets of the Lebanese town of Moukhtara, a community dominated by the Druze cultural-religious group, I came across this friendly figure.&nbsp; The Lebanese guide accompanying me immediately struck up a conversation and I \"joined in\" with smiles and nods of my head at seemly appropriate moments.&nbsp; My camera was in plain view and eventually I nonchalantly took a shot here and there using a 28mm lens.&nbsp; Due to the fact that I was standing on a low wall above the subject, my camera angle placed me slightly higher than he, but I felt the novelty of this perspective added to the light nature of this man\'s demeanor.&nbsp; And although the background was simple and uncluttered, I used an aperture setting of f5 to soften it a little and bring greater definition to my subject.&nbsp; Compositionally, I placed my him \"rule-of-thirds\" near the bottom left corner of my viewfinder frame, allowing the man space to the right, to \"interact\" with.&nbsp; I also \"framed\" him within the borders of the doorway behind him, instead of completely ignoring this architectural feature and allowing the figure of the subject to overlap these strong background lines.&nbsp; Finding a \"moment\" to capture wasn\'t hard here.&nbsp; The man was so animated that all I had to do was squeeze the shutter button.&nbsp; He offered plently of them.&nbsp; As always, I focused sharply on the subject\'s closest eye to the camera to ensure that his entire face would appear in sharp focus to the viewer.<strong><br /></strong></p>\r\n<p>{attachment3}</p>\r\n<p>For this next photo example, I ventured &ldquo;inside&rdquo; to capture this photograph set in an Istanbul hair salon. How did I make it? I just walked inside, spotted this interesting looking stylist, held up my camera, smiled and the two smiled back in agreement. Shooting here with a 24mm lens, I set my camera&rsquo;s ISO to 200 and f5.6 to retain as much background clarity as the lighting situation in the shop would allow.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment4}</p>\r\n<p>The next two pictures were made in India. Both are environmental portraits and both involved establishment of rapport with the subject, before the picture was made. In the case of the first, I frequented this chai (tea) shop on numerous occasions before the owner-operator came to recognize and &ldquo;know&rdquo; me in any real way. Except for my minimal grasp of her language &ndash; Hindi &ndash; we communicated only through gestures when I ordered tea without sugar. She would always see me with a camera, but it wasn&rsquo;t until later visits that I set out to use it at all. When I did, there came no objection and I was granted (without words) freedom to photograph anything (including her) from any part of the tiny shop I wanted.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment5}</p>\r\n<p>{attachment6}</p>\r\n<p>For making the final photograph, I spent a couple hours talking with this man via his rudimentary English. Passing by his front door one morning, he greeted me with questions: Where did I come from, where was my family and what was I doing in a place like this? Once I satisfied his curiosity with detailed answers, I was invited for tea. The experience brought a fascinating interaction and powerful pictures besides. In this photo, my host &ndash; then in his mid-fifties &ndash; was telling of his life in this small, rural village. In the process, he took a picture from the wall behind him and proudly displayed \"the storyteller as a young man.\" I got down to a low camera position in order to shoot upwards and accentuate his figure against the spartan surroundings of his simple room. This is the resulting shot.</p>\r\n<p>Many a powerful people photograph begins when eye contact is made and rapport is built. Friendliness, respect and a competent camera style is the path to take when looking for that fleeting grin, raise of an eyebrow or rubbing of an eye that tells the camera - and the viewer - a whole lot more about what it is to be human. Begin your journey where you most feel comfortable, then strive to stretch your vision through true interaction with your subject. In the final product, it\'s all well worth it.</p>',18,2,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-12 09:07:14','2015-02-26 10:06:12'),(100,34,'Making the Best of Light and Perspective',NULL,'<h6>While lenses 50mm and longer are traditional choices for people shots, there\'s expressive power at the other end of the focal-length spectrum, too.</h6>\r\n<p>Many of the first people photographs I ever took were made with a 50mm lens. From there, I moved in the telephoto direction like many a beginning photographer does. Those earliest stages of my work dealt with family and friends and shined with the signature-soft backgrounds characteristic of a 70-200 zoom, set to a wide aperture. Wide-angle lenses lay low on my priority list of equipment to buy. \"People-less\" landscapes weren&rsquo;t exactly my thing and I didn&rsquo;t shoot much in close-quarters back in those days either. It wasn&rsquo;t until years later that I purchased a 28mm prime to use for my first magazine assignment, just to feel \"professional,\" I guess. But at that point the tide had turned and \"wides\" had moved to a prominent position in my camera bag &ndash; especially when it came to photographing people in new and novel ways.</p>\r\n<p>To begin with, wide-angles are very \"social\" lenses. They move the photographer to come closer to people and to interact with them on a level that&rsquo;s just not possible with lenses of any other focal-length. And for me, it&rsquo;s that moving into \"personal space\" with a wide and relatively non-intrusive lens that can mark the difference between just a shot of a person and a feel for the personality behind the picture. Take the portrait presented below, for instance. I came across this man a few years ago in northern Afghanistan, near the historic site of Bamiyan, where a giant stone sculpture of Buddha once stood. What first struck me about this man was the air of \"dignity\" he radiated and the lines and folds of cloth that cloaked and guarded his face from the country&rsquo;s harsh sun. I shot from a few meters away at first and then moved nearer. The man didn&rsquo;t refuse and even connected with me on a somewhat personal level for those short moments; until I was able to frame the elements I wanted with my 35mm lens - my nearly \"standard\" lens at the time - squeeze the shutter and tell the story. I thanked the man, he smiled and we both went away content with the interaction.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment1}</p>\r\n<p>But there are even greater advantages accruing to lenses shorter than the one I used here. Expansive perspective and tremendous depth of field are among the characteristics increasingly available to photographers using lenses 28mm and beyond &ndash; traits at hand to create stunning people shots, along with the things they do.</p>\r\n<p>One direction to go with this, no matter which wide-angle lens you choose, is to fill the frame entirely with your subject. I did just this in following photo example.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment2}</p>\r\n<p>Awaiting a brilliant sunset, I walked a beach in the south of India several years ago. Looking over my shoulder, I noticed a group of young Muslim school girls with ice cream cones, following in my footsteps. When I stopped, they stopped &ndash; and giggled, so I decided to take photographic advantage of the situation and walked toward them. When we met, the girls immediately jockeyed for position before my lens. I played along, positioning my viewfinder&rsquo;s frame for the best composition. Reaching what I wanted, I closed the shutter. The \"energy\" that filled the frame at that moment was immense and wide-angle coverage gave it just the \"immediacy\" it required.</p>\r\n<p>A second approach to photographing people with a wide-angle lens is to choose your backgrounds well. All photographs consist of a \"subject\" and a \"background.\" Simple enough, but it shouldn&rsquo;t be just any old background if your picture is to cross the threshold separating \"snapshot\" from \"Photograph.\" That is, every element within your composition should, in one logical way or another, fit with every other element in the frame. Together, these elements should then support, in a logical manner, the main subject of the picture. If a background element doesn&rsquo;t do this, the photographer should move camera position to remove it. And if that&rsquo;s not possible, a wider aperture should be set to render the background \"unrecognizable,\" by one stop of light or more.</p>\r\n<p>But a wide-angle frame need not be restricted to a single subject and held to a single \"plane.\" Use the extensive dimensional qualities of wide-angle lenses to explore your human subject more fully, add context and \"environment\" to your expression and a \"psychological\" aspect to your subject&rsquo;s interpretation.</p>\r\n<p>Beginning with next photograph below, I&rsquo;ve tried to do just this. Here, I&rsquo;ve created an \"environmental portrait\" of this Turkish girl in the context of her Islamic school in Cologne, Germany. Using a wide-angle zoom set to 24mm and opened to f-stop 2.8, I made several photographs of this classroom scene from a few meters away. Receiving an affirmative nod from the teacher readying her lesson at the front of the room, I moved quietly closer to this young student seated in the first row. The girl&rsquo;s shyness kept her eyes on the Koran in front of her. I then lowered my perspective and stabilized my elbows on the table in front of her, composed my image to include classmates throughout the background and squeezed the shutter the moment she looked my way. It was the glance I was hoping for and the soft and thematically-fitting background I&rsquo;d planned. [Note: the closer you are to your sharply-focused-upon subject, the shallower the depth of field behind that subject will be. This holds true for lenses of any focal length, but is of particular interest for those seeking soft backgrounds while using wide-angles and their characteristically great DOF.]</p>\r\n<p>{attachment3}</p>\r\n<p>The next picture highlights yet another facet of people photography for which wide-angle lenses are uniquely suited &ndash; the juxtaposition of elements within the frame to express a particular emotion or feeling. This image was made in northern India. Walking through village streets one morning, I spotted this shopkeeper and movie advertisement on a wall, next door. The faces seemed similar, the eyes dark and haunting. I asked the man if he minded standing next to the poster for a photo and he agreed. But it took a wide-angle lens &ndash; in this case a 28mm &ndash; to bring him and the section of poster-board I wanted together, expressing the air of lurking psychological suspense I intended.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment4}</p>\r\n<p>But juxtapositions and relationships set up in wide-angle, people shots need not always be so \"literal.\" The photographer can often identify and incorporate elements of design that affect the look and feel of the message being sent. My next image is a case in point. Here I positioned a model near a window to fix a \"match\" between this simple, but graphic background and the woman positioned before it. Let me explain.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment5}</p>\r\n<p>Two sets of elements work together - and in counterpoint - to make this photograph effective. The first consists of the soft, sensuous folds and curves of hair and sweater that define the model. The second is brought by the hard diagonal lines drawn in shadow on the wall behind her. (Note: diagonal lines, whether visible or imagined, add visual tension and energy to compositions.) It is the like-direction tilt of the model&rsquo;s head that unifies the two &ndash; subject and background, adding visual interest to the frame. Develop an eye for design elements such as these and you&rsquo;ll bring greater strength to your wide-angle compositions with people, every time.</p>\r\n<p>Any discussion of wide-angle lenses and people photography must touch on the subject of \"distortion.\" Shoot head-on with a 35mm to 24mm lens and you&rsquo;ll see virtually no hint of it. Choose wider lenses or approach your subject from more acute angles and it will be noticeable in your pictures. Key to the phenomenon is to remain flexible, for creative advantages lie within. For instance, to make this last photo below, I sat on the front steps of a Buddhist monastery in Sikkim and pointed my 24mm lens upward to photograph this monk standing at the front doors. The effect is one of \"accentuation.\" The young man appears to \"tower\" in his devout role within Sikkimese society.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment6}</p>\r\n<p>Other instances exist too (e.g. the hands of a golfer on his club; the eye of a billiard player looking down the length of his cue stick, etc.) where e a bit &ndash; if not a lot &ndash; of distortion can further the photographer&rsquo;s interpretation of a person or group, raising people pictures from a wide-angle perspective, to a completely different level. Experiment and see!</p>',18,3,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-12 09:08:21','2015-02-26 10:10:44'),(101,34,'Seeing Photos Within Photos',NULL,'<h6>Not seeing the forest for the trees can be a photographer\'s nightmare, too.</h6>\r\n<p>Every photographer has walked onto a scene overrun with people. The bigger the crowd and the more hustle-and-bustle there is - the more daunting a task it seems to get any kind of meaningful photographs from it all. There are several ways to approach such a situation. The first is to simply wander through the crowd, capturing images as they cross your path.</p>\r\n<p>In the first example below, I did just this one day while walking through a busy plaza in Nepal\'s over-crowed capital city of Kathmandu. Following the flow of pedestrian traffic one morning, I turned to catch this rickshaw driver standing high on his the pedals, in search of potential customers. Warm, early-morning sunlight was just beginning to wash into this part of the ancient city, resulting in a rich and pleasing mix of highlights and shadows. The young businessman\'s face was so positioned, that the spot-lit effect on it drew my attention and I stopped to build a composition in my viewfinder. I quickly looked around to see what else I might include in my wide-angle (i.e. 24mm) view that would \"play-off\" this main subject in an interesting way. High on a building in the background, I noticed a billboard with three faces, lit with the same nice light. The faces on the billboard struck a similar note to that of the rickshaw driver and the diagonal \"line\" that could be drawn between the two - lower left and upper right - brought visual tension and energy to the frame. I made the picture.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment1}</p>\r\n<p>The second way to capture meaningful images among crowds, is to find an inconspicuous spot where things seem to be happening and make your stand, capturing interesting faces and situations as they come to you. This was the approach I took in making the next photograph.&nbsp; Captured during a Tibetan Buddhist temple ceremony in Dharamsala, India, I positioned myself discretely near the front of a line where the devout were paying homage to a statue of Buddha. As each attendee approached, I evaluated his or her \"photo potential.\" One of my favorites, this capture of a mother guiding her child through the experience, derives from simply choosing an opportune camera position and waiting for just the right time - a private and intimate moment, in this case - to come along.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment2}</p>\r\n<p>A third strategy is much more proactive in its design, calling on the photographer to make a plan of just how he or she going to approach all that seeming chaos, dive in and come away with some powerful images of people to be found there. With usually not a lot of time to get the job done, this is my primary method and I\'ve rarely been disappointed with the results. Here\'s how I go about it.</p>\r\n<p>Such plans of action should ideally begin with a degree of preliminary research. Find out all you can about the event, scene or situation before you arrive. Gain a general idea of just what will take place, in which locations and why. This overview information will give you the best idea of how the situation will be laid out, where best to enter it from, where the best light for photographing people will be, etc. If it\'s a regularly-scheduled market or bazaar that you\'re interested in, go there without your camera a few times, if you can - take a look around, buy something from one of the local vendors and ask questions that only an insider like they could give you an answer to. Strike up those rapport-building conversations and use the contacts each time you return to further your photographic project.</p>\r\n<p>For preparation like this I had little time a couple of years ago when photographing in Lebanon. I was there for the so-called, \"Cedar Revolution,\" which drew massive numbers of demonstrators and supporters to the streets. With excitement and political fervor high, people photographs were everywhere. The question was only, where to begin to capture even a fraction of what this phenomenon was all about? I started from the top and worked my way downwards - literally, bringing focus to my people images by moving from the general to specific details within the crowds.</p>\r\n<p>I went into this situation with only one contact, a Lebanese colleague and friend who helped get where I wanted to go. The \"research\" I took with me stemmed from a summary internet brief of the situation - not as much information as I would have liked to have had, but it was a start, nevertheless.</p>\r\n<p>Taken from the roof of a multi-storied building, the following photo captures one demonstration situation which occurred just south of the Lebanese capital, Beirut. I wasn\'t along up there either. Many photographers had climbed the long stairway before me, positioning themselves near the unsecured edge of the roof to get shots like these. My friend held tight to the back of my jacket as I made my way also to the brink. I moved to just behind where a crowd supporter was waving the Lebanese flag. I made my photo with a wide-angle (again 24mm) to capture the hordes below and squeezed the shutter just as the flag swung - just so - into my viewfinder. Then, I stepped back with care and made my way to the stairs and back to the street.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment3}</p>\r\n<p>Reaching the ground, my colleague and I began photographing at the edge of the crowd. Here we found a contingent of college students from the American University in Beirut, who had stationed themselves for support of the event. The colors, of course, were brilliant and banners, placards and enthusiasm charged the situation with a captivating energy. I began to photograph, choosing the demonstrator placed as subject in the left of the frame of the photo example below. As with many such public events where participants are thoroughly engaged with the moment, making photographs - even close-in captures with wide-angle lenses - are fairly easy. People want to be noticed and to show others their support of the cause. It\'s a good opportunity to just go for it, and this is what I did here.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment4}</p>\r\n<p>After making this initial photograph, I took a few steps closer with the same lens to isolate / showcase this particularly enthusiastic participant, still further (photo below). I held him in the viewfinder and each time I saw a \"sense-of-moment\" expression or gesture about to happen, I readied my finger on the shutter button. Luckily too, the light cooperated for this series of people-specific shots. With the luck of a passing cloud bank that remained for a good ten minutes, I was able to work with the best of people-light - soft, even and with a degree of richness to, as well.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment5}</p>\r\n<p>The next phto below took my quest for isolated people details still further. Seeing another group of students coming my way, I scanned the crowd for anything \"telling.\" This time it was a Lebanese flag painted on the cheek of this young marcher. I walked beside the group for a short distance and when a spot opened up for me to move in, I did to capture this person and her national emblem before falling away.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment6}</p>\r\n<p>And there\'s yet another way to capture situations that seem beyond the reach of planning or even isolating images of particular individuals and the details they hold. This is to go the route of the creative. I went this direction to capture the next photograph shown below.&nbsp; Made during a candlelight march by Buddhist monks in India, I simply set my camera to aperture priority and selected a slow shutter speed of 1/15 sec. to expose this scene in natural, late afternoon light. As the procession passed, I squeezed the shutter as the monks streamed by. As for thinking \"composition,\" I looked over the group carefully upon approach to see just what was coming. I then made my decision as to who I wanted in the picture and where and then waited for it all to materialize in my viewfinder. This strategy and this capture, interpret well the mood and energy present at just that moment.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment7}</p>\r\n<p>Note of caution - When you are photographing in large and / or tight crowd situations, maintain awareness of who is around you at all times. You don\'t want to fall prey to pickpockets and you don\'t want to be injured by crowd momentum, either. I always take a moment here and there during my shooting to glance around, if only to let others see that I am conscious of what\'s going on to the sides and behind me. Having a friend along is a real asset, too. Then they can do the watching, leaving you free to concentrate - without worry - on the photos you want to make. If they\'re photographers, as well, the two of you can then switch roles and give the other a chance with the scene. Point is - just stay safe!</p>',17,4,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-12 09:09:07','2015-02-26 10:13:06'),(102,35,'Test Lessaon 1',NULL,'<p><strong><em>While lenses 50mm and longer are traditional choices for people shots, there\'s expressive power at the other end of the focal-length spectrum, as well.</em></strong></p>\r\n<p>Many of the first people photographs I ever took were made with a 50mm lens. From there, I moved in the telephoto direction like many a beginning photographer does. Those earliest stages of my work dealt with family and friends and shined with the signature-soft backgrounds characteristic of a 70-200 zoom, set to a wide aperture. Wide-angle lenses lay low on my priority list of equipment to buy. \"People-less\" landscapes weren&rsquo;t exactly my thing and I didn&rsquo;t shoot much in close-quarters back in those days either. It wasn&rsquo;t until years later that I purchased a 28mm prime to use for my first magazine assignment, just to feel \"professional,\" I guess. But at that point the tide had turned and \"wides\" had moved to a prominent position in my camera bag &ndash; especially when it came to photographing people in new and novel ways.</p>\r\nTo begin with, wide-angles are very \"social\" lenses. They move the photographer to come closer to people and to interact with them on a level that&rsquo;s just not possible with lenses of any other focal-length. And for me, it&rsquo;s that moving into \"personal space\" with a wide and relatively non-intrusive lens that can mark the difference between just a shot of a person and a feel for the personality behind the picture. Take the portrait presented below, for instance. I came across this man a few years ago in northern Afghanistan, near the historic site of Bamiyan, where a giant stone sculpture of Buddha once stood. What first struck me about this man was the air of \"dignity\" he radiated and the lines and folds of cloth that cloaked and guarded his face from the country&rsquo;s harsh sun. I shot from a few meters away at first and then moved nearer. The man didn&rsquo;t refuse and even connected with me on a somewhat personal level for those short moments; until I was able to frame the elements I wanted with my 35mm lens - my nearly \"standard\" lens at the time - squeeze the shutter and tell the story. I thanked the man, he smiled and we both went away content with the interaction.<br /><br /><br />\r\n<p>{attachment1}</p>\r\n<p>But there are even greater advantages accruing to lenses shorter than the one I used here. Expansive perspective and tremendous depth of field are among the characteristics increasingly available to photographers using lenses 28mm and beyond &ndash; traits at hand to create stunning people shots, along with the things they do.</p>\r\n<p>One direction to go with this, no matter which wide-angle lens you choose, is to fill the frame entirely with your subject. I did just this in following photo example.<br /><br /><br /></p>\r\n<p>{attachment2}</p>\r\n<p>Awaiting a brilliant sunset, I walked a beach in the south of India several years ago. Looking over my shoulder, I noticed a group of young Muslim school girls with ice cream cones, following in my footsteps. When I stopped, they stopped &ndash; and giggled, so I decided to take photographic advantage of the situation and walked toward them. When we met, the girls immediately jockeyed for position before my lens. I played along, positioning my viewfinder&rsquo;s frame for the best composition. Reaching what I wanted, I closed the shutter. The \"energy\" that filled the frame at that moment was immense and wide-angle coverage gave it just the \"immediacy\" it required.</p>\r\n<p>A second approach to photographing people with a wide-angle lens is to choose your backgrounds well. All photographs consist of a \"subject\" and a \"background.\" Simple enough, but it shouldn&rsquo;t be just any old background if your picture is to cross the threshold separating \"snapshot\" from \"Photograph.\" That is, every element within your composition should, in one logical way or another, fit with every other element in the frame. Together, these elements should then support, in a logical manner, the main subject of the picture. If a background element doesn&rsquo;t do this, the photographer should move camera position to remove it. And if that&rsquo;s not possible, a wider aperture should be set to render the background \"unrecognizable,\" by one stop of light or more.</p>\r\n<p>But a wide-angle frame need not be restricted to a single subject and held to a single \"plane.\" Use the extensive dimensional qualities of wide-angle lenses to explore your human subject more fully, add context and \"environment\" to your expression and a \"psychological\" aspect to your subject&rsquo;s interpretation.</p>\r\n<p>Beginning with next photograph below, I&rsquo;ve tried to do just this. Here, I&rsquo;ve created an \"environmental portrait\" of this Turkish girl in the context of her Islamic school in Cologne, Germany. Using a wide-angle zoom set to 24mm and opened to f-stop 2.8, I made several photographs of this classroom scene from a few meters away. Receiving an affirmative nod from the teacher readying her lesson at the front of the room, I moved quietly closer to this young student seated in the first row. The girl&rsquo;s shyness kept her eyes on the Koran in front of her. I then lowered my perspective and stabilized my elbows on the table in front of her, composed my image to include classmates throughout the background and squeezed the shutter the moment she looked my way. It was the glance I was hoping for and the soft and thematically-fitting background I&rsquo;d planned. [Note: the closer you are to your sharply-focused-upon subject, the shallower the depth of field behind that subject will be. This holds true for lenses of any focal length, but is of particular interest for those seeking soft backgrounds while using wide-angles and their characteristically great DOF.]</p>',5,2,'grid-image-6.jpg','image/jpeg',51351,'2015-02-05 06:37:18',NULL,'2015-01-22 09:34:50','2015-02-05 06:44:09'),(103,36,'Sample Lesson to Test complete flow',NULL,'',30,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-23 08:12:34','2015-01-23 08:12:34'),(104,39,'Historical places of india',NULL,'<span style=\"color: #666666; font-family: HelveticaNeue, \'Helvetica Neue\', Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 13px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: 18.5px; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; display: inline !important; float: none; background-color: #ffffff;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\"><strong>Varanasi Ghat</strong> :<br /><br /></span> Ghats in Varanasi are the most holiest places of the city situated along with the banks of </span><a style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; font-family: HelveticaNeue, \'Helvetica Neue\', Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 13px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; font-stretch: inherit; line-height: 18.5px; vertical-align: baseline; color: #ef7f2c; text-decoration: none; outline: 0px; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: norm