,0,4,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-05-08 10:01:29','2015-05-08 09:59:21','2015-05-08 10:01:29'),(239,77,'nature photography lesson',NULL,'<p><span style=\"color: #000000; font-family: \'Helvetica Neue\', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: 20px; orphans: auto; text-align: left; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 1; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; display: inline !important; float: none; background-color: #ffffff;\">Water is the driving force of all nature.</span><span style=\"box-sizing: border-box; color: #000000; font-family: \'Helvetica Neue\', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: 20px; orphans: auto; text-align: left; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 1; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;\"><br style=\"box-sizing: border-box;\" />Read more at http://www.brainyquote.com/quotes/topics/topic_nature.html#9wtl0EQr1sfi2W0z.99</span></p>',0,1,'nature2.jpg','image/jpeg',8302,'2015-05-08 10:01:16',NULL,'2015-05-08 10:01:16','2015-05-08 10:01:16'),(240,78,'Digital Camera Basics',NULL,'<p>First of all - welcome to the course.&nbsp; Good to have you aboard!&nbsp; Over the next four weeks we\'ll be covering a lot of ground as far as learning to use your digital slr camera is concerned.&nbsp; But the journey won\'t be solely \"technical.\"&nbsp; We\'ll cover the basics of digital camera craft and have fun throughout applying what\'s been learned.&nbsp; So let\'s get started!</p>\r\n<p>Cameras put to use photographing news events, taking family photos and snapping pics of family pets have changed over the years.&nbsp; From hobbyists to professionals, there\'s been a healthy market interest to push for cameras that are smaller, faster and better.&nbsp; Thus innovation in the camera market has been rapid.&nbsp; And if you\'re a true enthusiast of photography, you\'ll probably consider the camera you buy today to be obsolete in a matter of a few years.&nbsp; At least that\'s what camera manufacturers are banking on. The big manufacturers continue to develop new features to tempt photographers away from their current camera choice - and the competition is fierce.</p>\r\n<p>One innovation that stands out in the evolution of 35mm photography is the introduction of the <em>SLR</em>, or single-lens reflex camera.&nbsp; A mirror and prism were its key mechanisms.&nbsp; It worked in a way that the image seen through the viewfinder was more accurate than the one that would, in fact, be captured on film. This camera design was then, of course, followed by the <em>DSLR</em>, or digital single-lens reflex camera.&nbsp; The DSLR boasted the same technology, but recorded the image \"digitally\" on a \"sensor\" (below), rather than on film\'s chemical emulsion.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment1}</p>\r\n<p>Today, there\'s no shortage of \"digicams\" on the market.&nbsp; Interestingly, photo \"apps\" such as <em>Instagram</em> &mdash; sometimes said to glorify poor photography by adding an easy filter &mdash; have renewed people\'s interest in actually taking good pictures. The question then is, where to start?</p>\r\n<p>If you haven\'t used a DSLR before or just becoming acquainted with yours now, you may not be familiar with the technology that makes it different &mdash; what makes it the preferred camera for experienced photographers and amateurs, alike. Some components include the optical viewfinder and interchangeable lenses. Digital cameras in general utilize lots of interesting technology, but we\'ll focus on a few key pieces that make them different.</p>\r\n<p>Unlike an SLR, a DSLR will often have two viewfinders &mdash; a digital display (below) which is also used for menus or to view photos already taken, and the traditional optical viewfinder, which represents the main selling point of an SLR over cameras that came before it.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment2)</p>\r\n<p>{attachment3}</p>\r\n<p>In an SLR or DSLR, the optical viewfinder or eyepiece offers the most accurate optical preview so the photographer can be confident the photo is framed well and the lighting is correct before he or she snaps a shot. It\'s nearly the same as the image that is captured.&nbsp; So, when you line up the shot, the light enters through the lens (which is removable and interchangeable). Light is reflected twice before becoming what you see through the viewfinder. The first time it is reflected off the mirror, and the second time, it is reflected off a <em>pentaprism</em>. A pentaprism (see below) is used in the viewfinder to reflect an image at a right angle without reversing it. It has five sides to deviate a beam of light and is used in higher-end (\"prosumer\" and professional) DSLRs.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment4}</p>\r\n<p>When the picture is taken, the mirror moves, which causes the viewfinder to go black momentarily, so the light can shine directly onto the sensor that takes the picture (in an SLR, the light would have hit the film).</p>\r\n<p><strong>Pixels</strong></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #888888;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">\"Pixels\" are the \"grammatical\" building blocks of digital camera sensors.&nbsp;</span> <span style=\"color: #000000;\">\"Pixel\" is a contraction of the term <em><strong>PI</strong>cture <strong>EL</strong>ement</em>. Digital images are made up of small squares, just like a tile mosaic on your kitchen or bathroom wall. Though a digital photograph looks smooth and continuous just like a regular photograph, it\'s actually composed of millions of tiny squares as seen in the cut-out below.</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #888888;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">{attachment5}<strong><br /></strong></span></span></p>\r\n<p>Each pixel in the image has a numerical value of between 0 and 255 and is made up of three color channels - red, green and blue.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment6}</p>\r\n<p><strong>Megapixels &amp; Resolution</strong></p>\r\n<p>If there is one thing that the average camera user knows about, it\'s megapixel count. Loved by the beginner, the amount of pixels on a camera&rsquo;s sensor determines the amount of data that can be captured.</p>\r\n<p>So what do megapixels actually mean?&nbsp; Each &ldquo;megapixel&rdquo; is a million pixels capable of capturing bits of color that will result in an image. Let&rsquo;s take a example file (below) from a major camera brand, for example. The maximum resolution of a file produced by this particular camera\'s sensor is 4288 x 2848. On the long side of an image are 4,288 pixels, while the shorter side has 2,848 pixels. If we multiply 4288&times;2848, the resulting number is 12.2 million. So this particular dslr\'s megapixel count is 12.2 megapixels.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment7}<br /><br />While megapixels are a valuable measurement of a camera sensor&rsquo;s capabilities, more megapixels is not always better. One reason that camera companies have somewhat capped the number of megapixels that they will put into a sensor, is that more megapixels usually means higher levels of digital \"noise.\"&nbsp; In film terms, this equates with film \"grain.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>There is also a law of diminishing returns associated with the number of pixels on a sensor. Digital cameras have been able to produce large print sizes for years with 6 or fewer megapixels. This isn&rsquo;t going to change &ndash; any camera that you&rsquo;re going to buy today is now capable of producing large prints. However, before upgrading to that new 24-megapixel camera model, ask yourself what you will use that massive resolution for. While professionals may need huge amounts of resolution for their purposes (mainly to crop what they don\'t want from original captures), if you&rsquo;re just getting started with digital photography, it\'s best to not buy into the megapixel myth that \"more is more.\"</p>\r\n<p>Don&rsquo;t get me wrong, having the extra resolution for cropping is great. Just don&rsquo;t purchase one camera over another for megapixels alone.&nbsp; In conclusion, megapixels are a measure of only one of a digicam&rsquo;s capabilities.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Noise &amp; Sensor Sensitivity</strong></p>\r\n<p>A camera&rsquo;s &ldquo;ISO&rdquo; settings adjust the sensitivity of the sensor to light. In the film camera days, the ISO (earlier referred to as \"ASA\") was associated with the film you loaded in the camera and could not be changed. Digital sensors have the advantage of being adjustable from shot to shot, a great convenience when you\'re moving from outdoors to indoors and back.</p>\r\n<p>You may know that when you are in low light, you should consider bumping up the ISO to accommodate a usable shutter speed (too low a shutter speed - e.g. 1/15 sec and lower - you run greater risk of camera shake).&nbsp; A photographer friend once asked me why it\'s not beneficial to always set a high ISO, since doing so allows greater capture of light.&nbsp; Wouldn\'t this be the same as a super \"fast\" lens (ie. a lens capable of opening up to f2.0 or even f1.8) or a slower shutter speed (ie. allowing more time for light to hit the sensor / we\'ll talk more about \"exposure\" in the next lesson)?</p>\r\n<p>He had it correct in thinking that this was the case.&nbsp; In fact, raising the ISO does allow for more shutter speed or aperture flexibility - more room for exposure choice.&nbsp; However, this comes at a cost. High ISO settings allow for faster shutter speeds in low light, but introduce digital noise (\"grain\" in film terms) into the image.&nbsp; A camera&rsquo;s sensor works best at the lowest ISO setting (e.g. ISO 100 or 200).&nbsp; At these settings, you&rsquo;re going to see the best colors, lowest amount of noise and overall highest image quality.&nbsp; Low ISO settings produce the cleanest image but require lots of light - good clear and sunny skies outdoors and professional studio lighting indoors. Generally, you will want to use the lowest ISO setting that lighting conditions and your camera will allow.</p>\r\n<p>From sensor to sensor, ISO performance varies. One of the biggest strides in recent camera technology is the high ISO capability of modern cameras. So much so, that yesterday&rsquo;s ISO 400 is now matched in quality by today&rsquo;s ISO 800.&nbsp; The boundaries of low-light performance continue to be pushed to levels that were never before possible.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Sensor Size</strong></p>\r\n<p>Not all camera sensors are built equally. Each company uses their own technologies and specifications in building the latest sensors for their latest camera models. The specifications used have a great impact on the overall quality of the sensor and as a result, the images made with it.</p>\r\n<p>One of the major factors that determines image quality is the physical size of a sensor. This is why a DSLR is going to produce better images than almost any point-and-shoot camera.&nbsp; The size of the sensor in a pocket-sized camera is merely a fraction of its SLR counterpart.&nbsp; Typically, larger sensors will also perform better in high ISO situations &ndash; an effect that can certainly be witnessed when comparing point-and-shoots to even entry-level DSLR&rsquo;s.&nbsp; That is, images made at high ISO settings with a point-and-shoot will exhibit far more noise than those captured with even a low price range dslr camera.</p>\r\n<p>By now, you may have heard of an effect called a &ldquo;crop factor&rdquo;.&nbsp; This term describes the size of a camera sensor in relation to a &ldquo;standard&rdquo; size.&nbsp; What is this standard size? The reference point is a &ldquo;full frame&rdquo; sensor, meaning a sensor that is the same size as a 35mm frame of film. Any sensor that is smaller than a full-frame sensor is going to experience the \"crop factor.\"<br /><br />The box below represents the area that would be captured by a full-frame sensor, while the lesser areas represent a \"crop factor\" of that camera&rsquo;s field of view.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment8}</p>\r\n<p>You may know too that to crop an image is to use a selected portion of the image, or to basically select a smaller region of the image, thus cutting away captured pixels. On a crop-factor camera, you are getting a field of view that is tighter than that of a full frame sensor.&nbsp; Now in terms lenses, crop factors have an influence too.&nbsp; For example, Canon digital slrs (excluding their full-frame models) use a 1.5 crop factor sensor.&nbsp; This means if you have a 100mm lens attached, in 35mm (full-frame) terms, this lens effectively becomes a 150mm lens (100 x 1.5).</p>\r\n<p>There are sensors larger than 35mm &ldquo;full frame&rdquo; sizes, too.&nbsp; Digital \"medium format\" is a growing field that is favored by product and studio photographers.&nbsp; These photographers favor the massive resolution (80 megapixels) that is offered by manufacturers such as, \"Phase One.\"&nbsp; And now competitors such as Mamiya and Hasselblad are close on their heels with their own versions of massive megapixel models.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Take the Controls - Modes<br /></strong></p>\r\n<p>The majority of dslrs today place camera control in one dial or a combination of buttons.&nbsp; As seen in the drawing below, the photographer is presented with a range of options when it comes to using his or her digital camera.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment9}</p>\r\n<p>The exposure modes of a dslr let you control one setting while the camera automatically adjusts the others. In Shutter Priority mode (<strong>Tv</strong>), you to set the shutter speed while the camera sets the aperture/f-stop to produce a \"proper\" exposure. In Aperture Priority mode (<strong>Av</strong>), the photographer sets the aperture/f-stop while the camera sets the shutter speed. Manual mode (<strong>M</strong>) is fully under your control to set both aperture and shutter speed, allowing for both proper exposure and maximum creativity.&nbsp; Based on light level, fully automatic mode or \"Program\" (<strong>P</strong>) makes all the decisions for you at a squeeze of the shutter button.&nbsp; It\'s fast, but this mode setting affords the photographer little room for individual creative expression.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Aperture</strong></p>\r\n<p>Aperture, or \"f-stop\", refers to how big the hole will be for the light to pass through when the shutter is open and the picture is snapped (we\'ll talk more about this in Lesson #2).&nbsp; For now, just remember that lower f-numbers correspond with larger holes.&nbsp; And, the larger the f-number, the more things in front of and behind the subject will be in focus, but the more light you will need. The smaller the f-number, the more things in front of and behind the subject will be out of focus and the less light you will need.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Shutter speed</strong></p>\r\n<p>Shutter speed is how long the shutter needs to be open, allowing light into the camera, to properly expose the image. Fast shutter speeds allow you to &ldquo;freeze&rdquo; the action in a photo, but require lots of light. Slower shutter speeds allow for shooting with less light, but can cause motion blur in the image. The creative and expressive choice is yours.</p>\r\n<p>\"<strong>Light</strong>\" is the \"language\" of photography, be it film-based or digital.&nbsp; The basics are the same and the controls (i.e. aperture, shutter speed and ISO) are your means of creative expression with the camera.&nbsp; These and how they relate to \"exposure\" will be covered at length in Lesson #2.</p>',0,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-05-08 12:43:05','2015-05-08 12:43:05'),(241,78,'Exposure Explained',NULL,'<p>We touched on aspects of exposure at the end of the first lesson and we&rsquo;ll talk through it more fully in this one.&nbsp; So get ready to move your camera&rsquo;s mode dial or button away from that all-controlling &ldquo;P&rdquo; (Program) mode and on to more creative endeavors.&nbsp; We&rsquo;re going manual (&ldquo;M&rdquo;)! <br /><br />Exposure is one of the first - and one of the most confusing - concepts for newcomers to photography.&nbsp; All the numbers, settings, abbreviations and relationships can be quite daunting at first, but once they&rsquo;re mastered, you&rsquo;ll fully understand just what the other modes offered by your camera are doing for you when they\'re set.<br /><br /><strong>ISO</strong>, s<strong>hutter speed</strong> and a<strong>perture</strong> -&nbsp; these are the components of photographic exposure (diagram below) and the relationship between them is a dynamic one.&nbsp; That is, when one of these component settings is changed, the two others are affected, too.&nbsp; Together, the three work to create a properly exposed photograph.&nbsp; Let&rsquo;s run through this briefly again.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment1}<br /><br /><strong>ISO</strong> is a measurement of the digital camera sensor&rsquo;s sensitivity to light (with film, this equates to the chemical emulsion&rsquo;s sensitivity to light striking it).&nbsp; ISO commonly ranges from 100 to 1600, with many cameras going as low as 50 and as high as 6400 and more. An ISO rating of 100 is less sensitive to light than an ISO rating of 800. The former would be used in brightly-lit circumstances (sunny day with no clouds or indoors using studio lights) in order to prevent overexposure. The latter would be used in low-light conditions (cloudy day or indoors in low light) to prevent the photo from being underexposed.<br /><br /><strong>Shutter speed</strong> refers to the length of time the shutter remains open to expose the camera&rsquo;s sensor to light and create the image. Shutter speeds on most cameras range from 1/8000th of a second down to a full minute and more.&nbsp; In practice, you&rsquo;ll want to use a fast shutter speed in bright light to avoid overexposing your photo.&nbsp; Conversely, you should set a slow shutter speed in dim light to keep your picture from underexposing.&nbsp; Note here that a shutter speed of 1/30 sec. is about as low as you might want to go before camera shake starts to become an issue.<br /><br /><strong>Aperture</strong>, also referred to as &ldquo;f-stop&rdquo;, refers to the size of the lens opening when the picture is taken.&nbsp; Apertures range from f/1.8 (large opening) to f/22 (small opening).&nbsp; The larger the aperture, the more light is allowed into the camera to create the image. Some lenses offer an aperture of f/1.4 or even f/1.2, which allow even more light to reach the sensor when fully open.&nbsp; These lenses come at a higher price, however, both in terms of cost and weight.&nbsp; Such &ldquo;fast&rdquo; lenses, as they\'re often referred to, allow the photographer to capture images in much lower light situations.&nbsp; F-stop terminology can create confusion.&nbsp; Just keep in mind that a small number equals a large opening and a large f-stop number represents a small opening (diagram below).</p>\r\n<p>{attachment2}</p>\r\n<p><strong>Depth of Field</strong> is the distance in front and behind that which is sharply focused on, that appears also in focus.&nbsp; And this area is dependent on the f/stop (aperture) that has been set either by the photographer or by the camera via its program modes.</p>\r\n<p>At a low f/stop (large aperture, say f/2.8) there is very little depth of field, while a high f/stop (small aperture, say f/32) exhibits much more depth of field. This can be visualized easily by photographing a row of pencils, where that closest the camera is sharply focused on.&nbsp; At f/2.8 (very shallow depth of field), only the pencil closest to the camera is in sharp focus.&nbsp; Those farther away are out of focus, \"blurred\" or \"soft.\"&nbsp; As the f-stop number becomes higher, the diaphram of the lens becomes smaller and more of the pencil arrangement comes into sharper focus, until a very small aperture diaphram results at f/32 and all pencils from near to far appear in-focus and sharply so.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment3}</p>\r\n<p>In real world terms this means that you can control the amount of your subject that will be in focus by choosing different f/stops. When photographing flat objects (objects on a single plane with no visible 3-dimensional properties), the aperture setting is not critical, for if you have the camera back parallel to the subject it will all be in focus. When you photograph a 3-D object though, you must decide which plane of the object you wish to be in focus and how you want to use depth of field. You can decide to use a shallow depth of field (low f/stop,2.8) to highlight one plane of the subject (for example, a particular pencil mid-way down the line of pencils), while blurring or softening the rest. Conversely, you may decide to have as much of the subject as possible in focus by using a high f/stop like f/32, as we\'ve seen in the pencil example below.</p>\r\n<p>Remember though - if you have less light entering the camera (through a small aperture opening), the exposure time (via shutter speed setting) must be longer in order to get a proper exposure on the image sensor.&nbsp; That is, aperture and shutter speed work in opposite directions from one another.&nbsp; Once you have established a proper exposure using your camera\'s light meter (center of drawing below establishing a perfect exposure at f/5.6 and 1/200 sec.), a step-wise change in either aperture or shutter speed requires a change - in the same number of steps of the other - in the opposite direction.&nbsp; This means (for example) if you want to soften / blur the background behind your sharply-focused subject, you might open up your lens diaphram (aperture) completely to f1.8.&nbsp; This is in this diagram example, a 2-stop change in aperture.&nbsp; To maintain perfect exposure, you will need to increase shutter speed by two \"stops\" in the opposite direction (ie. 1/800 sec.).&nbsp; This will give you the exact same \"perfect\" exposure, but with a shallow depth of field.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment4}</p>\r\n<p>Let\'s now take an example where you want to blur a car passing in front of your lens.&nbsp; Your \"priority\" setting in this case would not be aperture, but instead your main consideration is shutter speed.&nbsp; To allow the car to blur at least mildly, you might choose a slower shutter speed of 1/100 sec.&nbsp; Being a 2-stop decrease in shutter speed from the original perfect exposure setting, you would need to increase aperture by 2-stops (i.e. f/8).</p>\r\n<p>On a sunny day, an ISO setting would allow you a full range of such reciprocals to choose from.&nbsp; As lightening conditions become darker, this range shrinks - choices of aperture and shutter speeds become fewer.&nbsp; The solution it to shift to the next higher ISO setting to maintain an acceptable range of settings to accomplish (in terms of depth of field, stopping and blurring action) just what you want to in your photo. As you can see, the combination of ISO, shutter speed, and aperture are all about controlling the amount of light that reaches the camera&rsquo;s sensor (or the film&rsquo;s emulsion surface).</p>\r\n<p><strong>Establishing Proper Exposure - Your Camera&rsquo;s Light Meter</strong><br /><br />In contrast to a hand-held meter that measures the amount of light falling on a scene, your in-camera light meter measures light reflected from the scene you are photographing.<br /><br />{attachment5}<br /><br />Your camera&rsquo;s light meter does have a &ldquo;standard&rdquo; to which it compares all light it reflectively measures.&nbsp; This standard is referred to as &ldquo;18 percent grey,&rdquo; a middle tone of grey (below) that equates to pointing your camera at grass, soil, your blue jeans, khaki-colored cloths or the back of your hand, in the same light as the scene you&rsquo;re about to photograph.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment6}<br /><br />Furthermore, your camera&rsquo;s reflective light meter is programmed to be very strict in applying it&rsquo;s middle and average tone of grey standard.&nbsp; This means that when you are photographing a scene or subject in evenly-distributed light of &ldquo;average&rdquo; reflectance throughout (example: a person sitting in the shade of a tree on a sunny day), the light meter will acknowledge the choice and the result will be a properly exposed photo.<br /><br /><strong>Light Meter Challenge - light background / dark subject</strong><br /><br />Fine, but what if the photo is to be of a dark object against a white background?&nbsp; Well, your camera&rsquo;s light meter mission is still to maintain a standard of &ldquo;middle grey,&rdquo;&nbsp; This means that your light meter will read the entire scene, see it being much brighter than 18 percent grey and reduce exposure to bring down the white area so it meets the middle grey standard.&nbsp; <strong>RESULT</strong>: Background properly exposed / subject underexposed (too dark).<br /><br /><strong>Light Meter Challenge - dark background / light subject</strong></p>\r\n<p>Let&rsquo;s look at the opposite situation - dark background and white or light-colored subject.&nbsp; Once again the camera&rsquo;s light meter will strive for middle-tone, 18 percent grey and an overall reading of the scene will be too dark.&nbsp; The camera light meter will strive to make the background lighter (18 percent grey), thus making the already light subject even lighter.&nbsp; <strong>RESULT:</strong> Background properly exposed / subject overexposed (too light).</p>\r\n<p><strong>In-Camera Reflective Light Meter Options </strong></p>\r\n<p>In order to accurately expose a greater range of subject lighting and reflectance combinations, most cameras feature several metering options. Each option works by assigning a weighting to different light regions; those with a higher weighting are considered more reliable, and thus contribute more to the final exposure calculation.&nbsp; In the diagram of meter types below, the whitest regions are those which contribute most towards the exposure calculation, whereas black areas are ignored.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment7}</p>\r\n<p>Partial and spot-metering give the photographer far more control over the exposure than any of the other settings, but this also means that these are more difficult to use &mdash; at least initially. They are useful when there is a relatively small object within your scene which you either need to be perfectly exposed, or know that it will provide the closest match to middle grey.</p>\r\n<p>One of the most common applications of partial metering is a portrait of someone who is backlit. Metering off of their face can help avoid making the subject look like an under-exposed silhouette against the bright background. On the other hand, care should be taken as the shade of a person\'s skin may lead to inaccurate exposure if it is far from neutral grey reflectance &mdash; but probably not as inaccurate as what would have been caused by the backlighting.</p>\r\n<p>Spot-metering is used less often because its metering area is very small and thus quite specific. This can be an advantage when you are unsure of your subject\'s reflectance and have a specially designed grey card (or other small object) to meter off of.</p>\r\n<p>More sophisticated algorithms may go beyond just a regional map and include: evaluative, zone and matrix metering. These are usually the default when your camera is set to auto exposure. Each generally works by dividing the image up into numerous sub-sections, where each section is then considered in terms of its relative location, light intensity or color. The location of the autofocus point and orientation of the camera (portrait vs. landscape) may also contribute to the calculation.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Exposure Compensation&nbsp; </strong></p>\r\n<p>Any of the above metering modes can use a feature called exposure compensation. The metering calculation still works as normal, except the final settings are then compensated by the exposure compensation value. This allows for manual corrections if you observe a metering mode to be consistently under or over-exposing. Most cameras allow up to 2 stops of exposure compensation; each stop of exposure compensation provides either a doubling or halving of light compared to what the metering mode would have done otherwise. A setting of zero means no compensation will be applied (default).</p>\r\n<p>Exposure compensation is ideal for correcting in-camera metering errors caused by the subject\'s reflectivity. No matter what metering mode is used, an in-camera light meter will always mistakenly under-expose a subject such as a white dove in a snowstorm.&nbsp; Photographs in the snow will always require around +1 exposure compensation (due to the light meter reading the brightness of the snow and then setting out to bring it down to 18 percent grey).&nbsp; Adding (compensating) one more stop of light puts the \"white back in the white.\"&nbsp; In low-key situations (e.g. a black dog against a black background) just the opposite is required.&nbsp; The camera\'s light meter tries to bring the dark scene up to middle (18 percent) grey and in so doing, leaves the scene \"muddy\" in appearance.&nbsp; Decreasing exposure (via the compensation dial or buttons on your camera) by one stop keeps the \"black in the black.\"</p>\r\n<p>The last thing I want to cover in this lesson - and it\'s an important one, is <strong>White Balance.&nbsp; </strong>In fact, White balance (<strong>WB</strong>) is considered as one of the most important settings of a digital camera. So as example, let\'s consider a scenario where you want to capture the beauty of sea waves hitting the shore with an overcast sky in the background. Sounds interesting? Well, if you don&rsquo;t use the correct white balance setting of your digital camera, you may get a picture with colors different from the actual ones you\'re seeing. Therefore, in order to produce a beautifully exposed image with true-to-life colors, you must learn to effectively use the white balance settings of your digital camera.</p>\r\n<p>To understand the concept of White Balance, you need to first understand the concept of color temperature. Color temperature is a characteristic of visible light. It provides a method of describing these characteristics and is measured in Kelvin (K). A light having higher color temperature will have more blue light or larger Kelvin value, as compared to lower light, which has a smaller Kelvin value. The following table shows the color temperature of various sources of light.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment8}</p>\r\n<p>A digital camera can measure the colors in the red, green, and blue light of the spectrum, as reflected to its sensors. In a photo taken under the midday sun there is the whole spectrum of light (which makes up &ldquo;white&rdquo; sunlight). Under these conditions, the colors in an image appear nearest to the &ldquo;true&rdquo; colors. An image taken under tungsten bulb (a normal household incandescent bulb) without adjusting the digital camera for white balance, produces a dull orange shade as it spreads the biased light. Similarly, an image taken under fluorescent lighting produces a brighter bluish cast. However, it is possible to shift the color in the desirable direction, provided you have a good understanding of your digital camera and its settings.</p>\r\n<p>White balance can be set manually.&nbsp; The process involves taking meter readings from a pure white card in the same light where shooting is to be done.&nbsp; This is laborious, since the photographer must do this each time lighting conditions change.&nbsp; Fortunately, digital cameras today have white balance <strong>presets</strong> that are icon-defined on a dial or in a screen menu of your camera (below).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>{attachment9}</p>\r\n<p>These are usually indicated as:</p>\r\n<p><strong>Auto</strong> &ndash; The Auto setting helps in adjusting the white balance automatically according to the different lighting conditions.<br /><br /><strong>Tungsten</strong> &ndash; This mode is used for lighting with regular light bulbs found in every home.&nbsp; The tungsten setting of the digital camera cools down the color temperature in photos.<br /><br /><strong>Fluorescent</strong> &ndash; This mode is used for getting brighter and warmer shots while compensating for the cool shade of fluorescent light.<br /><br /><strong>Daylight</strong> &ndash; This mode is for the normal daylight setting, while shooting outdoors. Many cameras do not have the Daylight mode.<br /><br /><strong>Cloudy</strong> &ndash; This mode is ideal for shooting on a cloudy day. This is because it warms up the subject and surroundings and allows you to capture better shots.<br /><br /><strong>Flash</strong> &ndash; The flash mode is required when there is inadequate lighting available. This mode helps pick the right White Balance under low light conditions.<br /><br /><strong>Shade</strong> &ndash; A shaded location generally produces cooler or bluer pictures, hence you need to warm up the surroundings while shooting shaded objects.</p>\r\n<p>Granted<strong> - </strong>we\'ve covered a lot here, but it should give you a solid knowledge of just how your digital camera works and \"thinks.\"&nbsp; With this know-how and the technical expertise of your digicam, you\'ll be equipped to express yourself freely and more confidently as a photographer<strong>.</strong></p>',0,2,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-05-08 12:44:12','2015-05-08 13:14:18'),(242,78,'Composition and Light',NULL,'<p>In photography - digital or film - it&rsquo;s not only what you photograph that matters, it&rsquo;s the way you photograph your subject, as well.&nbsp; A badly composed photograph can turn a great scene into a very dull one.&nbsp; At the same time, a well composed photo can make even the most ordinary of subjects come alive.</p>\r\n<p>When I was starting out in photography, I viewed composition as something obscure - almost akin to \"magic.\"&nbsp; I really had no idea where to start with this.&nbsp; But the more I worked with my photography, the more I came to realize that composition doesn&rsquo;t have to be complicated.&nbsp; There are all sorts of theories about how a photograph should be arranged and many of these so-called, \"rules,\" go clear back to early Greek times and their ideas of proportion, symmetry and the like.&nbsp; Truth is though, if you pay&nbsp;too much attention to strict formulas such as these, your photos will lose any kind&nbsp;of spontaneity and that does take the \"magic\" out of your work.</p>\r\n<p>In the real world, you&rsquo;ll be working with a&nbsp;wide range of scenes and subjects and&nbsp;this calls for a more open-minded approach to how elements within the frame should be presented. What works for one photograph, won&rsquo;t necessarily work for another.&nbsp; The key thing is to understand how all the decisions you make about composition can affect the way a picture looks and how people view and interpret the photographs you make.&nbsp; The way you frame a shot, choose a focal length of lens or position a subject within the frame, can make all the difference.</p>\r\n<p>One of the first pointers I did put to work when starting in photography is to avoid placing the subject smack-dab in the middle of the frame.&nbsp; It seems the natural thing to do when you\'re just beginning.&nbsp; The result though is a rather static and boring look to the photo.&nbsp; One of the ways to counteract this is to bring the so-called, \"Rule of Thirds,\" into play.&nbsp; The idea is to divide the scene (your viewfinder) into thirds, vertically and horizontally, as in the diagram below.&nbsp; One of the four intersections of imaginary lines is then is a good place to position your subject.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment1}</p>\r\n<p>Keep in mind that this is just a \"guideline.\"&nbsp; Fact is, it is too strictly adhered to much too often in photography.&nbsp; Perhaps a more casual variant of this guideline is to simply position your subject away from the center, as I\'ve done in the next shot made in a tropical Nairobi (Kenya).&nbsp; From here you can then get a \"feel\" for how it can be balanced with everything else in the scene.&nbsp; No rules or guidelines for achieving this balance either.&nbsp; The more you work with it, the quicker you simply develop an instinct for when something just looks right.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment2}</p>\r\n<p><strong>Keep it Simple - </strong>Simplicity is more times than not, key to a strong and pleasing photograph.&nbsp; Looking at a scene with the naked eye, your brain quickly zooms in on the main point of interest.&nbsp; In contrast, the camera goes through no such process, it captures everything in front of it.&nbsp; The result can be a messy, cluttered picture with no clear center of interest - no place for the viewer\'s eye to focus on, as in the backyard garden example that follows.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment3}</p>\r\n<p>What is needed is to choose a subject, then select a lens focal length or camera perspective that defines a center of attention within the frame, as I\'ve done with the next photo of brightly-colored flowers present in this garden scene.&nbsp; Distractions will often be present, but it\'s you job to keep them in the background as best you can or simply make them part of the story if their \"fit\" is in any way possible.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment4}</p>\r\n<p><strong>Fill the Frame -</strong> When you&rsquo;re shooting a large-scale scene it can be difficult to know just how large your subject should be within the frame.&nbsp; How much should you zoom in?&nbsp; Leaving too much empty space (\"negative space\") in your photo is something you don\'t want to do either.&nbsp; It makes your subject smaller than it needs to be and can also leave viewers confused about what they should be looking at.&nbsp; So you don\'t have problems with this, zoom in either with your lens or simply move closer to the subject when and where possible.&nbsp; Zooming in from a fixed camera position flattens the perspective of the shot and makes it easier to control or remove unwanted elements in the background.&nbsp; However, physically moving closer can result in a much more interesting picture, as with the shot below made of a group of school girls strolling on a beach in South India.&nbsp; I simply moved in close until the composition felt \"right\" and I was rewarded throughout the frame with these brilliant smiles.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment5}</p>\r\n<p><strong>Leading lines -</strong> A poorly composed photograph will leave your viewers unsure about where to look, and their attention might drift aimlessly around the scene without finding a clear focal point. However, you can use lines to control the way people&rsquo;s eyes move around the picture, taking them to a subject - a focal point in the distance.&nbsp; Converging lines give a strong&nbsp;sense of perspective and&nbsp;three-dimensional depth, drawing you into an image, as do the abandoned train tracks in the harbor area of Dusseldorf, Germany.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment6}</p>\r\n<p>Curved lines like that of the stream below can lead you on a&nbsp;journey around the frame, taking you towards the main subject, here being a foot-bridge in a village park.&nbsp; Lines exist everywhere, in the form of walls, fences, roads, buildings and telephone wires. They can also be implied, perhaps by the direction in which an off-centre subject is&nbsp;looking.&nbsp; When photos contain a strong line, it&rsquo;s almost impossible for your eye not to follow it.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment7}<br /><br /><strong>Use diagonals -</strong> Horizontal lines lend a static,&nbsp;calm feel to a picture, while vertical ones&nbsp;often suggest permanence and stability. To introduce a feeling of drama, movement or uncertainty, look for diagonal lines to create a strong sense of movement and force.</p>\r\n<p>Often all it takes is a change of camera position or focal length to get them.&nbsp; Wider angles of view tend to introduce diagonal lines due to the increased perspective.&nbsp; By using wide angle lenses, you\'re much more likely to tilt the camera up or down to fit more of the scene into the frame and this automatically creates diagonals.&nbsp; Diagonal lines can also be created artificially, by simply tilting the camera before squeezing the shutter button, as I have done from a low camera angle in my capture of a performing artist in the Old City of Fez, Morocco, below.&nbsp; This technique can be very effective, but photographers should be alerted to use it carefully and sparingly.&nbsp; Intentional camera tilt doesn\'t fit to every shot you make.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment8}</p>\r\n<p>Diagonal lines don\'t need to be tangible, either.&nbsp; They can be imagined, as in the next photo showing a girl looking down with pride at her baby sister next to her on the sofa.&nbsp; This line-of-sight, too, represents a diagonal line adding dynamism to this picture.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment9}</p>\r\n<p><strong>Space to move -</strong> Even though photographs themselves are static, they can still convey a strong sense of movement.&nbsp; When we look at pictures, we&nbsp;see what&rsquo;s happening and tend to look&nbsp;ahead &ndash; this creates a feeling of imbalance or unease if your subject has nowhere to move except out of the frame, as with the Italian monk below.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment10}</p>\r\n<p>Your compositions will be much more effective if you leave space for the action to move \"into,\" as I\'ve done with this young girl running on a beach in Kerala, India.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment11}</p>\r\n<p>This effect doesn\'t just apply to moving subjects, either.&nbsp; For example, when you look at a portrait you tend to follow someone&rsquo;s gaze and they too need an area to&nbsp;look \"into.\"&nbsp; Compare the two photographs below, for example, second of which lends a more stable \"feel.\"&nbsp; With the subject looking out of the frame, the feel is one of \"on edge\" and discomfort - and this is the point.&nbsp; Don\'t misunderstand this difference, though.&nbsp; Both have there effect - their place in photography.&nbsp; I just depends on the message the photographer wants to send to the viewer.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment12}</p>\r\n<p>{attachment13}</p>\r\n<p><strong>Backgrounds -</strong> Don&rsquo;t just concentrate on your&nbsp;subject &ndash; look at what&rsquo;s happening in the background, too. This ties in with <em>simplifying the scene</em> and <em>filling the frame</em>. You can&rsquo;t usually exclude the background completely, of course, but you can control it.&nbsp; You&rsquo;ll often find that changing your position is enough to replace an unwanted background that nicely complements your subject.&nbsp; Or&nbsp;you can use a wide lens aperture and&nbsp;a&nbsp;longer focal length to soften the background, by throwing it completely out of focus, as in the photo of a majestic Afghan hound standing on a beach, below.&nbsp; Using this technique not only \"nullifies\" the background, it places added emphasis on a sharply in-focus subject at the same time.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment14}</p>\r\n<p><strong>Creative with colours -</strong> Bright primary colors really attract the eye, especially when they&rsquo;re contrasted with a complementary hue.&nbsp; Complementary colors are those that lie opposite each other on the color wheel. Orange and blue, for example, are complimentary colors, as are red and green and yellow and violet. Such color combinations add contrast and visual excitement to the photographic frame.&nbsp; And scenes consisting almost entirely of a single hue can be very effective, as well.&nbsp; Take for example the walls and stairs of orange in a New Delhi, India park presented below.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment15}</p>\r\n<p>The key to color is to be really selective about how you isolate and frame your subjects to exclude unwanted colours.&nbsp; Simplicity reins supreme in this arena, also.&nbsp; Two or three colors of related hue deliver the strongest color photographs.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Breaking the rules -</strong> In summary, photo composition is a little like a visual language &ndash; you can use it to make your pictures communicate a specific message.&nbsp; However, just as we sometimes use the written word to create a deliberately surprising effect, we&nbsp;can do the same with photos by breaking with standard composition conventions.<br />Doing&nbsp;it by&nbsp;accident doesn&rsquo;t count, though! It&rsquo;s&nbsp;when you understand the rules of composition and then break them on purpose that things start to get interesting.&nbsp; It&rsquo;s often best to break one rule at time and look closely at the results.</p>\r\n<p>Just&nbsp;remember: for every rule we suggest, somewhere out there is&nbsp;a great picture that proves you can disregard it and still produce a&nbsp;fantastic image!</p>\r\n<p><strong>Light - </strong>Photography is all about light and without any kind of it, you&rsquo;d not be very successful with making a photograph.&nbsp; Understanding how to use light, manipulate it and incorporate it into the photos you capture is the most important aspect of photography that you&rsquo;ll learn. Once you understand light and how it affects your pictures, you&rsquo;ll be way ahead of most beginning photographers.</p>\r\n<p>Part of learning about lighting is getting the hang of the three main different angles: front light, side light, and back light.&nbsp; As with most photo scenarios, the subject matter you choose is important.&nbsp; Front-, side- and back-lighting a person for a portrait takes a different thought process than it does for landscapes,fine art or commercial photography. No matter what your subject is though, master lighting and you&rsquo;ll be on your way to becoming a pro.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Front Light - </strong>Front light is the easiest illumination angle you&rsquo;ll work as a photographer.&nbsp; Results are the most predictable when light is striking subjects straight on.&nbsp; It is also the least dramatic type of light you\'ll photograph your subjects in.&nbsp; More times than not you\'ll get good results with front lighting.&nbsp; And as in the casual portrait below, colors are at their brightest and there are fewer shadows to deal with than other types of lighting.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment16}</p>\r\n<p>Down-side to using front lighting is that it makes subjects appear flat, which can result in boring photos.&nbsp; Thus creativity is at its lowest when front lighting is brought into play.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Side Light - </strong>If you want to explore the creative, dramatic side of photography, side lighting is the way to do it.&nbsp; Side lighting visually defines the subject from its background.&nbsp; Thus it&rsquo;s the perfect light for emphasizing texture, defining depth, and bringing out patterns. For these reasons, both nature and landscape photographers regularly put side lighting to use for its limited palette of harmonious shades and soft lighting effect.&nbsp; Take for example the following photo made amid the mountainous landscape of Ladakh in northern India.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment17}</p>\r\n<p>When you side light a subject, its texture pops. And side lighting is more effective with portraits because it helps you emphasize the emotion and depth of your subject in a more dramatic way, such as the image of this woman below, looking out of a window.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment18}</p>\r\n<p>Down sides to side-lit subjects are few.&nbsp; One being that too much contrast in a photo can be unflattering.&nbsp; In these cases, the use of a reflector to bounce in additional light or the use of \"fill flash\" can be put to work to reduce any contrast that\'s present.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Back Light - </strong>Back lighting is one of the most popular lighting options for creating drama. Back light is when the sun or other light source comes from behind your subject - which means you&rsquo;re shooting into the light.&nbsp; Back light is undoubtedly the trickiest to use, but when it\'s used properly, the results can be stunning.</p>\r\n<p>The most popular backlit images tend to be people in nature like the sailor below, out on the water on a sunny afternoon.&nbsp; Nature scenes too are likely subjects for back lighting effect, as with this group of ferns in a forest, that follows.&nbsp; And just as with side lighting, backlit images emphasize contrasting depth in the scene, as well.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment19}</p>\r\n<p>{attachment20}</p>\r\n<p>So there you have it, the \"building blocks\" of all types of photography.&nbsp; Learn compositional rules and guidelines, apply them where they fit and once you\'ve mastered them, boldly break them to express your own creativity and style.&nbsp; But don\'t forget the light.&nbsp; It\'s rules don\'t change.&nbsp; Practice shooting at different times of the day and use direction of light to your best advantage - to express who you are as a photographer.</p>',0,3,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-05-08 12:45:10','2015-05-08 13:17:07'),(243,78,'From Snapshots to Photographs',NULL,'<p>Lessons 1 through 3 have given you a pretty good idea (including practice) of what photography and digital photography in particular, is all about.&nbsp; We&rsquo;ve looked at camera controls and functions, discussed how elements are arranged within the frame and how to light them.&nbsp; Now it\'s time to put together this information and skills and take some fantastic digital photographs of your own.</p>\r\n<p>Before we start though, let\'s make a distinction between two very different categories of photographic capture - between so-called, \"snapshots\" and \"photographs.\"&nbsp; The distinction may seem trivial, but as you grow as a photographer, you\'ll see that the difference is significant and you\'ll know when you\'re making one or the other.</p>\r\n<p>Wikipedia defines a \"snapshot\" as \"a photograph that is \"shot\" spontaneously and quickly, most often without artistic or journalistic intent. Snapshots are commonly considered to be technically \"imperfect\" or amateurish&mdash;out of focus or poorly framed or composed. Common snapshot subjects include the events of everyday life, such as birthday parties and other celebrations, sunsets, children playing, group photos, pets, tourist attractions and the like.\"</p>\r\n<p>OK - I agree in part, but subjects here can be equally stunning and meaningful when shot as \"photographs.\"&nbsp; I also agree that snapshots tend to be quick and \"rough\" captures aimed primarily at being a \"document\" of a scene or event.&nbsp; In contrast, a \"photograph\" is a well thought through capture of a scene or event that is pleasantly and effectively composed, exposed and intended to be a form of art.</p>\r\n<p>Now - taking this rather academic description of the two into account, let\'s put them both into practice with some examples.&nbsp; And let\'s start with an everyday garden scene, captured as a snapshot in the image below.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment1}</p>\r\n<p>Given what we\'ve covered to date, an analysis of this images reveals no real \"subject,\" other than the whole scene itself.&nbsp; There\'s no photographer-defined element for the viewer\'s eyes to settle on.&nbsp; The image contains nice colors, but when you notice the lighting situation, it\'s very \"contrasty,\" meaning that both very strong light and deep shadows exist in the frame.&nbsp; Make a note here that it\'s always best to stay with one type of light or the other - all full sunlight or all \"open shade\" conditions (low-key, yet warm and filtered sunlight), as exist in the shade of the tree in this frame.</p>\r\n<p>In the next frame you\'ll notice a transformation starting to occur.&nbsp; A few steps closer and a \"subject\" begins to be defined in the form of the tree and the birdhouse that hangs from its trunk.&nbsp; Notice too the position of the tree.&nbsp; It\'s not positioned dead-center, but slightly off-center making for a more pleasing composition.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment2}</p>\r\n<p>Enter the third of this garden series (below).&nbsp; Here the photographer has moved even closer to clearly define the subject of this composition to be the birdhouse itself.&nbsp; But not only proximity suggests this, the house is positioned roughly rule-of-thirds within the frame, possesses sharp focus and a wide aperture setting has been used to soften the background and place even greater emphasis on the intended subject.&nbsp; Snapshot?&nbsp; Photograph?&nbsp; This three-photo example should make it clear that starting with an undefined pull-up-and-shoot \"document\" of a garden scene, the photographer has used light, compositional guidelines and essential elements to capture a \"photograph\" that is pleasing to look at in terms of its design.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment3}</p>\r\n<p>The next two examples take this process to the next level.&nbsp; The first of two images below is already in \"photograph\" form.&nbsp; \"Subject\" of this composition lies on the left of the frame in the form of the songbook held by the conductor of this about-to-perform group of singers and musicians.&nbsp; What ties subject and background together here is the songbook repeatedly present throughout the frame.&nbsp; The fact that both subject and background appear in sharp focus (great depth of field created by a large f-stop number / small aperture opening) visually indicates that they are strongly related.&nbsp; To have done otherwise (ie. soft, out-of-focus background / small f-stop number / large aperture opening) would have weakened this relationship, placing greater emphasis on the sharply-in-focus man and songbook.&nbsp; Notice too that the entire scene is evenly lit by \"open shade\" type of lighting, the best for people pictures, since it creates no harsh shadows on faces.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment4}</p>\r\n<p>Second of these two photographs offers an even tighter (closer) view of this scene and a somewhat different photograph entirely.&nbsp; Subject?&nbsp; Well, it\'s noticeably the foreground girl on the right.&nbsp; And as we discussed earlier, her looking not inward, but out of the frame creates a feeling of \"tension,\" as if she is waiting and watching for the group\'s call to perform.&nbsp; Nice even light prevails and the mix of faces and songbooks keeps the eye circling through the composition.&nbsp; Thus moving closer to the scene in this situation has delivered a different message - and somewhat different feel to the photograph.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment5}</p>\r\n<p>The next pair of images were captured digitally in the recreational boat harbor area of Dusseldorf, Germany, a location of trendy restaurants, shops and - art work.&nbsp; And the first of the two pictures below focuses on a part of this.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment6}</p>\r\n<p>Which of those compositional elements and strategies we\'ve already discussed can be identified here?&nbsp; The first can be that the frame is filled - filled with these Gumby-like figures scaling this building.&nbsp; Can a \"subject\" readily be identified?&nbsp; Take a look throughout the frame which consists of a repetition (in different colors) of similar forms and you\'ll note that the somewhat larger red one near the bottom right of the frame stand out.&nbsp; It stands out due to its relative size, but also because of its rule-of-thirds compositional placement.&nbsp; This photograph possesses a dynamism in how it has been composed.&nbsp; And use of a wide-angle lens to make it creates (automatically) those diagonal lines, discussed earlier, that add to its energetic impact.</p>\r\n<p>The second harbor photograph the follows takes its strength from the bold diagonal line of the foot-bridge, cutting across the frame.&nbsp; There\'s high-contrast afternoon sunlight illuminating this scene, which casts strong shadows associated with pedestrians making their way.&nbsp; The combination adds another dimension to the photo.&nbsp; But can you identify a \"subject\" amid all this - something or someone for the eyes to focus on, to come to rest on?&nbsp; Well it\'s the couple with the baby stroller, entering from the lower right corner of the frame (rule of thirds), with plenty of room to move \"into.\"&nbsp; An added element to the energy that exists in this photo is the lifted feet in motion of this couple, which adds a sense of \"moment\" to this photograph.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment7}</p>\r\n<p>Still another way to bring defining attention to a subject, is to silhouette it.&nbsp; Giving the subject more room in front (to walk \"into\") than behind, I did just this in Italian town not long ago (photo below).&nbsp; How did I do it?&nbsp; I made an exposure reading from the brightest part of the scene (the background wall), set this exposure using a shutter speed fast enough (1/250 sec) to stop the action, underexposed by one stop by adjusting my camera\'s exposure compensation dial, focused sharply on the ground where I would capture the subject and when she reached that point, I squeezed the shutter button.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment8}</p>\r\n<p>Appropriately framing an intended subject is yet another means of showcasing it within a composition.&nbsp; Not any \"frame\" will do, however.&nbsp; It needs to be thematically fitting to the subject it surrounds or partially borders.&nbsp; Take for example the two images below, the first of which was made of a sailing vessel through the rigging of the sailboard in which I was riding.&nbsp; The second photograph was made on a summer\'s day in Kazakhstan, of boys diving from a bridge into the refreshing water of a local lake.&nbsp; The photo was captured on a digital camera using a 24mm wide-angle lens to include both a background swimmer already in the water and the partial appendages of one poised to make the leap.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment9}</p>\r\n<p>{attachment10}</p>\r\n<p>The final photo example incorporates both of these techniques to showcase the subject.&nbsp; A statue of a couple locked in romantic embrace - the scene bordered by nature-esque tree branches - was silhouetted by locking in exposure from the brightest area of sky in the scene, decreasing exposure (underexposing) by one stop using the camera\'s exposure compensation control, focusing sharply on the statue and then squeezing the shutter button to make the digital capture.</p>\r\n<p>{attachment11}</p>\r\n<p>Thus are some of the ways to use both your digital camera\'s controls, combined with a working and creative knowledge of composition, to create photographs that communicate to the viewer and express precisely how you see and feel about the world around you.&nbsp; And the best advice one can give and receive - put it all into practice just as often as you can!</p>',0,4,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-05-08 12:46:25','2015-05-08 13:28:42');
